{"title_page": "O-Six", "text_new": "'''0-Six''' (2006 \u20132012), also known as '''832F''', was a female [[gray wolf]], whose death by hunting just outside the protected area of [[Yellowstone National Park]] stirred debate about the hunting and protection of wolves in Wyoming, Montana and Idaho. The bestselling book ''American Wolf'' focused on O-Six's life and on conservation policies in the Yellowstone region.\n\n==Life==\nO-Six was for several years the mother of the Lamar Canyon [[Pack (canine)|pack]] in [[Yellowstone National Park]]. Born in 2006 in the Agate Creek pack,<ref name=\"blakeslee45\">{{cite book |last1=Blakeslee |first1=Nate |title=American Wolf |date=2017 |publisher=Crown |isbn=978-1-101-90279-0 |page=45}}</ref> she was principally known by the year of her birth.<ref>Blakeslee, p. 65</ref> She was a member of the fourth generation of wolves born in Yellowstone after the 1995 reintroduction of wolves to the park.<ref>Blakeslee, pp. 12, 14</ref> Leaving her birth pack, she established the Lamar Canyon pack as a three-year-old in 2010. The pack's territory in the easily-accessible [[Lamar River]] valley allowed tourists and wolf researchers to observe the wolves extensively. O-Six was one of the most visible and photographed wolves in Yellowstone, and was described a \"rock star.\"<ref>Blakeslee, p. 238</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Schweber |first1=Nate |title=\u2018Famous\u2019 Wolf Is Killed Outside Yellowstone |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/science/earth/famous-wolf-is-killed-outside-yellowstone.html?ref=nateschweber |publisher=New York Times |date=December 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter several years, O-Six was captured, fitted with a radio tracking collar and released, gaining the collar number 832F.<ref>Blakeslee, p. 139</ref> She produced three litters before the Lamar pack was dispersed by another wolf pack. Wandering into new territory, the remaining pack members, including O-Six, left the park, where no hunting is allowed, and appeared on private land to the east, near Crandall, Wyoming, during Wyoming's 2012 wolf hunting season. The allowed take in that season was eight wolves. She was shot by a hunter on November 6, 2012, the eighth wolf to be legally killed in Wyoming in 2012.<ref>Blakeslee, p. 7, pp. 229-233</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe death of O-Six was immediately reported in the ''New York Times'', leading to extensive coverage of O-Six and wolf-hunting policies surrounding Yellowstone.<ref>Blakeslee, pp. 236-239</ref><ref name=\"ng1\">{{cite news |last1=Ng |first1=Christina |title=Yellowstone's 'Famous' Alpha Wolf Shot and Killed |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/yellowstones-famous-alpha-female-wolf-shot-killed-hunter/story?id=17925005 |accessdate=23 January 2020 |publisher=ABC News |date=December 10, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"hull1\">{{cite web |last1=Hull |first1=Jeff |title=The Death of 832F, Yellowstone's Most Famous Wolf |url=https://www.outsideonline.com/1913831/out-bounds-death-832f-yellowstones-most-famous-wolf |website=Outside Online |accessdate=23 January 2020 |ref=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"williams1\">{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Matt |title=Yellowstone's popular alpha female wolf shot dead by hunters outside park |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/dec/09/yellowstone-female-wolf-dead-hunters |accessdate=23 January 2020 |agency=The Guardian |date=December 10, 2012}}</ref> Following the publication of the bestselling book ''American Wolf'' by Nate Blakeslee in 2017, which focused on O-Six's life, O-Six received additional media coverage<ref name=\"worrall1\">{{cite news |last1=Worrall |first1=Simon |title=The 'Most Famous Wolf in the World' Lived Hard\u2014and Died Tragically |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/news/2017/11/american-wolf-nate-blakeslee-yellowstone-hunting/ |accessdate=23 January 2020 |publisher=National Geographic |date=November 11, 2017}}</ref>, and was the subject of a ''National Geographic'' documentary.<ref>Blakeslee, p.239</ref> More coverage followed the shooting of O-Six's daughter [[926F (Spitfire)|926F]] in Montana in 2018.<ref name=\"robbins1\">{{cite news |last1=Robbins |first1=Jim |title=A Famous Alpha Wolf\u2019s Daughter, Spitfire, Is Killed by a Hunter |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/30/science/wolf-spitfire-killed.html |accessdate=23 January 2020 |publisher=New York Times |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"horton1\">{{cite news |last1=Horton |first1=Alex |title=A hunter killed a legendary Yellowstone wolf. Years later, her cub died the same way. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2018/12/02/hunter-killed-legendary-yellowstone-wolf-years-later-her-daughter-died-same-way/ |accessdate=23 January 2020 |publisher=Washington Post |date=December 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of wolves in Yellowstone]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2006 animal births]]\n[[Category:2012 animal deaths]]\n[[Category:Wolves in the United States]]\n[[Category:Individual wolves]]\n", "text_old": "'''0-Six''' (2006 \u20132012), also known as '''832F''', was a female [[gray wolf]], whose death by hunting just outside the protected area of [[Yellowstone National Park]] stirred debate about the hunting and protection of wolves in Wyoming, Montana and Idaho. The bestselling book ''American Wolf'' focused on O-Six's life and on conservation policies in the Yellowstone region.\n\n==Life==\nO-Six was for several years the alpha female of the Lamar Canyon [[Pack (canine)|pack]] in [[Yellowstone National Park]]. Born in 2006 in the Agate Creek pack,<ref name=\"blakeslee45\">{{cite book |last1=Blakeslee |first1=Nate |title=American Wolf |date=2017 |publisher=Crown |isbn=978-1-101-90279-0 |page=45}}</ref> she was principally known by the year of her birth.<ref>Blakeslee, p. 65</ref> She was a member of the fourth generation of wolves born in Yellowstone after the 1995 reintroduction of wolves to the park.<ref>Blakeslee, pp. 12, 14</ref> Leaving her birth pack, she established the Lamar Canyon pack as a three-year-old in 2010. The pack's territory in the easily-accessible [[Lamar River]] valley allowed tourists and wolf researchers to observe the wolves extensively. As [[Alpha (ethology)|alpha female]], O-Six was one of the most visible and photographed wolves in Yellowstone, and was described a \"rock star.\"<ref>Blakeslee, p. 238</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Schweber |first1=Nate |title=\u2018Famous\u2019 Wolf Is Killed Outside Yellowstone |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/science/earth/famous-wolf-is-killed-outside-yellowstone.html?ref=nateschweber |publisher=New York Times |date=December 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter several years, O-Six was captured, fitted with a radio tracking collar and released, gaining the collar number 832F.<ref>Blakeslee, p. 139</ref> She produced three litters before the Lamar pack was dispersed by another wolf pack. Wandering into new territory, the remaining pack members, including O-Six, left the park, where no hunting is allowed, and appeared on private land to the east, near Crandall, Wyoming, during Wyoming's 2012 wolf hunting season. The allowed take in that season was eight wolves. She was shot by a hunter on November 6, 2012, the eighth wolf to be legally killed in Wyoming in 2012.<ref>Blakeslee, p. 7, pp. 229-233</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe death of O-Six was immediately reported in the ''New York Times'', leading to extensive coverage of O-Six and wolf-hunting policies surrounding Yellowstone.<ref>Blakeslee, pp. 236-239</ref><ref name=\"ng1\">{{cite news |last1=Ng |first1=Christina |title=Yellowstone's 'Famous' Alpha Wolf Shot and Killed |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/yellowstones-famous-alpha-female-wolf-shot-killed-hunter/story?id=17925005 |accessdate=23 January 2020 |publisher=ABC News |date=December 10, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"hull1\">{{cite web |last1=Hull |first1=Jeff |title=The Death of 832F, Yellowstone's Most Famous Wolf |url=https://www.outsideonline.com/1913831/out-bounds-death-832f-yellowstones-most-famous-wolf |website=Outside Online |accessdate=23 January 2020 |ref=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"williams1\">{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Matt |title=Yellowstone's popular alpha female wolf shot dead by hunters outside park |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/dec/09/yellowstone-female-wolf-dead-hunters |accessdate=23 January 2020 |agency=The Guardian |date=December 10, 2012}}</ref> Following the publication of the bestselling book ''American Wolf'' by Nate Blakeslee in 2017, which focused on O-Six's life, O-Six received additional media coverage<ref name=\"worrall1\">{{cite news |last1=Worrall |first1=Simon |title=The 'Most Famous Wolf in the World' Lived Hard\u2014and Died Tragically |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/news/2017/11/american-wolf-nate-blakeslee-yellowstone-hunting/ |accessdate=23 January 2020 |publisher=National Geographic |date=November 11, 2017}}</ref>, and was the subject of a ''National Geographic'' documentary.<ref>Blakeslee, p.239</ref> More coverage followed the shooting of O-Six's daughter [[926F (Spitfire)|926F]] in Montana in 2018.<ref name=\"robbins1\">{{cite news |last1=Robbins |first1=Jim |title=A Famous Alpha Wolf\u2019s Daughter, Spitfire, Is Killed by a Hunter |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/30/science/wolf-spitfire-killed.html |accessdate=23 January 2020 |publisher=New York Times |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"horton1\">{{cite news |last1=Horton |first1=Alex |title=A hunter killed a legendary Yellowstone wolf. Years later, her cub died the same way. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2018/12/02/hunter-killed-legendary-yellowstone-wolf-years-later-her-daughter-died-same-way/ |accessdate=23 January 2020 |publisher=Washington Post |date=December 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of wolves in Yellowstone]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2006 animal births]]\n[[Category:2012 animal deaths]]\n[[Category:Wolves in the United States]]\n[[Category:Individual wolves]]\n", "name_user": "Adamd22", "label": "safe", "comment": "the concept of alpha-female is a misnomer, she was mother of the pack", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/O-Six"}
{"title_page": "Lauder Greenway family", "text_new": "{{short description|Scottish-American clan}}\n{{Infobox family\n|name             = '''Lauder Greenway Family'''\n|region           = [[New York City]]<br>[[Greenwich, Connecticut]]<br>[[Washington, D.C.]]\n|origin  = [[Scotland]]\n|heirlooms        =\n|estate           = [[Lauder Greenway Estate]]\n|members          = [[George Lauder, Sr.]]<br>[[George Lauder (Scottish industrialist)|George Lauder]]<br>[[John Campbell Greenway|John Greenway]]<br>[[James Greenway]]<br>[[G. Lauder Greenway]]<br>[[Polly Lauder Tunney]]<br>[[John V. Tunney]]\n|meaning          =\n|footnotes        =\n}}\n\nThe '''Lauder Greenway Family''' is a Scottish-American clan whose influence on, and involvement in, American political and economic affairs dates from the 1640s through the contemporary era. The modern progenitor is [[George Lauder, Sr.]] (1815 - 1901), a Scottish businessman and political radical who raised his son, [[George Lauder (Scottish industrialist)|George Lauder]], and nephew [[Andrew Carnegie]]. The two latter men would go on to create the [[Carnegie Steel Corporation]], the forerunner to [[U.S. Steel]], and subsequently become two of the richest men in the world.\n\n==Business activities==\nThe genesis of the modern iteration of the family is through their development, and partial ownership of, the [[Carnegie Steel Corporation]]. George Lauder was a Scottish industrialist and trained engineer who studied under [[Lord Kelvin]]. He was the \"cousin-brother\" of steel magnate and philanthropist [[Andrew Carnegie]], and a partner in the Carnegie Steel Corporation.<ref name=Skrabek2012>{{cite book|last1=Skrabek |first1=Quentin R. |title=The Carnegie Boys: The Lieutenants of Andrew Carnegie that Changed America |date=2012 |publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc |location=Jefferson, NC |isbn=978-0-7864-6455-5 |page=22 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S1Zd2j12_0wC&pg=PA22&dq=%22George+Lauder%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3a0CVI32KYOfggTXg4KQCA&ved=0CBwQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=%22George%20Lauder%22&f=false}}</ref> The sale of Carnegie Steel to [[J.P. Morgan]] created [[U.S. Steel]], where Lauder was on the board of directors. This was the first corporation in the world with a market capitalization exceeding US$1 billion (${{Inflation|US|1.4|1901|r=1|fmt=c}} billion today).<ref>{{cite web|title=What was the first company with a $1 billion market cap?|url=https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/09/1-billion-market-cap.asp|website=Investopedia|accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref> Lauder's daughter, Harriet, married Dr. James C. Greenway, bringing the two families together.\n\n==Philanthropic activities==\nMajor, long term support from the family has been directed to [[Yale University]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Leaders Through the School's History|url=https://publichealth.yale.edu/about/background/history/leaders.aspx|accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref> [[Phillips Andover]], the [[Metropolitan Opera Association]],<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=G. Lauder Greenway Dies at 77; Headed Met Opera Association|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/06/23/obituaries/g-lauder-greenway-dies-at-77-headed-met-opera-association.html|accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref> the [[New York Philharmonic]],<ref name=\"auto\"/> and the [[New York University]] [[Institute of Fine Arts]].\n\n==Notable Contemporary Members==\n\n*[[George Lauder, Sr.]] (1815 - 1901), Leader of [[Chartism]] in Scottish politics\n*[[George Lauder (Scottish industrialist)|George Lauder]] (1837 - 1924), billionaire industrialist, [[Mechanical engineer]], partner in [[Carnegie Steel Corporation]], director of [[U.S. Steel]]\n*[[John Campbell Greenway]] (1872 - 1926), General, [[U.S. Army]], a [[Rough Rider]] with [[Theodore Roosevelt]], intelligence officer with the [[Office of Naval Intelligence]], Mining Magnate\n*Harriet Lauder Greenway and James Greenway Sr. (married 1903), whose marriage linked the Lauder and Greenway Families together and purchased the [[Lauder Greenway Estate]]. They also gifted the endowment that created the [[Yale School of Public Health]] \n*George Lauder Jr. (1878 - 1916), philanthropist and yachtsman whose [[schooner]], the [[Endymion (Yacht)|Endymion]], held the record for fastest transatlantic crossing.\n*[[James Greenway]] (1903 - 1989), Curator, [[Museum of Comparative Zoology]] at [[Harvard University]], renowned [[Ornithologist]], Lt. Commander [[U.S. Navy]], Intelligence Officer with the [[Office of Naval Intelligence]]\n*[[G. Lauder Greenway]] (1904 - 1981), Chairman, [[Metropolitan Opera Association]], and Director, [[New York Philharmonic]]. Intelligence officer with the [[Office of Naval Intelligence]]. Long time companion of [[Ailsa Mellon Bruce]]\n*[[Polly Lauder Tunney]] (1907 - 2008), Philanthropist, wife of World Heavyweight Champion [[Gene Tunney]]\n*[[John V. Tunney]] (1934 - 2018),  [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Congressman]] then [[United States Senator|U.S. Senator]] from [[California]]. Basis of the film ''[[The Candidate (1972 film)|The Candidate]] starring [[Robert Redford]].\n*[[George V. Lauder]] (b. 1955), Curator, [[Museum of Comparative Zoology]] at Harvard University, renowned [[Ichthyologist]].\n\n==Ancestry==\n===Lauder Side===\nThrough [[George Lauder (Scottish industrialist)|George Lauder]]\u2019s marriage to Anna Maria Romeyn Varick, their descendants above are from the Old Dutch Society of New York City. Mrs. Lauder was a descendant of both [[Joris Jansen Rapelje]], a member of the [[Council of Twelve Men]], the first democratic body in the history of the United States (1641), and [[Founding Father]] Colonel [[Richard Varick]], private secretary to [[George Washington]], and the first mayor of New York City after independence.\n\n===Greenway Side===\nOn the Greenway side, this family are descendant from a number of military and business leaders from American History including:\n*[[General]] [[Evan Shelby]] (1720 - 1794), [[Brigadier General]] in the [[Continental Army]], Signer of the [[Fincastle Resolutions]]\n*[[Colonel]] [[Samuel McDowell]] (1735 - 1817), [[Colonel]] in the [[Continental Army]], and [[Federal Judge]]\n*[[General]] [[William Campbell (general)|William Campbell]] (1745 - 1781), [[Brigadier General]] in the [[Continental Army]], Signer of the [[Fincastle Resolutions]]\n*[[Governor]] [[Issac Shelby]] (1750 - 1826), [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]] hero, and first Governor of the state of [[Kentucky]]\n*[[Doctor (title)|Dr.]] [[Ephraim McDowell]] (1771 - 1830), An American physician and pioneer surgeon. The first person to successfully [[Oophorectomy|remove an ovarian tumor]], he has been called \"the father of ovariotomy\"<ref>Ira M. Rutkow (1988). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=pGQ0YB7yLy4C&source=gbs_navlinks_s The History of Surgery in the United States, 1775\u20131900, Volume 2]''. Norman Publishing, p. 90 {{ISBN|9780930405489}}</ref> as well as founding father of [[abdominal surgery]].<ref>Leslie Thomas Morton, Robert J. Moore, 2005, ''A Bibliography of Medical and Biomedical Biography''. Ashgate,. p. 238</ref><ref>James Ramage, Andrea S. Watkins (2011). ''Kentucky Rising: Democracy, Slavery, and Culture from the Early Republic to the Civil War''. University Press of Kentucky</ref>\n*[[Colonel]] [[Addison White]] (1824 - 1909), [[U.S. Congressman]] from Kentucky and Colonel, [[Confederate States Army]]\n\n==Residence==\nThe [[Lauder Greenway Estate]] is a 50-acre private property with a [[French Renaissance]] mansion in [[Greenwich, Connecticut]]. For a time, it was the most expensive home in United States history.\n\nBuilt for industrialist John Hamilton Gourlie in 1896, it was purchased by the Lauder Greenway Family in 1905 and would stay in that family's hands for a majority of its existence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greenwich's Copper Beech Farm sells for unprecedented $120 million|url=https://www.ctpost.com/local/article/Greenwich-s-Copper-Beech-Farm-sells-for-5396897.php|website=CT Post|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> Considered \"...Greenwich, Conn.\u2019s last Great Estate, an opulent robber baron-era property enveloping 50 prized acres along the tony New York suburb\u2019s waterfront.\" It is the largest surviving [[Gilded Age]] mansion in Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web|title=Touring Greenwich's (Newly Price-Chopped) $140 Million Copper Beech Farm|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/morganbrennan/2013/10/02/touring-greenwichs-newly-price-chopped-140-million-copper-beech-farm/#5937ce1433fa|website=Forbes|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Portal bar|Capitalism|History|Scotland|United States}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Scottish families]]\n[[Category:American families of Scottish ancestry]]\n[[Category:Business families of the United States]]\n[[Category:Wealth in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Scottish-American clan}}\n{{Infobox family\n|name             = '''Lauder Greenway Family'''\n|region           = [[New York City]]<br>[[Greenwich, Connecticut]]<br>[[Washington, D.C.]]\n|origin  = [[Scotland]]\n|heirlooms        =\n|estate           = [[Lauder Greenway Estate]]\n|members          = [[George Lauder, Sr.]]<br>[[George Lauder (Scottish industrialist)|George Lauder]]<br>[[John Campbell Greenway|John Greenway]]<br>[[James Greenway]]<br>[[G. Lauder Greenway]]<br>[[Polly Lauder Tunney]]<br>[[John V. Tunney]]\n|meaning          =\n|footnotes        =\n}}\n\nThe '''Lauder Greenway Family''' is a Scottish-American clan whose influence on, and involvement in, American political and economic affairs dates from the 1640s through the contemporary era. The modern progenitor is [[George Lauder, Sr.]] (1815 - 1901), a Scottish businessman and political radical who raised his son, [[George Lauder (Scottish industrialist)|George Lauder]], and nephew [[Andrew Carnegie]]. The two latter men would go on to create the [[Carnegie Steel Corporation]], the forerunner to [[U.S. Steel]], and subsequently become two of the richest men in the world.\n\n==Business activities==\nThe genesis of the modern iteration of the family is through their development, and partial ownership of, the [[Carnegie Steel Corporation]]. George Lauder was a Scottish industrialist and trained engineer who studied under [[Lord Kelvin]]. He was the \"cousin-brother\" of steel magnate and philanthropist [[Andrew Carnegie]], and a partner in the Carnegie Steel Corporation.<ref name=Skrabek2012>{{cite book|last1=Skrabek |first1=Quentin R. |title=The Carnegie Boys: The Lieutenants of Andrew Carnegie that Changed America |date=2012 |publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc |location=Jefferson, NC |isbn=978-0-7864-6455-5 |page=22 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S1Zd2j12_0wC&pg=PA22&dq=%22George+Lauder%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3a0CVI32KYOfggTXg4KQCA&ved=0CBwQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=%22George%20Lauder%22&f=false}}</ref> The sale of Carnegie Steel to [[J.P. Morgan]] created [[U.S. Steel]], where Lauder was on the board of directors. This was the first corporation in the world with a market capitalization exceeding US$1 billion (${{Inflation|US|1.4|1901|r=1|fmt=c}} billion today).<ref>{{cite web|title=What was the first company with a $1 billion market cap?|url=https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/09/1-billion-market-cap.asp|website=Investopedia|accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref> Lauder's daughter, Harriet, married Dr. James C. Greenway, bringing the two families together.\n\n==Philanthropic activities==\nMajor, long term support from the family has been directed to [[Yale University]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Leaders Through the School's History|url=https://publichealth.yale.edu/about/background/history/leaders.aspx|accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref> [[Phillips Andover]], the [[Metropolitan Opera Association]],<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=G. Lauder Greenway Dies at 77; Headed Met Opera Association|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/06/23/obituaries/g-lauder-greenway-dies-at-77-headed-met-opera-association.html|accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref> the [[New York Philharmonic]],<ref name=\"auto\"/> and the [[New York University]] [[Institute of Fine Arts]].\n\n==Notable Contemporary Members==\n\n*[[George Lauder, Sr.]] (1815 - 1901), Leader of [[Chartism]] in Scottish politics\n*[[George Lauder (Scottish industrialist)|George Lauder]] (1837 - 1924), billionaire industrialist, [[Mechanical engineer]], partner in [[Carnegie Steel Corporation]], director of [[U.S. Steel]]\n*[[John Campbell Greenway]] (1872 - 1926), General, [[U.S. Army]], a [[Rough Rider]] with [[Theodore Roosevelt]], intelligence officer with the [[Office of Naval Intelligence]], Mining Magnate\n*Harriet Lauder Greenway and James Greenway Sr. (married 1903), whose marriage linked the Lauder Greenway Family together, and also gifted the endowment that created the [[Yale School of Public Health]]\n*George Lauder Jr. (1878 - 1916), philanthropist and yachtsman whose [[schooner]], the [[Endymion (Yacht)|Endymion]], held the record for fastest transatlantic crossing.\n*[[James Greenway]] (1903 - 1989), Curator, [[Museum of Comparative Zoology]] at [[Harvard University]], renowned [[Ornithologist]], Lt. Commander [[U.S. Navy]], Intelligence Officer with the [[Office of Naval Intelligence]]\n*[[G. Lauder Greenway]] (1904 - 1981), Chairman, [[Metropolitan Opera Association]], and Director, [[New York Philharmonic]]. Intelligence officer with the [[Office of Naval Intelligence]]. Long time companion of [[Ailsa Mellon Bruce]]\n*[[Polly Lauder Tunney]] (1907 - 2008), Philanthropist, wife of World Heavyweight Champion [[Gene Tunney]]\n*[[John V. Tunney]] (1934 - 2018),  [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Congressman]] then [[United States Senator|U.S. Senator]] from [[California]]. Basis of the film ''[[The Candidate (1972 film)|The Candidate]] starring [[Robert Redford]].\n*[[George V. Lauder]] (b. 1955), Curator, [[Museum of Comparative Zoology]] at Harvard University, renowned [[Ichthyologist]].\n\n==Ancestry==\n===Lauder Side===\nThrough [[George Lauder (Scottish industrialist)|George Lauder]]\u2019s marriage to Anna Maria Romeyn Varick, their descendants above are from the Old Dutch Society of New York City. Mrs. Lauder was a descendant of both [[Joris Jansen Rapelje]], a member of the [[Council of Twelve Men]], the first democratic body in the history of the United States (1641), and [[Founding Father]] Colonel [[Richard Varick]], private secretary to [[George Washington]], and the first mayor of New York City after independence.\n\n===Greenway Side===\nOn the Greenway side, this family are descendant from a number of military and business leaders from American History including:\n*[[General]] [[Evan Shelby]] (1720 - 1794), [[Brigadier General]] in the [[Continental Army]], Signer of the [[Fincastle Resolutions]]\n*[[Colonel]] [[Samuel McDowell]] (1735 - 1817), [[Colonel]] in the [[Continental Army]], and [[Federal Judge]]\n*[[General]] [[William Campbell (general)|William Campbell]] (1745 - 1781), [[Brigadier General]] in the [[Continental Army]], Signer of the [[Fincastle Resolutions]]\n*[[Governor]] [[Issac Shelby]] (1750 - 1826), [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]] hero, and first Governor of the state of [[Kentucky]]\n*[[Doctor (title)|Dr.]] [[Ephraim McDowell]] (1771 - 1830), An American physician and pioneer surgeon. The first person to successfully [[Oophorectomy|remove an ovarian tumor]], he has been called \"the father of ovariotomy\"<ref>Ira M. Rutkow (1988). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=pGQ0YB7yLy4C&source=gbs_navlinks_s The History of Surgery in the United States, 1775\u20131900, Volume 2]''. Norman Publishing, p. 90 {{ISBN|9780930405489}}</ref> as well as founding father of [[abdominal surgery]].<ref>Leslie Thomas Morton, Robert J. Moore, 2005, ''A Bibliography of Medical and Biomedical Biography''. Ashgate,. p. 238</ref><ref>James Ramage, Andrea S. Watkins (2011). ''Kentucky Rising: Democracy, Slavery, and Culture from the Early Republic to the Civil War''. University Press of Kentucky</ref>\n*[[Colonel]] [[Addison White]] (1824 - 1909), [[U.S. Congressman]] from Kentucky and Colonel, [[Confederate States Army]]\n\n==Residence==\nThe [[Lauder Greenway Estate]] is a 50-acre private property with a [[French Renaissance]] mansion in [[Greenwich, Connecticut]]. For a time, it was the most expensive home in United States history.\n\nBuilt for industrialist John Hamilton Gourlie in 1896, it was purchased by the Lauder Greenway Family in 1905 and would stay in that family's hands for a majority of its existence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greenwich's Copper Beech Farm sells for unprecedented $120 million|url=https://www.ctpost.com/local/article/Greenwich-s-Copper-Beech-Farm-sells-for-5396897.php|website=CT Post|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> Considered \"...Greenwich, Conn.\u2019s last Great Estate, an opulent robber baron-era property enveloping 50 prized acres along the tony New York suburb\u2019s waterfront.\" It is the largest surviving [[Gilded Age]] mansion in Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web|title=Touring Greenwich's (Newly Price-Chopped) $140 Million Copper Beech Farm|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/morganbrennan/2013/10/02/touring-greenwichs-newly-price-chopped-140-million-copper-beech-farm/#5937ce1433fa|website=Forbes|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Portal bar|Capitalism|History|Scotland|United States}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Scottish families]]\n[[Category:American families of Scottish ancestry]]\n[[Category:Business families of the United States]]\n[[Category:Wealth in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "1I0I1I0I1I0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable Contemporary Members", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lauder_Greenway_family"}
{"title_page": "Pamela J. Green", "text_new": "{{short description|American molecular biologist}}\n{{Notability|date=June 2017}}\n'''Pamela J. Green''' is Crawford H. Greenewalt Chair, Professor of [[Plant]] and [[Soil Sciences]] and Professor of [[Marine biology|Marine]] Studies at the [[University of Delaware]]. She has researched the uses for [[RNA]], one of the three major biological [[macromolecules]] that are essential for all known forms of life.<ref name=dbi>{{cite web|url=http://www.dbi.udel.edu/biographies/pamela-j-green|title=Delaware Biotechnology Institute, Pamela J. Green|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nGreen received her [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] for [[Biology]] from [[Purdue University]] in 1979 and her [[Ph.D.]] for [[Biochemistry]] and [[Molecular Biology]] from [[Stony Brook University]] in 1985.<ref name=dbi />\n\n==Research areas==\nGreen's lab researches on post-transcriptional mechanisms which regulate the expression of [[genes]] in higher plants. The lab is interested in the fate of [[mRNA]] molecules which have their role as intermediates in the gene expression process.<ref name=univdel>{{cite web|url=http://canr.udel.edu/faculty/green-pamela/|title=College of Agriculture & Natural Resources|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\nJeong, D.H., Green, P.J., Methods for validation of miRNA sequence variants and the cleavage of their targets. Methods, 58:  135-143 (2012), EPub 2012 Aug 17.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = Methods for validation of miRNA sequence variants and the cleavage of their targets|last = Jeong|first = D.H.|date = August 17, 2012|journal = Methods|doi = 10.1016/j.ymeth.2012.08.005|pmid = 22922269|access-date = |last2 = Green|first2 = P.J. |volume=58 |issue = 2|pages=135\u2013143}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dbi.udel.edu/biographies/pamela-j-green Delaware Biotechnology Institute]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Green, Pamela J}}\n[[Category:American molecular biologists]]\n[[Category:University of Delaware faculty]]\n[[Category:Highly Cited Researchers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women biologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Stony Brook University alumni]]\n[[Category:Purdue University alumni]]\n\n\n{{US-biologist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American molecular biologist}}\n{{Notability|date=June 2017}}\n'''Pamela J. Green''' is Crawford H. Greenewalt Chair, Professor of [[Plant]] and [[Soil Sciences]] and Professor of [[Marine biology|Marine]] Studies at the [[University of Delaware]]. She has researched the uses for [[RNA]], one of the three major biological [[macromolecules]] that are essential for all known forms of life.<ref name=dbi>{{cite web|url=http://www.dbi.udel.edu/biographies/pamela-j-green|title=Delaware Biotechnology Institute, Pamela J. Green|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nGreen received her [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] for [[Biology]] from [[Purdue University]] in 1979 and her [[Ph.D.]] for [[Biochemistry]] and [[Molecular Biology]] from [[Stony Brook University]] in 1985.<ref name=dbi />\n\n==Research areas==\nGreen's lab researches on post-transcriptional mechanisms which regulate the expression of [[genes]] in higher plants. The lab is interested in the fate of [[mRNA]] molecules which have their role as intermediates in the gene expression process.<ref name=univdel>{{cite web|url=http://canr.udel.edu/faculty/green-pamela/|title=College of Agriculture & Natural Resources|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\nJeong, D.H., Green, P.J., Methods for validation of miRNA sequence variants and the cleavage of their targets. Methods, 58:  135-143 (2012), EPub 2012 Aug 17.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = Methods for validation of miRNA sequence variants and the cleavage of their targets|last = Jeong|first = D.H.|date = August 17, 2012|journal = Methods|doi = 10.1016/j.ymeth.2012.08.005|pmid = 22922269|access-date = |last2 = Green|first2 = P.J. |volume=58 |issue = 2|pages=135\u2013143}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dbi.udel.edu/biographies/pamela-j-green Delaware Biotechnology Institute]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Green, Pamela J}}\n[[Category:American molecular biologists]]\n[[Category:University of Delaware faculty]]\n[[Category:Highly Cited Researchers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women biologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Stony Brook University alumni]]\n[[Category:Purdue University alumni]]\n\n\n{{US-biologist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pamela_J._Green"}
{"title_page": "Harmonic generation", "text_new": "{{distinguish|High harmonic generation|G\u00e9n\u00e9ration harmonique}}\n[[File:N-th harmonic generation.png|thumb|N-th harmonic generation]]\n'''Harmonic generation''' ('''HG''', also called '''multiple harmonic generation''') is a [[nonlinear optics|nonlinear optical]] process in which n [[photon]]s with the same frequency interact with a nonlinear material, are \"combined\", and generate a new photon with n times the energy of the initial photons (equivalently, n times the [[frequency]] and the [[wavelength]] divided by n).\n\n==General process==\n\nIn a medium having a substantial [[nonlinear susceptibility]], harmonic generation is possible. Note that for even orders (n=2,4,...), the medium must have no center of symmetry (non-centrosymmetrical).<ref name=Boyd2007>{{cite book|language=en |title= Nonlinear optics (third edition) | chapter = The Nonlinear Optical Susceptibility |year=2007|last1=Boyd|first1= R. |pages=1\u201367| doi = 10.1016/B978-0-12-369470-6.00001-0|isbn= 9780123694706 }}</ref>\n\nBecause the process requires that many photons are present at the same time and at the same place, the generation process has a low probability to occur, and this probability decreases with the order n. To generate efficiently, the symmetry of the medium must allow the signal to be amplified (through [[phase matching]] for instance), and the light source must be intense and well-controlled spatially (with a collimated [[laser]]) and temporally (more signal if the laser has short pulses).<ref name=handbookNL>{{cite book|language=en |title= Handbook of Nonlinear Optics (2nd edition)|year=2003|last1=Sutherland|first1= Richard L.|isbn= 9780824742430 }}</ref>\n\n== Sum-frequency generation (SFG) ==\n{{Main|Sum-frequency generation}}\nA special case where the number of photons in interaction is n=2, but with two different photons at <math>\\omega_1</math> and <math>\\omega_2</math>.\n\n== Second-harmonic generation (SHG) ==\n{{Main|Second-harmonic generation}}\nA special case where the number of photons in interaction is n=2. Also a special case of sum-frequency generation where both photons are at the same frequency <math>\\omega</math>.\n\n== Third-harmonic generation (THG) ==\n\nA special case where the number of photons in interaction is n=3, if all the photons have the same frequency <math>\\omega</math>. If they have different frequency, the general term of [[four-wave mixing]] is preferred. This process involves the 3rd order nonlinear susceptibility <math>\\chi^{(3)}</math><ref name=\"boyd\">{{cite book|language=en |title= Nonlinear optics (third edition)|year=2007|last1=Boyd|first1= R.W.|isbn= 9780123694706 | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=uoRUi1Yb7ooC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Nonlinear+optics&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixn8Gq18LmAhUGA6wKHX5NB10Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Nonlinear%20optics&f=false}}</ref>.\n\nUnlike SHG, it is a volumetric process<ref name=\"MoreauxSandre2001\">{{cite journal|last1=Moreaux|first1=Laurent|last2=Sandre|first2=Olivier|last3=Charpak|first3=Serge|last4=Blanchard-Desce|first4=Mireille|last5=Mertz|first5=Jerome|title=Coherent Scattering in Multi-Harmonic Light Microscopy|journal=Biophysical Journal|volume=80|issue=3|year=2001|pages=1568\u20131574|issn=00063495|doi=10.1016/S0006-3495(01)76129-2|pmc=1301348}}</ref> and has been shown in liquids<ref name=\"KajzarMessier1985\">{{cite journal|last1=Kajzar|first1=F.|last2=Messier|first2=J.|title=Third-harmonic generation in liquids|journal=Physical Review A|volume=32|issue=4|year=1985|pages=2352\u20132363|issn=0556-2791|doi=10.1103/PhysRevA.32.2352}}</ref>. However, it is enhanced at interfaces<ref name=\"ChengXie2002\">{{cite journal|last1=Cheng|first1=Ji-Xin|last2=Xie|first2=X. Sunney|title=Green's function formulation for third-harmonic generation microscopy|journal=Journal of the Optical Society of America B|volume=19|issue=7|year=2002|pages=1604|issn=0740-3224|doi=10.1364/JOSAB.19.001604}}</ref>.\n\n=== Materials used for THG ===\n\nNonlinear crystals such as [[Barium_borate|BBO]] (\u03b2-BaB<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub>) or [[Lithium_triborate|LBO]] can convert THG, otherwise THG can be generated from membranes in microscopy<ref>{{cite book|title= Second Harmonic Generation Imaging, 2nd edition|surname1= Pavone|first1= Francesco S. |surname2= Campagnola|first2= Paul J. | year=2016|isbn=978-1-4398-4914-9|publisher= CRC Taylor&Francis|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=EiTOBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Second+Harmonic+Generation+Imaging+Pavone+Francesco&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiM_6jryv7lAhVGF6wKHQa2CjAQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Second%20Harmonic%20Generation%20Imaging%20Pavone%20Francesco&f=false}}</ref>.\n\n== Fourth-harmonic generation (FHG or 4HG) ==\n\nA special case where the number of photons in interaction is n=4.\nReported around the year 2000<ref name=\"KojimaKonno2000\">{{cite journal|last1=Kojima|first1=Tetsuo|last2=Konno|first2=Susumu|last3=Fujikawa|first3=Shuichi|last4=Yasui|first4=Koji|last5=Yoshizawa|first5=Kenji|last6=Mori|first6=Yusuke|last7=Sasaki|first7=Takatomo|last8=Tanaka|first8=Mitsuhiro|last9=Okada|first9=Yukikatsu|title=20-W ultraviolet-beam generation by fourth-harmonic generation of an all-solid-state laser|journal=Optics Letters|volume=25|issue=1|year=2000|pages=58|issn=0146-9592|doi=10.1364/OL.25.000058}}</ref>, powerful lasers now enable efficient FHG. This process involves the 4th order nonlinear susceptibility <math>\\chi^{(4)}</math>. \n\n=== Materials used for FHG ===\nSome [[Barium_borate|BBO]] (\u03b2-BaB<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub>) are used for FHG<ref>{{cite web |url= http://raicol.com/bbo/bbo-for-fhg |title=BBO for FHG |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= raicol.com|publisher= |access-date=2019-12-01 |quote=}}</ref>.\n\n== Harmonic generation for n > 4 ==\n\nHarmonic generation for n = 5 (5HG) or more is theoretically possible, but the interaction requires a very high number of photons to interact and has therefore a low probability to happen : the signal at higher harmonics will be very low, and requires very intense lasers to be generated. To generate high harmonics (like n = 30 and so on), a substantially different process can be used : [[High harmonic generation]]. \n\n==Sources==\n\n*{{cite book|language=en |title= Nonlinear optics (third edition)|year=2007|last1=Boyd|first1= R.W.|isbn= 9780123694706 | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=uoRUi1Yb7ooC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Nonlinear+optics&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixn8Gq18LmAhUGA6wKHX5NB10Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Nonlinear%20optics&f=false}}\n* {{cite book|language=en |title= Handbook of Nonlinear Optics (2nd edition)|year=2003|last1=Sutherland|first1= Richard L.|isbn= 9780824742430 | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ccXo3WrHp2UC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Handbook+of+Nonlinear+Optics&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwistLGg18LmAhUPUK0KHdwxAzIQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Handbook%20of%20Nonlinear%20Optics&f=false}}\n* {{cite book|language=en |title= Optics (4th Edition)|year=2002|last1=Hecht|first1= Eugene|isbn= 978-0805385663|publisher = Addison-Wesley}}\n* {{cite book|language=en |title= Applied Nonlinear Optics |year=2006|last1=Zernike|first1= Frits|last2=Midwinter|first2= John E.|isbn= 978-0486453606|publisher = Dover Publications|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Y3Wsyo7TgdkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Applied+Nonlinear+Optics&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjDgbb_1sLmAhUJWa0KHZSXCI0Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Applied%20Nonlinear%20Optics&f=false}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/chemistry/third-harmonic-generation |title=THG: an overview |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= sciencedirect.com|publisher= |access-date=2019-12-01 |quote=}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Nonlinear optics]]\n*[[Second-harmonic generation]]\n*[[High harmonic generation]]\n*[[Optical frequency multiplier]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Lasers}}\n[[Category:Nonlinear optics]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|High harmonic generation}}\n[[File:N-th harmonic generation.png|thumb|N-th harmonic generation]]\n'''Harmonic generation''' ('''HG''', also called '''multiple harmonic generation''') is a [[nonlinear optics|nonlinear optical]] process in which n [[photon]]s with the same frequency interact with a nonlinear material, are \"combined\", and generate a new photon with n times the energy of the initial photons (equivalently, n times the [[frequency]] and the [[wavelength]] divided by n).\n\n==General process==\n\nIn a medium having a substantial [[nonlinear susceptibility]], harmonic generation is possible. Note that for even orders (n=2,4,...), the medium must have no center of symmetry (non-centrosymmetrical).<ref name=Boyd2007>{{cite book|language=en |title= Nonlinear optics (third edition) | chapter = The Nonlinear Optical Susceptibility |year=2007|last1=Boyd|first1= R. |pages=1\u201367| doi = 10.1016/B978-0-12-369470-6.00001-0|isbn= 9780123694706 }}</ref>\n\nBecause the process requires that many photons are present at the same time and at the same place, the generation process has a low probability to occur, and this probability decreases with the order n. To generate efficiently, the symmetry of the medium must allow the signal to be amplified (through [[phase matching]] for instance), and the light source must be intense and well-controlled spatially (with a collimated [[laser]]) and temporally (more signal if the laser has short pulses).<ref name=handbookNL>{{cite book|language=en |title= Handbook of Nonlinear Optics (2nd edition)|year=2003|last1=Sutherland|first1= Richard L.|isbn= 9780824742430 }}</ref>\n\n== Sum-frequency generation (SFG) ==\n{{Main|Sum-frequency generation}}\nA special case where the number of photons in interaction is n=2, but with two different photons at <math>\\omega_1</math> and <math>\\omega_2</math>.\n\n== Second-harmonic generation (SHG) ==\n{{Main|Second-harmonic generation}}\nA special case where the number of photons in interaction is n=2. Also a special case of sum-frequency generation where both photons are at the same frequency <math>\\omega</math>.\n\n== Third-harmonic generation (THG) ==\n\nA special case where the number of photons in interaction is n=3, if all the photons have the same frequency <math>\\omega</math>. If they have different frequency, the general term of [[four-wave mixing]] is preferred. This process involves the 3rd order nonlinear susceptibility <math>\\chi^{(3)}</math><ref name=\"boyd\">{{cite book|language=en |title= Nonlinear optics (third edition)|year=2007|last1=Boyd|first1= R.W.|isbn= 9780123694706 | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=uoRUi1Yb7ooC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Nonlinear+optics&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixn8Gq18LmAhUGA6wKHX5NB10Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Nonlinear%20optics&f=false}}</ref>.\n\nUnlike SHG, it is a volumetric process<ref name=\"MoreauxSandre2001\">{{cite journal|last1=Moreaux|first1=Laurent|last2=Sandre|first2=Olivier|last3=Charpak|first3=Serge|last4=Blanchard-Desce|first4=Mireille|last5=Mertz|first5=Jerome|title=Coherent Scattering in Multi-Harmonic Light Microscopy|journal=Biophysical Journal|volume=80|issue=3|year=2001|pages=1568\u20131574|issn=00063495|doi=10.1016/S0006-3495(01)76129-2|pmc=1301348}}</ref> and has been shown in liquids<ref name=\"KajzarMessier1985\">{{cite journal|last1=Kajzar|first1=F.|last2=Messier|first2=J.|title=Third-harmonic generation in liquids|journal=Physical Review A|volume=32|issue=4|year=1985|pages=2352\u20132363|issn=0556-2791|doi=10.1103/PhysRevA.32.2352}}</ref>. However, it is enhanced at interfaces<ref name=\"ChengXie2002\">{{cite journal|last1=Cheng|first1=Ji-Xin|last2=Xie|first2=X. Sunney|title=Green's function formulation for third-harmonic generation microscopy|journal=Journal of the Optical Society of America B|volume=19|issue=7|year=2002|pages=1604|issn=0740-3224|doi=10.1364/JOSAB.19.001604}}</ref>.\n\n=== Materials used for THG ===\n\nNonlinear crystals such as [[Barium_borate|BBO]] (\u03b2-BaB<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub>) or [[Lithium_triborate|LBO]] can convert THG, otherwise THG can be generated from membranes in microscopy<ref>{{cite book|title= Second Harmonic Generation Imaging, 2nd edition|surname1= Pavone|first1= Francesco S. |surname2= Campagnola|first2= Paul J. | year=2016|isbn=978-1-4398-4914-9|publisher= CRC Taylor&Francis|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=EiTOBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Second+Harmonic+Generation+Imaging+Pavone+Francesco&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiM_6jryv7lAhVGF6wKHQa2CjAQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Second%20Harmonic%20Generation%20Imaging%20Pavone%20Francesco&f=false}}</ref>.\n\n== Fourth-harmonic generation (FHG or 4HG) ==\n\nA special case where the number of photons in interaction is n=4.\nReported around the year 2000<ref name=\"KojimaKonno2000\">{{cite journal|last1=Kojima|first1=Tetsuo|last2=Konno|first2=Susumu|last3=Fujikawa|first3=Shuichi|last4=Yasui|first4=Koji|last5=Yoshizawa|first5=Kenji|last6=Mori|first6=Yusuke|last7=Sasaki|first7=Takatomo|last8=Tanaka|first8=Mitsuhiro|last9=Okada|first9=Yukikatsu|title=20-W ultraviolet-beam generation by fourth-harmonic generation of an all-solid-state laser|journal=Optics Letters|volume=25|issue=1|year=2000|pages=58|issn=0146-9592|doi=10.1364/OL.25.000058}}</ref>, powerful lasers now enable efficient FHG. This process involves the 4th order nonlinear susceptibility <math>\\chi^{(4)}</math>. \n\n=== Materials used for FHG ===\nSome [[Barium_borate|BBO]] (\u03b2-BaB<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub>) are used for FHG<ref>{{cite web |url= http://raicol.com/bbo/bbo-for-fhg |title=BBO for FHG |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= raicol.com|publisher= |access-date=2019-12-01 |quote=}}</ref>.\n\n== Harmonic generation for n > 4 ==\n\nHarmonic generation for n = 5 (5HG) or more is theoretically possible, but the interaction requires a very high number of photons to interact and has therefore a low probability to happen : the signal at higher harmonics will be very low, and requires very intense lasers to be generated. To generate high harmonics (like n = 30 and so on), a substantially different process can be used : [[High harmonic generation]]. \n\n==Sources==\n\n*{{cite book|language=en |title= Nonlinear optics (third edition)|year=2007|last1=Boyd|first1= R.W.|isbn= 9780123694706 | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=uoRUi1Yb7ooC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Nonlinear+optics&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixn8Gq18LmAhUGA6wKHX5NB10Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Nonlinear%20optics&f=false}}\n* {{cite book|language=en |title= Handbook of Nonlinear Optics (2nd edition)|year=2003|last1=Sutherland|first1= Richard L.|isbn= 9780824742430 | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ccXo3WrHp2UC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Handbook+of+Nonlinear+Optics&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwistLGg18LmAhUPUK0KHdwxAzIQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Handbook%20of%20Nonlinear%20Optics&f=false}}\n* {{cite book|language=en |title= Optics (4th Edition)|year=2002|last1=Hecht|first1= Eugene|isbn= 978-0805385663|publisher = Addison-Wesley}}\n* {{cite book|language=en |title= Applied Nonlinear Optics |year=2006|last1=Zernike|first1= Frits|last2=Midwinter|first2= John E.|isbn= 978-0486453606|publisher = Dover Publications|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Y3Wsyo7TgdkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Applied+Nonlinear+Optics&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjDgbb_1sLmAhUJWa0KHZSXCI0Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Applied%20Nonlinear%20Optics&f=false}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/chemistry/third-harmonic-generation |title=THG: an overview |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= sciencedirect.com|publisher= |access-date=2019-12-01 |quote=}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Nonlinear optics]]\n*[[Second-harmonic generation]]\n*[[High harmonic generation]]\n*[[Optical frequency multiplier]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Lasers}}\n[[Category:Nonlinear optics]]\n", "name_user": "BP-Aegirsson", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harmonic_generation"}
{"title_page": "Watson Ranch Quartzite", "text_new": "{{short description|Geologic formation in Utah, United States}}\n{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Watson Ranch Quartzite\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| type           = [[Formation (stratigraphy)|Formation]]\n| age            =  [[Ordovician]]\n| prilithology   =\n| otherlithology =\n| namedfor       =\n| namedby        =\n| region         = [[Utah]]\n| country        = [[United States]]\n| coordinates    =\n| unitof         =\n| subunits       =\n| underlies      =\n| overlies       =\n| thickness      =\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            =\n| map_caption    =\n}}\nThe '''Watson Ranch Quartzite''' is a [[Formation (geology)|geologic formation]] in [[Utah]]. It preserves [[fossils]] dating back to the [[Ordovician]] [[Period (geology)|period]].\n==Background==\nThe namesake of the quartzite is the homestead of Jack Watson, owner of the Watson Ranch. The ranch was in the [[Fossil Mountain (Utah)|Fossil Mountain]] and [[Ibex Crags|Ibex area]].<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Swanson |editor1-first=Terry W |title=Western Cordillera and Adjacent Areas |date=2003 |publisher=Geological Society of America |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JpO0Gq0mdkQC&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=%22Watson+Ranch+Quartzite%22&source=bl&ots=o6iNGyNQAM&sig=ACfU3U0PThLd2BmM9Vm2uYSXB-Hzg1R_sg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwihz872uvfoAhU5knIEHS_ICzIQ6AEwA3oECAwQKA#v=onepage&q=%22Watson%20Ranch%20Quartzite%22&f=false}}</ref>\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite web|title= Fossilworks: Gateway to the Paleobiology Database|author= Various Contributors to the Paleobiology Database|url= http://www.fossilworks.org/|accessdate= 2014-07-08}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Earth sciences|Utah|Paleontology|Paleozoic}}\n* [[List of fossiliferous stratigraphic units in Utah]]\n* [[Paleontology in Utah]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ordovician geology of Utah]]\n[[Category:Quartzite formations]]\n[[Category:Ordovician southern paleotropical deposits]]\n\n\n{{Utah-geologic-formation-stub}}\n{{Ordovician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Geologic formation in Utah, United States}}\n{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Watson Ranch Quartzite\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| type           = [[Formation (stratigraphy)|Formation]]\n| age            =  [[Ordovician]]\n| prilithology   =\n| otherlithology =\n| namedfor       =\n| namedby        =\n| region         = [[Utah]]\n| country        = [[United States]]\n| coordinates    =\n| unitof         =\n| subunits       =\n| underlies      =\n| overlies       =\n| thickness      =\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            =\n| map_caption    =\n}}\nThe '''Watson Ranch Quartzite''' is a [[Formation (geology)|geologic formation]] in [[Utah]]. It preserves [[fossils]] dating back to the [[Ordovician]] [[Period (geology)|period]].\n==Background==\nThe namesake of the quartzite is the homestead of Jack Watson, owner of the Watson Ranch. The ranch was in the [[Fossil Mountain (Utah)|Fossil Mountain]] and [[Ibex Crags|Ibex area]].<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Swanson |editor1-first=Terry W |title=Western Cordillera and Adjacent Areas |date=2003 |publisher=Geological Society of America |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JpO0Gq0mdkQC&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=%22Watson+Ranch+Quartzite%22&source=bl&ots=o6iNGyNQAM&sig=ACfU3U0PThLd2BmM9Vm2uYSXB-Hzg1R_sg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwihz872uvfoAhU5knIEHS_ICzIQ6AEwA3oECAwQKA#v=onepage&q=%22Watson%20Ranch%20Quartzite%22&f=false}}</ref>\n==Further eeading==\n*{{cite web|title= Fossilworks: Gateway to the Paleobiology Database|author= Various Contributors to the Paleobiology Database|url= http://www.fossilworks.org/|accessdate= 2014-07-08}}\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Earth sciences|Utah|Paleontology|Paleozoic}}\n* [[List of fossiliferous stratigraphic units in Utah]]\n* [[Paleontology in Utah]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ordovician geology of Utah]]\n[[Category:Quartzite formations]]\n[[Category:Ordovician southern paleotropical deposits]]\n\n\n{{Utah-geologic-formation-stub}}\n{{Ordovician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Evrik", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Watson_Ranch_Quartzite"}
{"title_page": "Pamela Fraker", "text_new": "{{short description|American biochemist}}\n'''Pamela J. Fraker''' is professor emeritus at [[Michigan State University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leelanauconservancy.org/2018/06/generous-spirit-pam-fraker/|title=A Generous Spirit: Pam Fraker|date=2018-06-13|website=The Leelanau Conservancy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>  In 2007 she was elected to the [[National Academy of Sciences]], the first woman from MSU to be so honored.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://msutoday.msu.edu/news/2007/first-msu-woman-elected-to-national-academy-of-sciences/|title=First MSU woman elected to National Academy of Sciences|last=University|first=Michigan State|website=MSUToday|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> She retired as distinguished professor of biochemistry and molecular biology in May 2012, after 39 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/naturalscience/docs/bmb_nwsltr-feb2013-forweb.pdf|title=Biochemistry and Molecular Biology 2013 Alumni Newsletter|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nShe grew up in [[Williamsport, Indiana]]. Despite neither of her parents having high school diplomas, Fraker was encouraged to pursue her education.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Davis|first=T. H.|date=2012-10-01|title=Profile of Pamela J. Fraker|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=109|issue=42|pages=16754\u201316755|doi=10.1073/pnas.1215646109|pmid=23027978|pmc=3479528|issn=0027-8424}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nShe attended [[Purdue University]], starting in 1962, studying biology. She studied under microbiologist Samuel Kaplan at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois]], [[Champaign, Illinois|Champaign]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Fraker earned her PhD at the University of Illinois in 1971.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Research ==\nFraker was the lead scientist of two studies investigating the physiological factors that influence the immune system, in particular the discovery of an appetite-controlling hormone and the relationship between [[metabolism]], the [[immune system]] and the [[Neuroendocrine cell|neuroendocrine]] system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2008/02/080204172208.htm|title=What Does And Doesn't Affect Immune System|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fraker, Pamela}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Williamsport, Indiana]]\n[[Category:American biochemists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American biologists]]\n[[Category:American women biologists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Purdue University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American biochemist}}\n'''Pamela J. Fraker''' is professor emeritus at [[Michigan State University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leelanauconservancy.org/2018/06/generous-spirit-pam-fraker/|title=A Generous Spirit: Pam Fraker|date=2018-06-13|website=The Leelanau Conservancy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>  In 2007 she was elected to the [[National Academy of Sciences]], the first woman from MSU to be so honored.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://msutoday.msu.edu/news/2007/first-msu-woman-elected-to-national-academy-of-sciences/|title=First MSU woman elected to National Academy of Sciences|last=University|first=Michigan State|website=MSUToday|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> She retired as distinguished professor of biochemistry and molecular biology in May 2012, after 39 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/naturalscience/docs/bmb_nwsltr-feb2013-forweb.pdf|title=Biochemistry and Molecular Biology 2013 Alumni Newsletter|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nShe grew up in [[Williamsport, Indiana]]. Despite neither of her parents having high school diplomas, Fraker was encouraged to pursue her education.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Davis|first=T. H.|date=2012-10-01|title=Profile of Pamela J. Fraker|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=109|issue=42|pages=16754\u201316755|doi=10.1073/pnas.1215646109|pmid=23027978|pmc=3479528|issn=0027-8424}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nShe attended [[Purdue University]], starting in 1962, studying biology. She studied under microbiologist Samuel Kaplan at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois]], [[Champaign, Illinois|Champaign]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Fraker earned her PhD at the University of Illinois in 1971.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Research ==\nFraker was the lead scientist of two studies investigating the physiological factors that influence the immune system, in particular the discovery of an appetite-controlling hormone and the relationship between [[metabolism]], the [[immune system]] and the [[Neuroendocrine cell|neuroendocrine]] system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2008/02/080204172208.htm|title=What Does And Doesn't Affect Immune System|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fraker, Pamela}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Williamsport, Indiana]]\n[[Category:American biochemists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American biologists]]\n[[Category:Women biologists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Purdue University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pamela_Fraker"}
{"title_page": "Portland Beavers", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n| name = Portland Beavers\n| firstseason = 1903 \n| lastseason = 2010\n| allyears = 1903\u20131917, 1919\u20131972, 1978\u20131993, 2001\u20132010\n| city = Portland, Oregon\n| logo = PortlandBeaversLogo2008.png\n| caplogo = Portlandbeaverscap2008.PNG\n| past class level = {{plainlist|\n*[[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] (1946\u20131951, 1958\u20131972,<br>1978\u20131993, 2001\u20132010)\n*[[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] (1902, 1918)\n*[[Independent league baseball|Independent]] (1903)\n*[[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] (1904\u20131911)\n*[[Double-A (baseball)|Double-A]] (now [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]])<br>(1912\u20131917, 1919\u20131945)\n*[[Minor League Baseball#Open|Open]] (1952\u20131957)\n}}\n| league = [[Pacific Coast League]] (1903\u20131917,<br>1919\u20131972, 1978\u20131993, 2001\u20132010)\n| conference = Pacific Conference\n| division = North Division\n| past league = \n| pastmajorleague = {{plainlist|\n*[[San Diego Padres]] (2001\u20132010)\n*[[Minnesota Twins]] (1987\u20131993)\n*[[Philadelphia Phillies]] (1983\u20131986)\n*[[Pittsburgh Pirates]] (1979\u20131982)\n*[[Cleveland Indians]] (1972, 1978)\n*[[Minnesota Twins]] (1971)\n*[[Milwaukee Brewers]] (1970)\n*[[Cleveland Indians]] (1964\u20131969)\n*[[Kansas City Athletics]] (1962\u20131963)\n*[[St. Louis Cardinals]] (1961)\n*[[Kansas City Athletics]] (1959)\n*[[Chicago Cubs]] (1957\u20131958)\n*[[Brooklyn Dodgers]] (1956)\n*[[Detroit Tigers]] (1935)\n*[[Philadelphia Athletics]] (1925\u20131932)\n*[[Cleveland Indians]] (unofficial)<br>(1910\u20131915)\n}}\n|mascot = Lucky (2008-2010)<br /> Boomer (2001-2007)<br /> Round Tripper (1979-1994)\n\n| pastnames = {{plainlist|\n*Portland Beavers\n*Portland Ducks (1929)\n*Portland Buckaroos (1918)\n*Portland Giants (1905)\n*Portland Browns (1903\u20131904)\n*Portland Webfoots (1902\u20131903)\n}}\n| pastparks = {{plainlist|\n*[[PGE Park]] (1956\u20132010)\n*[[Vaughn Street Park]] (1901\u20131955)\n}}\n| classchamps = \n| leaguechamps = 1901, 1906, 1910, 1911, 1913, 1914, 1936, 1945, 1983\n| conferencechamps =  \n| divisionchamps = 1965, 1983, 1993, 2004\n}}\nThe '''Portland Beavers''' was the name of separate [[minor league baseball]] teams, which represented [[Portland, Oregon]], in the [[Pacific Coast League]] (PCL). The team was established in 1903, the first year of the PCL.\n\n==Franchise history==\nMany baseball teams have been known as the Portland Beavers; the most recent club, which began operating in 2001, recognized the history of all previous incarnations as its own, stating it was established in 1903, the same year the Pacific Coast League was established. The \"Beavers\" originated in 1906 following a newspaper contest to rename the existing Portland team that had been created in 1901 when a group of Portland businessmen founded the Portland Baseball Club.\n\nAlong with the [[Los Angeles Angels (PCL)|Los Angeles Angels]], [[Oakland Oaks (PCL)|Oakland Oaks]], [[Sacramento Solons]], [[San Francisco Seals (baseball)|San Francisco Seals]], and [[Seattle Rainiers]], a Portland Beavers club was a charter member of the Pacific Coast League in 1903. Portland and [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] were the only two charter cities that had a team in the PCL as of 2010, the other cities having been taken over by [[Major League Baseball]] franchises.\n\nFollowing the 2010 season, the Beavers were placed for sale and relocation because of the lack of a suitable stadium in Portland, as [[PGE Park]] was being remodeled into a soccer-only configuration for [[Major League Soccer]]'s 2011 expansion [[Portland Timbers]]. In 2010, the Beavers were sold to Jeff Moorad, owner of the [[San Diego Padres]].<ref name=\"tucson\">{{cite web|url=http://sandiego.padres.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101014&content_id=15635170&vkey=news_sd&c_id=sd|title=Moorad agrees to purchase Triple-A club | author = Corey Brock \u2013 MLB.com|date= October 14, 2010|publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=October 15, 2010}}</ref> The team temporarily moved to southern Arizona and became the [[Tucson Padres]] while awaiting a new purpose-built stadium in their planned future home of [[Escondido, California]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tucsonsentinel.com/sports/report/121810_tucson_padres/tucsons-new-triple-a-team-announces-name-tucson-padres/ |date=December 18, 2010 |last=Smith |first=Dylan |title=Tucson's new Triple-A team announces name: Tucson Padres |newspaper=Tucson Sentinel}}</ref> After the 2013 season, the Padres instead moved to [[El Paso, Texas]] and became the [[El Paso Chihuahuas]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alameda |first1=Damien |title=Tucson Padres become El Paso Chihuahuas |url=https://www.kold.com/story/23763428/tucson-padres-become-el-paso-chihuahuas/ |website=kold.com |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=October 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Establishment of a Portland team: 1903\u20131918===\nOn December 10, 1902, Henry Harris, the owner of the [[California League]]'s San Francisco team announced that the [[Pacific Northwest League]] team from Portland, the [[Portland Webfoots]], and a new team from [[Seattle]] were joining with the California League to create the Pacific Coast League (PCL).<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web |title=Beavers History |url=http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/team4/page.jsp?ymd=20090213&content_id=509331&vkey=team4_t248&fext=.jsp&sid=t248 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100409153325/http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/team4/page.jsp?ymd=20090213&content_id=509331&vkey=team4_t248&fext=.jsp&sid=t248 |archivedate=2010-04-09 |website=minorleaguebaseball.com |publisher=Portland Beavers |accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Before the Portland franchise joined the PCL, the president of the Pacific Northwest League, Henry Lucas, was adamant in keeping the Portland franchise in his league.<ref name=\"The Deseret News\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Xt4oAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LkoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1099,3742661&dq=pacific+northwest+league+portland&hl=en |title=Merry Fight Over Baseball |author= |work=The Deseret News |publisher=The Deseret News |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> A team in the Pacific Northwest League was formed called the Portland Green Gages, which folded early in its first season. When the Portland PCL team first started playing, they were known as the '''Portland Browns'''. In their first season, classified as an [[independent league baseball|independent league]], the PCL featured six teams including the Browns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/league.cgi?id=13348 |title=1903 Pacific Coast League |author= |work=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> The Browns finished their first season fifth in the PCL.<ref name=\"history\"/> During the 1904 season, the Browns finished with a record of 79\u2013136.<ref name=\"history\"/> The 136 [[loss (baseball)|losses]] still stands as a record in the PCL for most losses by a team in a single season.<ref name=\"history\"/> Other records for that season include the most [[error (baseball)|errors]] in a season (669), and the lowest single-season team [[fielding percentage]] (.929).<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\nBefore the 1905 season, professional baseball player [[Walt McCredie]] and former [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House]] member from [[Washington (state)|Washington]] [[William Wallace McCredie|Judge William Wallace McCredie]] purchased the Portland franchise.<ref name=\"history\"/> The team was then renamed the '''Portland Giants''' and Walter McCredie was named the [[player-manager]] of the team.<ref name=\"history\"/> During the 1905 season, the PCL was re-classified as a Class-A league in minor league baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=29652 |title=1905 Portland Giants |author= |work=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> In 1906, the team was renamed the '''Portland Beavers''' after a newspaper contest was started to decide the new name of the team.<ref name=\"history\"/> That season, the Portland team won its first pennant in the PCL.<ref name=\"history\"/> Beavers player [[Mike Mitchell (baseball)|Mike Mitchell]] led the PCL in [[home run]]s with six, the fewest ever to lead the PCL. Mitchell also led the league in [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]].<ref name=\"history\"/> The 1906 Beavers were recognized as one of the [[The National Baseball Association's top 100 minor league teams|100 greatest minor league teams of all time]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.milb.com/milb/history/top100.jsp |title=Top 100 Teams |publisher=MiLB.com |date=2001 |accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Beavers finished last in 1907, and second in 1908 and 1909. In 1910, Portland won another pennant behind the pitching of [[Vean Gregg]] and [[Gene Krapp]]. Gregg finished the season with a 32\u201318 record and 14 [[shutouts in baseball|shutout]]s while Krapp had a 29\u201316 record for the season. Portland repeated as PCL champs in 1911 fielding four 20-game-winning pitchers. In 1912, Judge McCredie helped get a new 12,000-seat grandstand built at [[Vaughn Street Park]]. His obituary later read that the ballpark was \"the sensation of baseball, because it inaugurated a minor league precedent of providing individual grandstand seats, which fellow magnates called an extravagance and a dangerous innovation.\" The NAPBL made a change to league classifications in 1912, making Double-A the top tier. The PCL, and the Portland Beavers, moved into this new classification from the previous top tier Class A league.\n[[File:Walt McCredie, Portland Beavers.jpg|left|thumb|Former Beavers manager and part owner [[Judge McCredie|Walt McCredie]].]]\nDuring the 1910s, the Beavers developed some working relationships with other teams. From 1911 to 1914 the Portland Beavers had their own farm team which played in the [[Northwest League]] (renamed the Pacific Coast International League in 1918). The Class B team shared the use of Vaughn Street Park and was known as the Portland Pippins in 1911, but changed their name to the Portland Colts in 1912. During the 1914 season, the Colts moved to the Seattle area and finished their last season as the Ballard Pippins before folding. Portland also had an informal relationship with the [[Cleveland Indians]] through much of the 1910s that saw many future major league stars come through Portland to fine-tune their skills.\n\nPortland played well in 1913 and 1914, winning the pennant both seasons. Though the 1915 Beavers featured future Hall of Famer [[Stan Coveleski]], the team didn't fare too well, and started into a tailspin that would last for over a decade. The year also marked the end of their relationship with the Cleveland Indians. With America's entry into World War I, restrictions were placed on travel, such that the Beavers withdrew from the PCL for the 1918 season, playing instead in the Class B Pacific Coast International League. The team was known as the '''Portland Buckaroos''' and finished their shortened season (play was stopped on July 7 due to the war) in second place 1\u00bd games back of Seattle. Ironically, the PCL ceased play just a week later as they too were unable to continue play due to restrictions on travel.\n\nDue to the Beavers' withdrawal from the PCL, the league offered Sacramento a franchise to replace the Portland team, while the McCredies continued to own the baseball club in Portland. The new team in Sacramento was known as the [[Sacramento Solons|Sacramento Senators]], and could be considered a continuation of the original Portland Baseball Club.\n\n===Return to the Pacific Coast League: 1919\u20131972===\nWith the McCredies still at the helm, Portland was offered an expansion franchise and re-entered the PCL in 1919. The team finished in seventh place, only ahead of last-place Seattle who was also an expansion team that year. Portland finished in last place in 1920 and again in 1921. After the 1921 season, the McCredies sold the team to [[Walter Klepper]] who had been president of the Seattle team. Klepper brought in the 35-year old [[Jim Thorpe]], who played outfield and first base with the Beavers in 1922,<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34232994/jim_thorpe_is_purchased_by_portland/ \"Jim Thorpe is Purchased by Beavers,\"] ''Oregon Daily Journal'' [Portland], vol. 20, no. 291 (Feb. 10, 1922), p. 14.</ref> paying him a then-unheard of minor league salary of US$1,000 per month.\n\nIt wasn't long before Klepper was in the middle of a dispute with Baseball Commissioner [[Kenesaw Mountain Landis]]. Klepper had brought Seattle player-manager Bill Kenworthy down to manage the Beavers, only Seattle claimed Kenworthy was still under contract and that Klepper had tampered in the matter. Landis suspended Klepper until January 1, 1925, and declared Kenworthy ineligible to play or manage Portland until 1924.<ref name=100greatest>Weiss, Bill and Marshall Wright. [http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/milb/history/top100.jsp?idx=22  \"Historians Weiss, Wright Rank 100 Best Minor League Baseball Teams.\"] Minor League Baseball. 2001. Retrieved September 27, 2008.</ref> According to ''The Portland Beavers'', a book by Kip Carlson and Paul Andresen, \"The feisty Klepper went to court and had the decision overturned, supposedly the only time that Landis ever had a ruling reversed.\" Kenworthy did manage the Beavers in 1924, replacing popular [[player-manager]] [[Jim Middleton (baseball)|Jim Middleton]]. He was fired mid-season, though, as he was not able to generate support from the players.<ref name=100greatest/> The 1924 season was also noteworthy in that future Hall of Famer [[Mickey Cochrane]] played on the team.\n\nAfter 1924, the Beavers officially became a farm team for a major league team for the first time when [[Philadelphia Athletics]] owners [[John Shibe|John]] and [[Tom Shibe]] purchased the Beavers as well as [[Vaughn Street Park]]. Despite having [[Duffy Lewis]] on the team in 1925 (winning the PCL batting title), [[Elmer Smith (20th century outfielder)|Elmer Smith]] in 1926 and 1927 (leading the PCL in home runs in 1926 and all of minor league baseball in home runs in 1927), and [[Ike Boone]] in 1928, the Beavers continued to finish in the bottom half of the league.\n\nLongtime head groundskeeper Rocky Benevento started working for the Beavers in 1927. Benevento was so popular with the fans that they took up a collection for him in 1956 to send him to the [[World Series]]. Benevento retired at the end of the 1966 season and was given a new car. When Benevento died in 1969, ''[[The Oregonian]]'' stated, \"He adored kids...he loved baseball...and most of all he loved people.\" His funeral had an overflowing crowd that included [[Oregon Governor]] [[Tom McCall]]. Benevento stayed with the team 40 years, spanning 30 managerial changes and five ownership changes. While the former location of Vaughn Street Park is now a parking lot, there is a plaque honoring Benevento for his efforts in furthering baseball in Portland.\n\nIn 1929, the Beavers changed their name to the Portland Ducks, bearing a duck on their uniform, and were also occasionally known that year as the Portland Rosebuds. The name change didn't change the team's luck as they finished with a 90\u2013112 record. Long\u2013time radio broadcaster Rollie Truitt also joined the Beavers staff in 1929, and worked for the team for 35 years, spanning 28 managerial changes and five ownership changes. Truitt would later be known as the \"Dean of Pacific Coast League broadcasters.\" In 1930, the team reverted to the Beavers name, but would occasionally be referred to as the Ducks for over a decade. The highlight of the Beavers last place 1930 season was William Rhiel's [[unassisted triple play]], the last recorded in PCL history.\n\nIn 1931, team President Tom Turner bought the franchise from the Shibe brothers and the team took a turn for the positive. [[Ed Coleman (baseball)|Ed Coleman]] led the PCL in hits and runs batted in, and the team finished in third, winning 100 games. The team continued to improve in 1932, winning Portland its first pennant since 1914. The team finished second in 1933. Turner brought Walter McCredie back to manager the team in 1934, but he died early in the season and the team fell to the bottom half of the league.\n\n[[File:Portland Beavers and Hollywood Stars pregame.jpeg|thumb|left|The Portland Beavers and [[Hollywood Stars]] managers before a game performing a comedy routine ([[Gilmore Field]] in the 1940s)]]\nFollowing the 1934 season, E.J. Shefter bought the team from Turner. The team improved in 1935, finishing one game over .500, and then won the pennant in 1936, finishing 1\u00bd games over runner-up [[Oakland Oaks (PCL)|Oakland]], then winning the postseason series to capture the crown. In 1937, the Beavers finished in fourth place, but made it to the playoffs defeating San Francisco in the first round before losing to the San Diego team featuring a young [[Ted Williams]]. The team finished sixth in 1938 before finishing in last place in 1939\u20131942. The 1940 team was so bad, finishing 56\u2013122, that they were still 25 games behind the seventh-place team (the league had eight teams at that time).\n\nIn 1943, William Klepper, with partner George Norgan buying a minority share, purchased the Beavers. The team came back that season with their first winning record since 1937. The management of the team began referring to the team as the \"Lucky Beavers\" and Vaughn Street Park was known as \"Lucky Beaver Stadium.\"  With the United States firmly involved in World War II, local radio station [[KXL (AM)|KXL]] sold over $300,000 in war bonds in 1943 to fund the building of a bomber for the war that would be dubbed \"The Lucky Beaver.\" Due to U.S. involvement in the war, the available pool of baseball players in the nation was ravaged. Somehow, the Beavers still moved up in the league, finishing second in 1944. In 1945 the Beavers brought another pennant to Portland being skippered by player-manager [[Marv Owen]]. Despite winning the pennant, the team lost to San Francisco in the first round of the playoffs. To commemorate Portland's 1945 pennant win, Portland held a banquet at the Multnomah Hotel (now the downtown Portland Embassy Suites). [[Oregon Governor]] [[Earl Snell]] presented a commemorative watch and gold and diamond [[Championship ring|ring]] to each player at the banquet. The watches were given to the players due to [[L. H. Gregory]] of ''The Oregonian'' requesting fans to donate money to a fund for the purpose. Gregory did this because he felt it was not right that no memento was given to the players from the 1936 championship team. Following the 1945 season, Norgan purchased Klepper's share of the team becoming the team's new owner.\n\nIn 1946, the Beavers fell to the bottom half of the league, finishing in seventh place, 41 games out of first. In 1947 [[Eddie Basinski]] joined the Beavers, and they finished third, losing to the [[Los Angeles Angels (PCL)|Los Angeles Angels]] in the first round of the playoffs. The team drew, up to then, a team record of 421,000 fans that season. This record would stand for the Beavers until the 2001 season when Triple-A Baseball returned to Portland.\n\nIn 1948, the team finish fifth, followed by a sixth-place finish in 1949. The 1949 season began the [[Baseball color line|integration]] of the Pacific Coast League as [[Frankie Austin]] and Luis Marquez became Beavers. Beginning with the 1950 season, the Beavers finished fourth for four straight years. [[Clay Hopper]], who had been [[Jackie Robinson]]'s manager when he played for the [[Montreal Royals]] in 1946, was named the team's manager in 1952. This year also marked the first year the Pacific Coast League was classified by the NAPBL as an \"open league.\" The open league was a step above Triple-A, and was an attempt by the Pacific Coast League to be considered the third [[Major League Baseball|major league]].\n\nPlans for a new ballpark were announced by the team in 1953. Originally the team planned to build a new stadium at 82nd and Holgate in Southeast Portland. Due to the [[Korean War]], among other issues, the stadium never came to fruition. In 1954 the team dropped again to the bottom of the league. After the 1954 season the team went up for sale to the community via [[Stock|public stock]], which resulted in 2,400 new owners for the 1955 season. With the change the Beavers rose to fifth place, only nine games back of first.\n\nIn 1956, the Beavers left the now-demolished Vaughn Street Park to move into 25,000-seat [[Multnomah Stadium]], today's Providence Park. Throughout most of the 1960s, the Beavers were the Triple-A affiliate of the [[American League]] Cleveland Indians, nurturing such future stars as [[Sam McDowell|\"Sudden\" Sam McDowell]], [[Lou Piniella|Lou \"Mad Dog\" Piniella]], and [[Luis Tiant|Luis \"El Gigante\" Tiant]]. Later major league affiliations included the [[Minnesota Twins]] and [[Philadelphia Phillies]].\n\nIn 1961, the Beavers signed the 56-year-old [[Satchel Paige]]. He pitched 25 innings for the Beavers, striking out 19 and giving up 18 earned runs without recording a decision.\n\nFollowing the 1972 season, principal owner Bill Cutler moved the team northeast to [[Spokane Indians|Spokane]], who had lost their PCL team to [[Albuquerque Dukes|Albuquerque]] after the 1971 season. For the next five seasons, Portland was in the [[Short season|short-season]] [[Minor League Baseball#Class A-Short Season|Class A]] [[Northwest League]] (NWL) with the independent and non-conforming [[Portland Mavericks]], owned by actor [[Bing Russell]].\n\n===Triple-A returns to Portland: 1978\u20131993===\nThe PCL expanded in 1978 and added a new team in Portland, calling themselves the Beavers, displacing the single-A Mavericks. The new Beavers played in [[Civic Stadium (Portland, Oregon)|Civic Stadium]] for sixteen seasons through 1993. In 1983, the Beavers won the PCL pennant, the first for Portland in 47 years. Though tied for third overall during the regular season,<ref name=br83pclss>{{cite news |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/league.cgi?id=e57bc74c |publisher=Baseball Reference |title=1983 PCL season |accessdate=November 7, 2015}}</ref> the Beavers won the second half division title by four games,<ref name=pclfssp2>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Rm8RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PeIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4532%2C502464 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |title=Pacific Coast League: final standings |date=September 2, 1983 |page=6D }}</ref> defeated first-half winner [[Edmonton Trappers]] in four games (3\u20131) to take the Northern Division title,<ref name=mlplyff>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=S28RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PeIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2348%2C1614293 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |title=Baseball: Minor League playoffs |date=September 7, 1983 |page=4B }}</ref> then swept the three-time defending champion [[Albuquerque Dukes]] in three games in the finals to capture the league championship.<ref name=bvcpttl>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=o_lVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PeIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6550%2C2734607|newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |title=Beavers capture title with 8-7 triumph |agency=Associated Press |date=September 11, 1983 |page=12B }}</ref><ref name=pclfnl83>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=o_lVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PeIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6333%2C2726225|newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |title=Baseball: Minor League playoffs |date=September 11, 1983 |page=10B }}</ref> As PCL champs in 1983, the Beavers participated in the first [[Triple-A World Series]], a three-team round-robin competition in [[Cardinal Stadium|Louisville]] with the champions of the [[International League]] and  the [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]].<ref name=tpawsontp>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SPAaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PUcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5269%2C2399185 |newspaper=Daily News |location=Bowling Green, Kentucky |agency=Associated Press |title=Triple-A World Series on tap |date=September 15, 1983 |page=3B }}</ref> Each team played the others twice and it was won by the [[Norfolk Tides|Tidewater Tides]] of the IL with three wins. Portland was second, splitting with both teams, and the [[Denver Bears]] were 1\u20133.<ref name=twwtaws>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3NghAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7Z0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=6403%2C4477209 |newspaper=Times Daily |location=Florence, Alabama |title=Tidewater wins Triple-A Series |date=September 20, 1983 |page=2C }}</ref>\n\n[[File:PGEPark.jpg|thumb|Vince Sinisi on deck in 2008.]]\nA decade later, Beavers owner [[Joe Buzas]] moved the team after the 1993 season east to [[Salt Lake City]],<ref name=ntbfslbv>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xoVTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gYYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3901%2C2151925 |newspaper=The Bulletin |location=Bend, Oregon |last=Baum |first=Bob |title=No turning back for Portland's Salt Lake-bound Beavers |date=September 3, 1993 |page=D2 }}</ref> where they became the [[Salt Lake Buzz]] in 1994 in a [[Smith's Ballpark|brand new ballpark]]. The team was renamed the Stingers in 2001, and have been the [[Salt Lake Bees|Bees]] since the 2006 season. For the first time since 1894, Portland was without professional baseball.\n\nAfter being without a team in 1994, the Class A [[Bend Rockies|Rockies]] of the Northwest League relocated from [[Bend, Oregon|Bend]] for the 1995 season.<ref name=brmotpd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=K8IjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BtEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2913%2C1417835 |newspaper=Moscow-Pullman Daily News |location=Idaho-Washington |title=Bend Rockies baseball moves over to Portland |agency=Associated Press |date=September 14, 1994 |page=3B }}</ref> The [[Portland Rockies]] played in the Rose City for the next six seasons and served an important role for the city, whose demand for a major league team was growing. They were league champions in 1997. Portland's support for the Rockies paved the way for the return of the Triple-A PCL in 2001.<ref name=fflock>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_UZWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=C-sDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6586%2C5993015 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |last=Fears |first=Shannon |title=Fans flock to Rockies games |date=July 23, 1995 |page=3E }}</ref>\n\n===The Beavers return: 2001\u20132010===\nFollowing the 2000 season, the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] and [[San Diego Padres]] swapped Triple-A affiliates. The [[Albuquerque Dukes]] (a charter franchise of the PCL in 1903 as the [[Los Angeles Angels (PCL)|Los Angeles Angels]] from 1903 to 1958, and later the [[Spokane Indians]] from 1958 to 1971) moved to Portland and became the Beavers, as the Padres' top affiliate. As part of the relocation agreement, Civic Stadium was renovated in 2000 and renamed [[PGE Park]]. The Las Vegas Stars (the 1919\u201372 Beavers) became the Dodgers' top affiliate; they were renamed the [[Las Vegas 51s|51s]] for 2001. The single-A Portland Rockies moved up the [[Columbia River]] to [[Pasco, Washington|Pasco]] and became the [[Tri-City Dust Devils]] in 2001.\n\nIn 2007, owner [[Merritt Paulson]] announced that he was considering changing the name of the team to prevent confusion with the [[Oregon State Beavers|Oregon State University]] teams from [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]].<ref>[http://www.oregonlive.com/sports/oregonian/index.ssf?/base/sports/1184901921229010.xml&coll=7 \"Merritt Paulson, new owner of the Beavers and Timbers, stages a 'Grand Reopening' tonight at PGE Park.\"] ''The Oregonian''. Retrieved July 20, 2007.</ref> Possible new names and logos were unveiled, and a vote was staged on the team website. \"Portland Beavers\" won the contest,<ref>[http://www.portlandbeavers.com/news/press/index.html?article_id=1011 \"Beavers to keep historic nickname.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505232445/http://www.portlandbeavers.com/news/press/index.html?article_id=1011 |date=May 5, 2009 }} Portland Beavers. 2008. Retrieved February 22, 2008.</ref> and the team unveiled new logos and colors on January 29, 2008.<ref>[http://www.portlandbeavers.com/news/press/index.html?article_id=1040 \"Beavers unveil new logo, uniforms.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080418064642/http://www.portlandbeavers.com/news/press/index.html?article_id=1040 |date=April 18, 2008 }} Portland Beavers. 2008. Retrieved January 30, 2008.</ref> The Beavers emphasized their connection to the three prior franchises with the notation \"Est. 1903\" on their primary logo. The team also brought back the name \"Lucky Beavers\" as part of a sleeve patch on their alternate jersey.\n\n====Hunt for new stadium and team sale: 2009\u20132010====\nIn 2009, the city of Portland was awarded a [[Major League Soccer|Major League Soccer (MLS)]] expansion franchise for 2011, to be named the [[Portland Timbers (MLS)|Portland Timbers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_news.jsp?ymd=20090320&content_id=228140&vkey=pr_mls&fext=.jsp |publisher=mlsnet.com |title=MLS awards 18th franchise to Portland |date=March 20, 2009 |accessdate=March 20, 2009 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100319020353/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_news.jsp?ymd=20090320&content_id=228140&vkey=pr_mls&fext=.jsp |archivedate=March 19, 2010 }}</ref> The Portland City Council approved a $31 million agreement to renovate PGE Park to a soccer- and football-only stadium, with the condition that [[New Portland ballpark|a new ballpark be built in Portland]] for the Beavers by 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2010/02/portland_city_council_approves_1.html |title=Portland City Council approves soccer deal for PGE Park |author=James Mayer |date=February 3, 2010 |work=The Oregonian |publisher=oregonlive.com |accessdate=February 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Veterans Memorial Coliseum in 2013 - Portland, Oregon.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Memorial Coliseum (Portland)|Memorial Coliseum]] in the [[Rose Quarter]] was an original site for the proposed ballpark; however, it met public opposition.]]\nInitial plans called for the new ballpark to be built at the site currently occupied by the [[Memorial Coliseum (Portland)|Memorial Coliseum]], which would have been torn down,<ref name=mlb>{{cite web|url=http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090311&content_id=523032&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp|date=March 11, 2009|title=Beavers' new stadium a step closer|accessdate=April 24, 2009|publisher=minorleaguebaseball.com| last=Jackson|first=Josh}}</ref> but public outcry about demolishing a Portland landmark led Portland mayor [[Sam Adams (Oregon politician)|Sam Adams]] to propose a second site in the [[Rose Quarter]] area north of Memorial Coliseum. The site, however, proved to be too small.<ref name=frank>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2009/04/saving_portlands_memorial_coli.html|title=Saving Portland's Memorial Coliseum may cost taxpayers|date=April 22, 2009|accessdate=April 24, 2009|last=Frank|first=Ryan|author2=Mark Larabee|work=[[The Oregonian]]}}</ref> Another location on the site of [[Walker Stadium (baseball)|Charles D. Walker Stadium]] in the [[Lents, Portland, Oregon|Lents]] neighborhood in southeast Portland was also rejected due to objections from neighbors.<ref name=larabee062209>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/oregonian/index.ssf?/base/news/124572753115390.xml&coll=7|title=Lents Park out as Beavers' home|last=Larrabee|first=Mark|date=June 22, 2009|accessdate=June 25, 2009|work=[[The Oregonian]]}}</ref>  That was until the [[Portland Pickles]] collegiate wood bat team began play in 2016 at Walker Stadium.\n\nIn June 2009, the Portland City Council voted to separate the soccer and baseball projects, allowing renovation of PGE Park to proceed without completed plans for a baseball stadium in place.<ref name=larabee062409>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2009/06/major_league_soccer_plan_still.html|title=Major League Soccer plan still alive as Portland council endorses latest plan|date=June 24, 2009|accessdate=June 25, 2009|last=Larabee|first=Mark|work=[[The Oregonian]]}}</ref> Other locations in the Portland area were considered for the ballpark, including a vacant terminal at the [[Port of Portland (Oregon)|Port of Portland]], [[Delta Park]], the [[Portland Metropolitan Exposition Center|Portland Expo Center]], [[Portland Meadows]], the [[Westwood Corporation Heliport]] site, a building owned by [[Portland Public Schools (Oregon)|Portland Public Schools]] near the Rose Quarter, and suburban locations in [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]], [[Clackamas, Oregon|Clackamas]], and [[Vancouver, Washington]].<ref name=larabee062209/><ref name=beaverton>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2009/07/beaverton_in_running_for_new_b.html|title=Beaverton in running for new Beavers baseball stadium|date=July 21, 2009|accessdate=July 23, 2009|last=Larabee|first=Mark|work=[[The Oregonian]]}}</ref><ref name=schmidt>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.oregonlive.com/washingtoncounty/index.ssf/2009/09/theres_no_crying_over_baseball.html\n| title      = Clackamas County added to list of possible future sites for Portland Beavers.\n| last       = Schmidt\n| first      = Brad\n| date       = September 3, 2009\n| work       = [[The Oregonian]]\n| accessdate = September 13, 2009\n}}</ref><ref name=brettman>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.oregonlive.com/clark-county/index.ssf/2009/11/vancouver_now_interested_in_wooing_portland_beavers.html\n| title      = Vancouver now interested in wooing Portland Beavers\n| last       = Brettman\n| first      = Allan\n| date       = November 10, 2009\n| work       = [[The Oregonian]]\n| accessdate = April 6, 2010\n}}</ref> None of these sites progressed past initial discussions.\n\nWith no suitable Portland location available, in July 2010, Paulson announced that he was putting the team up for sale and relocation.<ref name=fentress>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.oregonlive.com/pbeavers/index.ssf/2010/07/post_3.html\n| title      = Portland Beavers owner Merritt Paulson prepared to sell team; several cities interested\n| last       = Fentress\n| first      = Aaron\n| date       = July 28, 2010\n| accessdate = July 28, 2010\n| work       = [[The Oregonian]]\n}}</ref> Padres owner [[Jeff Moorad]] formed a group to buy the team and talked of moving its home games to the [[Lake Elsinore Diamond]] in [[Lake Elsinore, California]] until a new stadium in Escondido could be built.<ref name=maffei>{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/minors/business-beat/2010/2610406.html\n| publisher  = Baseball America\n| title      = Displaced Triple-A club likely to share Lake Elsinore ballpark in 2011\n| first1     = John\n| last1      = Maffei\n| first2     = Josh\n| last2      = Leventhal\n| date       = July 26, 2010\n| accessdate = July 28, 2010\n}}</ref> Eventually, the group decided to move the team temporarily to Tucson in 2011, rename them the [[Tucson Padres]], with plans to move again to Escondido when a new ballpark was built.<ref name=escondido>{{cite web|title=Council votes to bring baseball to Escondido|last=Breier|first=Michelle|author2=J. Harry Jones|date=December 15, 2010|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2010/dec/15/escondido-council-approves-moving-ahead-ballpark|accessdate= December 20, 2010}}</ref> The plans in Escondido failed, and the team was sold again; they moved to west Texas prior to the 2014 season and became the [[El Paso Chihuahuas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140502&content_id=74058844&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_farmalmc&sid=milb|title=Greetings from Southwest University Park, home of the El Paso Chihuahuas - MiLB.com News - The Official Site of Minor League Baseball|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe Portland area was without minor league baseball in 2011 and 2012. After the 2012 season, the NWL [[Yakima Bears]] relocated to a [[Ron Tonkin Field|new 4,500-seat stadium]] in the northwest suburb of [[Hillsboro, Oregon|Hillsboro]] and became the [[Hillsboro Hops]]. The Hops won the NWL title in 2014 and again in 2015, averaging more than 3,700 in attendance for 38 regular season home games.<ref name=nwlatt15>{{cite web |url=http://www.milb.com/milb/stats/stats.jsp?y=2015&t=l_att&lid=126&sid=l126 |publisher=Northwest League |title=attendance |accessdate=November 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n[[File:091306 106 Craig Breslow.jpg|thumb|[[Craig Breslow]]]]\n<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n*[[Eddie Basinski]], infielder, inductee in [[Pacific Coast League Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Kyle Blanks]], outfielder\n*[[Craig Breslow]], pitcher\n*[[Mickey Cochrane]], Hall of Fame catcher\n*[[Shawn Estes]], pitcher, pitched in 12 games of rehab between 2006\u20132008\n*[[Ray Fosse]], catcher, 1967\u20131968\n*[[George Freese]], infielder\n*[[Josh Geer]], pitcher\n*[[Ram\u00f3n Hern\u00e1ndez]], catcher, played 7 games of rehab\n*[[Sam McDowell]], pitcher, 8-0 1964\n*[[Satchel Paige]], pitcher, 5 starts, 2.88 ERA\n*[[Lou Piniella]], outfielder, 1964\n*[[Aaron Poreda]], pitcher\n*[[Jeff Richards (baseball player/actor)|Jeff Richards]], a.k.a. Dick Taylor, shortstop; then became an actor \n*[[Richie Scheinblum]], All Star outfielder\n*[[George Stone (outfielder)|George Stone]], AL batting title champion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=stone-003geo |title=George Stone Minor Leagues Statistics & History |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n*[[Luis Tiant]], pitcher, 15-1 1964\n*[[Jim Thorpe]], outfielder and first baseman, 1922\n*[[Ryan Webb]], pitcher\n\n==See also==\n*[[:Category:Portland Beavers players|Portland Beavers players]] \n*[[History of baseball in Portland, Oregon]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* Carlson, Kip & Andersen, Paul. ''The Portland Beavers.'' Arcadia Publishing, Charleston, South Carolina, 2004. {{ISBN|0-7385-3266-5}}\n* O'Neal, Bill. ''The Pacific Coast League 1903\u20131988.'' Eakin Press, Austin TX, 1990. {{ISBN|0-89015-776-6}}.\n* Snelling, Dennis. ''The Pacific Coast League: A Statistical History, 1903\u20131957''. McFarland & Company, Inc., Jefferson, North Carolina, 1995. {{ISBN|0-7864-0045-5}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?city=Portland&state=OR&country=US&empty=0 Baseball Reference] \u2013 Portland teams\n\n{{Baseball teams based in Portland, Oregon}}\n\n[[Category:Portland Beavers| ]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Dodgers minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Detroit Tigers minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Athletics minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Milwaukee Brewers minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Twins minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Athletics minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:San Diego Padres minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Cardinals minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:1903 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Sports teams in Portland, Oregon|Beavers]]\n[[Category:2010 disestablishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Baseball teams established in 1903]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs disestablished in 2010]]\n\n[[fr:Portland Beavers]]\n[[ja:\u30dd\u30fc\u30c8\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9\u30fb\u30d3\u30fc\u30d0\u30fc\u30ba]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n| name = Portland Beavers\n| firstseason = 1903 \n| lastseason = 2010\n| allyears = 1903\u20131917, 1919\u20131972, 1978\u20131993, 2001\u20132010\n| city = Portland, Oregon\n| logo = PortlandBeaversLogo2008.png\n| caplogo = Portlandbeaverscap2008.PNG\n| past class level = {{plainlist|\n*[[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] (1946\u20131951, 1958\u20131972,<br>1978\u20131993, 2001\u20132010)\n*[[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] (1902, 1918)\n*[[Independent league baseball|Independent]] (1903)\n*[[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] (1904\u20131911)\n*[[Double-A (baseball)|Double-A]] (now [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]])<br>(1912\u20131917, 1919\u20131945)\n*[[Minor League Baseball#Open|Open]] (1952\u20131957)\n}}\n| league = [[Pacific Coast League]] (1903\u20131917,<br>1919\u20131972, 1978\u20131993, 2001\u20132010)\n| conference = Pacific Conference\n| division = North Division\n| past league = \n| pastmajorleague = {{plainlist|\n*[[San Diego Padres]] (2001\u20132010)\n*[[Minnesota Twins]] (1987\u20131993)\n*[[Philadelphia Phillies]] (1983\u20131986)\n*[[Pittsburgh Pirates]] (1979\u20131982)\n*[[Cleveland Indians]] (1972, 1978)\n*[[Minnesota Twins]] (1971)\n*[[Milwaukee Brewers]] (1970)\n*[[Cleveland Indians]] (1964\u20131969)\n*[[Kansas City Athletics]] (1962\u20131963)\n*[[St. Louis Cardinals]] (1961)\n*[[Kansas City Athletics]] (1959)\n*[[Chicago Cubs]] (1957\u20131958)\n*[[Brooklyn Dodgers]] (1956)\n*[[Detroit Tigers]] (1935)\n*[[Philadelphia Athletics]] (1925\u20131932)\n*[[Cleveland Indians]] (unofficial)<br>(1910\u20131915)\n}}\n|mascot = Lucky (2008-2010)<br /> Boomer (2001-2007)<br /> Round Tripper (1979-1994)\n\n| pastnames = {{plainlist|\n*Portland Beavers\n*Portland Ducks (1929)\n*Portland Buckaroos (1918)\n*Portland Giants (1905)\n*Portland Browns (1903\u20131904)\n*Portland Webfoots (1902\u20131903)\n}}\n| pastparks = {{plainlist|\n*[[PGE Park]] (1956\u20132010)\n*[[Vaughn Street Park]] (1901\u20131955)\n}}\n| classchamps = \n| leaguechamps = 1901, 1906, 1910, 1911, 1913, 1914, 1936, 1945, 1983\n| conferencechamps =  \n| divisionchamps = 1965, 1983, 1993, 2004\n}}\nThe '''Portland Beavers''' was the name of separate [[minor league baseball]] teams, which represented [[Portland, Oregon]], in the [[Pacific Coast League]] (PCL). The team was established in 1903, the first year of the PCL.\n\n==Franchise history==\nMany baseball teams have been known as the Portland Beavers; the most recent club, which began operating in 2001, recognized the history of all previous incarnations as its own, stating it was established in 1903, the same year the Pacific Coast League was established. The \"Beavers\" originated in 1906 following a newspaper contest to rename the existing Portland team that had been created in 1901 when a group of Portland businessmen founded the Portland Baseball Club.\n\nAlong with the [[Los Angeles Angels (PCL)|Los Angeles Angels]], [[Oakland Oaks (PCL)|Oakland Oaks]], [[Sacramento Solons]], [[San Francisco Seals (baseball)|San Francisco Seals]], and [[Seattle Rainiers]], a Portland Beavers club was a charter member of the Pacific Coast League in 1903. Portland and [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] were the only two charter cities that had a team in the PCL as of 2010, the other cities having been taken over by [[Major League Baseball]] franchises.\n\nFollowing the 2010 season, the Beavers were placed for sale and relocation because of the lack of a suitable stadium in Portland, as [[PGE Park]] was being remodeled into a soccer-only configuration for [[Major League Soccer]]'s 2011 expansion [[Portland Timbers]]. In 2010, the Beavers were sold to Jeff Moorad, owner of the [[San Diego Padres]].<ref name=\"tucson\">{{cite web|url=http://sandiego.padres.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101014&content_id=15635170&vkey=news_sd&c_id=sd|title=Moorad agrees to purchase Triple-A club | author = Corey Brock \u2013 MLB.com|date= October 14, 2010|publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=October 15, 2010}}</ref> The team temporarily moved to southern Arizona and became the [[Tucson Padres]] while awaiting a new purpose-built stadium in their planned future home of [[Escondido, California]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tucsonsentinel.com/sports/report/121810_tucson_padres/tucsons-new-triple-a-team-announces-name-tucson-padres/ |date=December 18, 2010 |last=Smith |first=Dylan |title=Tucson's new Triple-A team announces name: Tucson Padres |newspaper=Tucson Sentinel}}</ref> After the 2013 season, the Padres instead moved to [[El Paso, Texas]] and became the [[El Paso Chihuahuas]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alameda |first1=Damien |title=Tucson Padres become El Paso Chihuahuas |url=https://www.kold.com/story/23763428/tucson-padres-become-el-paso-chihuahuas/ |website=kold.com |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=October 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Establishment of a Portland team: 1903\u20131918===\nOn December 10, 1902, Henry Harris, the owner of the [[California League]]'s San Francisco team announced that the [[Pacific Northwest League]] team from Portland, the [[Portland Webfoots]], and a new team from [[Seattle]] were joining with the California League to create the Pacific Coast League (PCL).<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web |title=Beavers History |url=http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/team4/page.jsp?ymd=20090213&content_id=509331&vkey=team4_t248&fext=.jsp&sid=t248 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100409153325/http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/team4/page.jsp?ymd=20090213&content_id=509331&vkey=team4_t248&fext=.jsp&sid=t248 |archivedate=2010-04-09 |website=minorleaguebaseball.com |publisher=Portland Beavers |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/team4/page.jsp?ymd=20090213&content_id=509331&vkey=team4_t248&fext=.jsp&sid=t248 |archivedate=April 9, 2010}}</ref> Before the Portland franchise joined the PCL, the president of the Pacific Northwest League, Henry Lucas, was adamant in keeping the Portland franchise in his league.<ref name=\"The Deseret News\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Xt4oAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LkoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1099,3742661&dq=pacific+northwest+league+portland&hl=en |title=Merry Fight Over Baseball |author= |work=The Deseret News |publisher=The Deseret News |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> A team in the Pacific Northwest League was formed called the Portland Green Gages, which folded early in its first season. When the Portland PCL team first started playing, they were known as the '''Portland Browns'''. In their first season, classified as an [[independent league baseball|independent league]], the PCL featured six teams including the Browns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/league.cgi?id=13348 |title=1903 Pacific Coast League |author= |work=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> The Browns finished their first season fifth in the PCL.<ref name=\"history\"/> During the 1904 season, the Browns finished with a record of 79\u2013136.<ref name=\"history\"/> The 136 [[loss (baseball)|losses]] still stands as a record in the PCL for most losses by a team in a single season.<ref name=\"history\"/> Other records for that season include the most [[error (baseball)|errors]] in a season (669), and the lowest single-season team [[fielding percentage]] (.929).<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\nBefore the 1905 season, professional baseball player [[Walt McCredie]] and former [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House]] member from [[Washington (state)|Washington]] [[William Wallace McCredie|Judge William Wallace McCredie]] purchased the Portland franchise.<ref name=\"history\"/> The team was then renamed the '''Portland Giants''' and Walter McCredie was named the [[player-manager]] of the team.<ref name=\"history\"/> During the 1905 season, the PCL was re-classified as a Class-A league in minor league baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=29652 |title=1905 Portland Giants |author= |work=Baseball-Reference |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> In 1906, the team was renamed the '''Portland Beavers''' after a newspaper contest was started to decide the new name of the team.<ref name=\"history\"/> That season, the Portland team won its first pennant in the PCL.<ref name=\"history\"/> Beavers player [[Mike Mitchell (baseball)|Mike Mitchell]] led the PCL in [[home run]]s with six, the fewest ever to lead the PCL. Mitchell also led the league in [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]].<ref name=\"history\"/> The 1906 Beavers were recognized as one of the [[The National Baseball Association's top 100 minor league teams|100 greatest minor league teams of all time]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.milb.com/milb/history/top100.jsp |title=Top 100 Teams |publisher=MiLB.com |date=2001 |accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Beavers finished last in 1907, and second in 1908 and 1909. In 1910, Portland won another pennant behind the pitching of [[Vean Gregg]] and [[Gene Krapp]]. Gregg finished the season with a 32\u201318 record and 14 [[shutouts in baseball|shutout]]s while Krapp had a 29\u201316 record for the season. Portland repeated as PCL champs in 1911 fielding four 20-game-winning pitchers. In 1912, Judge McCredie helped get a new 12,000-seat grandstand built at [[Vaughn Street Park]]. His obituary later read that the ballpark was \"the sensation of baseball, because it inaugurated a minor league precedent of providing individual grandstand seats, which fellow magnates called an extravagance and a dangerous innovation.\" The NAPBL made a change to league classifications in 1912, making Double-A the top tier. The PCL, and the Portland Beavers, moved into this new classification from the previous top tier Class A league.\n[[File:Walt McCredie, Portland Beavers.jpg|left|thumb|Former Beavers manager and part owner [[Judge McCredie|Walt McCredie]].]]\nDuring the 1910s, the Beavers developed some working relationships with other teams. From 1911 to 1914 the Portland Beavers had their own farm team which played in the [[Northwest League]] (renamed the Pacific Coast International League in 1918). The Class B team shared the use of Vaughn Street Park and was known as the Portland Pippins in 1911, but changed their name to the Portland Colts in 1912. During the 1914 season, the Colts moved to the Seattle area and finished their last season as the Ballard Pippins before folding. Portland also had an informal relationship with the [[Cleveland Indians]] through much of the 1910s that saw many future major league stars come through Portland to fine-tune their skills.\n\nPortland played well in 1913 and 1914, winning the pennant both seasons. Though the 1915 Beavers featured future Hall of Famer [[Stan Coveleski]], the team didn't fare too well, and started into a tailspin that would last for over a decade. The year also marked the end of their relationship with the Cleveland Indians. With America's entry into World War I, restrictions were placed on travel, such that the Beavers withdrew from the PCL for the 1918 season, playing instead in the Class B Pacific Coast International League. The team was known as the '''Portland Buckaroos''' and finished their shortened season (play was stopped on July 7 due to the war) in second place 1\u00bd games back of Seattle. Ironically, the PCL ceased play just a week later as they too were unable to continue play due to restrictions on travel.\n\nDue to the Beavers' withdrawal from the PCL, the league offered Sacramento a franchise to replace the Portland team, while the McCredies continued to own the baseball club in Portland. The new team in Sacramento was known as the [[Sacramento Solons|Sacramento Senators]], and could be considered a continuation of the original Portland Baseball Club.\n\n===Return to the Pacific Coast League: 1919\u20131972===\nWith the McCredies still at the helm, Portland was offered an expansion franchise and re-entered the PCL in 1919. The team finished in seventh place, only ahead of last-place Seattle who was also an expansion team that year. Portland finished in last place in 1920 and again in 1921. After the 1921 season, the McCredies sold the team to [[Walter Klepper]] who had been president of the Seattle team. Klepper brought in the 35-year old [[Jim Thorpe]], who played outfield and first base with the Beavers in 1922,<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34232994/jim_thorpe_is_purchased_by_portland/ \"Jim Thorpe is Purchased by Beavers,\"] ''Oregon Daily Journal'' [Portland], vol. 20, no. 291 (Feb. 10, 1922), p. 14.</ref> paying him a then-unheard of minor league salary of US$1,000 per month.\n\nIt wasn't long before Klepper was in the middle of a dispute with Baseball Commissioner [[Kenesaw Mountain Landis]]. Klepper had brought Seattle player-manager Bill Kenworthy down to manage the Beavers, only Seattle claimed Kenworthy was still under contract and that Klepper had tampered in the matter. Landis suspended Klepper until January 1, 1925, and declared Kenworthy ineligible to play or manage Portland until 1924.<ref name=100greatest>Weiss, Bill and Marshall Wright. [http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/milb/history/top100.jsp?idx=22  \"Historians Weiss, Wright Rank 100 Best Minor League Baseball Teams.\"] Minor League Baseball. 2001. Retrieved September 27, 2008.</ref> According to ''The Portland Beavers'', a book by Kip Carlson and Paul Andresen, \"The feisty Klepper went to court and had the decision overturned, supposedly the only time that Landis ever had a ruling reversed.\" Kenworthy did manage the Beavers in 1924, replacing popular [[player-manager]] [[Jim Middleton (baseball)|Jim Middleton]]. He was fired mid-season, though, as he was not able to generate support from the players.<ref name=100greatest/> The 1924 season was also noteworthy in that future Hall of Famer [[Mickey Cochrane]] played on the team.\n\nAfter 1924, the Beavers officially became a farm team for a major league team for the first time when [[Philadelphia Athletics]] owners [[John Shibe|John]] and [[Tom Shibe]] purchased the Beavers as well as [[Vaughn Street Park]]. Despite having [[Duffy Lewis]] on the team in 1925 (winning the PCL batting title), [[Elmer Smith (20th century outfielder)|Elmer Smith]] in 1926 and 1927 (leading the PCL in home runs in 1926 and all of minor league baseball in home runs in 1927), and [[Ike Boone]] in 1928, the Beavers continued to finish in the bottom half of the league.\n\nLongtime head groundskeeper Rocky Benevento started working for the Beavers in 1927. Benevento was so popular with the fans that they took up a collection for him in 1956 to send him to the [[World Series]]. Benevento retired at the end of the 1966 season and was given a new car. When Benevento died in 1969, ''[[The Oregonian]]'' stated, \"He adored kids...he loved baseball...and most of all he loved people.\" His funeral had an overflowing crowd that included [[Oregon Governor]] [[Tom McCall]]. Benevento stayed with the team 40 years, spanning 30 managerial changes and five ownership changes. While the former location of Vaughn Street Park is now a parking lot, there is a plaque honoring Benevento for his efforts in furthering baseball in Portland.\n\nIn 1929, the Beavers changed their name to the Portland Ducks, bearing a duck on their uniform, and were also occasionally known that year as the Portland Rosebuds. The name change didn't change the team's luck as they finished with a 90\u2013112 record. Long\u2013time radio broadcaster Rollie Truitt also joined the Beavers staff in 1929, and worked for the team for 35 years, spanning 28 managerial changes and five ownership changes. Truitt would later be known as the \"Dean of Pacific Coast League broadcasters.\" In 1930, the team reverted to the Beavers name, but would occasionally be referred to as the Ducks for over a decade. The highlight of the Beavers last place 1930 season was William Rhiel's [[unassisted triple play]], the last recorded in PCL history.\n\nIn 1931, team President Tom Turner bought the franchise from the Shibe brothers and the team took a turn for the positive. [[Ed Coleman (baseball)|Ed Coleman]] led the PCL in hits and runs batted in, and the team finished in third, winning 100 games. The team continued to improve in 1932, winning Portland its first pennant since 1914. The team finished second in 1933. Turner brought Walter McCredie back to manager the team in 1934, but he died early in the season and the team fell to the bottom half of the league.\n\n[[File:Portland Beavers and Hollywood Stars pregame.jpeg|thumb|left|The Portland Beavers and [[Hollywood Stars]] managers before a game performing a comedy routine ([[Gilmore Field]] in the 1940s)]]\nFollowing the 1934 season, E.J. Shefter bought the team from Turner. The team improved in 1935, finishing one game over .500, and then won the pennant in 1936, finishing 1\u00bd games over runner-up [[Oakland Oaks (PCL)|Oakland]], then winning the postseason series to capture the crown. In 1937, the Beavers finished in fourth place, but made it to the playoffs defeating San Francisco in the first round before losing to the San Diego team featuring a young [[Ted Williams]]. The team finished sixth in 1938 before finishing in last place in 1939\u20131942. The 1940 team was so bad, finishing 56\u2013122, that they were still 25 games behind the seventh-place team (the league had eight teams at that time).\n\nIn 1943, William Klepper, with partner George Norgan buying a minority share, purchased the Beavers. The team came back that season with their first winning record since 1937. The management of the team began referring to the team as the \"Lucky Beavers\" and Vaughn Street Park was known as \"Lucky Beaver Stadium.\"  With the United States firmly involved in World War II, local radio station [[KXL (AM)|KXL]] sold over $300,000 in war bonds in 1943 to fund the building of a bomber for the war that would be dubbed \"The Lucky Beaver.\" Due to U.S. involvement in the war, the available pool of baseball players in the nation was ravaged. Somehow, the Beavers still moved up in the league, finishing second in 1944. In 1945 the Beavers brought another pennant to Portland being skippered by player-manager [[Marv Owen]]. Despite winning the pennant, the team lost to San Francisco in the first round of the playoffs. To commemorate Portland's 1945 pennant win, Portland held a banquet at the Multnomah Hotel (now the downtown Portland Embassy Suites). [[Oregon Governor]] [[Earl Snell]] presented a commemorative watch and gold and diamond [[Championship ring|ring]] to each player at the banquet. The watches were given to the players due to [[L. H. Gregory]] of ''The Oregonian'' requesting fans to donate money to a fund for the purpose. Gregory did this because he felt it was not right that no memento was given to the players from the 1936 championship team. Following the 1945 season, Norgan purchased Klepper's share of the team becoming the team's new owner.\n\nIn 1946, the Beavers fell to the bottom half of the league, finishing in seventh place, 41 games out of first. In 1947 [[Eddie Basinski]] joined the Beavers, and they finished third, losing to the [[Los Angeles Angels (PCL)|Los Angeles Angels]] in the first round of the playoffs. The team drew, up to then, a team record of 421,000 fans that season. This record would stand for the Beavers until the 2001 season when Triple-A Baseball returned to Portland.\n\nIn 1948, the team finish fifth, followed by a sixth-place finish in 1949. The 1949 season began the [[Baseball color line|integration]] of the Pacific Coast League as [[Frankie Austin]] and Luis Marquez became Beavers. Beginning with the 1950 season, the Beavers finished fourth for four straight years. [[Clay Hopper]], who had been [[Jackie Robinson]]'s manager when he played for the [[Montreal Royals]] in 1946, was named the team's manager in 1952. This year also marked the first year the Pacific Coast League was classified by the NAPBL as an \"open league.\" The open league was a step above Triple-A, and was an attempt by the Pacific Coast League to be considered the third [[Major League Baseball|major league]].\n\nPlans for a new ballpark were announced by the team in 1953. Originally the team planned to build a new stadium at 82nd and Holgate in Southeast Portland. Due to the [[Korean War]], among other issues, the stadium never came to fruition. In 1954 the team dropped again to the bottom of the league. After the 1954 season the team went up for sale to the community via [[Stock|public stock]], which resulted in 2,400 new owners for the 1955 season. With the change the Beavers rose to fifth place, only nine games back of first.\n\nIn 1956, the Beavers left the now-demolished Vaughn Street Park to move into 25,000-seat [[Multnomah Stadium]], today's Providence Park. Throughout most of the 1960s, the Beavers were the Triple-A affiliate of the [[American League]] Cleveland Indians, nurturing such future stars as [[Sam McDowell|\"Sudden\" Sam McDowell]], [[Lou Piniella|Lou \"Mad Dog\" Piniella]], and [[Luis Tiant|Luis \"El Gigante\" Tiant]]. Later major league affiliations included the [[Minnesota Twins]] and [[Philadelphia Phillies]].\n\nIn 1961, the Beavers signed the 56-year-old [[Satchel Paige]]. He pitched 25 innings for the Beavers, striking out 19 and giving up 18 earned runs without recording a decision.\n\nFollowing the 1972 season, principal owner Bill Cutler moved the team northeast to [[Spokane Indians|Spokane]], who had lost their PCL team to [[Albuquerque Dukes|Albuquerque]] after the 1971 season. For the next five seasons, Portland was in the [[Short season|short-season]] [[Minor League Baseball#Class A-Short Season|Class A]] [[Northwest League]] (NWL) with the independent and non-conforming [[Portland Mavericks]], owned by actor [[Bing Russell]].\n\n===Triple-A returns to Portland: 1978\u20131993===\nThe PCL expanded in 1978 and added a new team in Portland, calling themselves the Beavers, displacing the single-A Mavericks. The new Beavers played in [[Civic Stadium (Portland, Oregon)|Civic Stadium]] for sixteen seasons through 1993. In 1983, the Beavers won the PCL pennant, the first for Portland in 47 years. Though tied for third overall during the regular season,<ref name=br83pclss>{{cite news |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/league.cgi?id=e57bc74c |publisher=Baseball Reference |title=1983 PCL season |accessdate=November 7, 2015}}</ref> the Beavers won the second half division title by four games,<ref name=pclfssp2>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Rm8RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PeIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4532%2C502464 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |title=Pacific Coast League: final standings |date=September 2, 1983 |page=6D }}</ref> defeated first-half winner [[Edmonton Trappers]] in four games (3\u20131) to take the Northern Division title,<ref name=mlplyff>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=S28RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PeIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2348%2C1614293 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |title=Baseball: Minor League playoffs |date=September 7, 1983 |page=4B }}</ref> then swept the three-time defending champion [[Albuquerque Dukes]] in three games in the finals to capture the league championship.<ref name=bvcpttl>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=o_lVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PeIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6550%2C2734607|newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |title=Beavers capture title with 8-7 triumph |agency=Associated Press |date=September 11, 1983 |page=12B }}</ref><ref name=pclfnl83>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=o_lVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PeIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6333%2C2726225|newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |title=Baseball: Minor League playoffs |date=September 11, 1983 |page=10B }}</ref> As PCL champs in 1983, the Beavers participated in the first [[Triple-A World Series]], a three-team round-robin competition in [[Cardinal Stadium|Louisville]] with the champions of the [[International League]] and  the [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]].<ref name=tpawsontp>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SPAaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PUcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5269%2C2399185 |newspaper=Daily News |location=Bowling Green, Kentucky |agency=Associated Press |title=Triple-A World Series on tap |date=September 15, 1983 |page=3B }}</ref> Each team played the others twice and it was won by the [[Norfolk Tides|Tidewater Tides]] of the IL with three wins. Portland was second, splitting with both teams, and the [[Denver Bears]] were 1\u20133.<ref name=twwtaws>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3NghAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7Z0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=6403%2C4477209 |newspaper=Times Daily |location=Florence, Alabama |title=Tidewater wins Triple-A Series |date=September 20, 1983 |page=2C }}</ref>\n\n[[File:PGEPark.jpg|thumb|Vince Sinisi on deck in 2008.]]\nA decade later, Beavers owner [[Joe Buzas]] moved the team after the 1993 season east to [[Salt Lake City]],<ref name=ntbfslbv>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xoVTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gYYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3901%2C2151925 |newspaper=The Bulletin |location=Bend, Oregon |last=Baum |first=Bob |title=No turning back for Portland's Salt Lake-bound Beavers |date=September 3, 1993 |page=D2 }}</ref> where they became the [[Salt Lake Buzz]] in 1994 in a [[Smith's Ballpark|brand new ballpark]]. The team was renamed the Stingers in 2001, and have been the [[Salt Lake Bees|Bees]] since the 2006 season. For the first time since 1894, Portland was without professional baseball.\n\nAfter being without a team in 1994, the Class A [[Bend Rockies|Rockies]] of the Northwest League relocated from [[Bend, Oregon|Bend]] for the 1995 season.<ref name=brmotpd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=K8IjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BtEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2913%2C1417835 |newspaper=Moscow-Pullman Daily News |location=Idaho-Washington |title=Bend Rockies baseball moves over to Portland |agency=Associated Press |date=September 14, 1994 |page=3B }}</ref> The [[Portland Rockies]] played in the Rose City for the next six seasons and served an important role for the city, whose demand for a major league team was growing. They were league champions in 1997. Portland's support for the Rockies paved the way for the return of the Triple-A PCL in 2001.<ref name=fflock>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_UZWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=C-sDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6586%2C5993015 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |last=Fears |first=Shannon |title=Fans flock to Rockies games |date=July 23, 1995 |page=3E }}</ref>\n\n===The Beavers return: 2001\u20132010===\nFollowing the 2000 season, the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] and [[San Diego Padres]] swapped Triple-A affiliates. The [[Albuquerque Dukes]] (a charter franchise of the PCL in 1903 as the [[Los Angeles Angels (PCL)|Los Angeles Angels]] from 1903 to 1958, and later the [[Spokane Indians]] from 1958 to 1971) moved to Portland and became the Beavers, as the Padres' top affiliate. As part of the relocation agreement, Civic Stadium was renovated in 2000 and renamed [[PGE Park]]. The Las Vegas Stars (the 1919\u201372 Beavers) became the Dodgers' top affiliate; they were renamed the [[Las Vegas 51s|51s]] for 2001. The single-A Portland Rockies moved up the [[Columbia River]] to [[Pasco, Washington|Pasco]] and became the [[Tri-City Dust Devils]] in 2001.\n\nIn 2007, owner [[Merritt Paulson]] announced that he was considering changing the name of the team to prevent confusion with the [[Oregon State Beavers|Oregon State University]] teams from [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]].<ref>[http://www.oregonlive.com/sports/oregonian/index.ssf?/base/sports/1184901921229010.xml&coll=7 \"Merritt Paulson, new owner of the Beavers and Timbers, stages a 'Grand Reopening' tonight at PGE Park.\"] ''The Oregonian''. Retrieved July 20, 2007.</ref> Possible new names and logos were unveiled, and a vote was staged on the team website. \"Portland Beavers\" won the contest,<ref>[http://www.portlandbeavers.com/news/press/index.html?article_id=1011 \"Beavers to keep historic nickname.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505232445/http://www.portlandbeavers.com/news/press/index.html?article_id=1011 |date=May 5, 2009 }} Portland Beavers. 2008. Retrieved February 22, 2008.</ref> and the team unveiled new logos and colors on January 29, 2008.<ref>[http://www.portlandbeavers.com/news/press/index.html?article_id=1040 \"Beavers unveil new logo, uniforms.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080418064642/http://www.portlandbeavers.com/news/press/index.html?article_id=1040 |date=April 18, 2008 }} Portland Beavers. 2008. Retrieved January 30, 2008.</ref> The Beavers emphasized their connection to the three prior franchises with the notation \"Est. 1903\" on their primary logo. The team also brought back the name \"Lucky Beavers\" as part of a sleeve patch on their alternate jersey.\n\n====Hunt for new stadium and team sale: 2009\u20132010====\nIn 2009, the city of Portland was awarded a [[Major League Soccer|Major League Soccer (MLS)]] expansion franchise for 2011, to be named the [[Portland Timbers (MLS)|Portland Timbers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_news.jsp?ymd=20090320&content_id=228140&vkey=pr_mls&fext=.jsp |publisher=mlsnet.com |title=MLS awards 18th franchise to Portland |date=March 20, 2009 |accessdate=March 20, 2009 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100319020353/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_news.jsp?ymd=20090320&content_id=228140&vkey=pr_mls&fext=.jsp |archivedate=March 19, 2010 }}</ref> The Portland City Council approved a $31 million agreement to renovate PGE Park to a soccer- and football-only stadium, with the condition that [[New Portland ballpark|a new ballpark be built in Portland]] for the Beavers by 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2010/02/portland_city_council_approves_1.html |title=Portland City Council approves soccer deal for PGE Park |author=James Mayer |date=February 3, 2010 |work=The Oregonian |publisher=oregonlive.com |accessdate=February 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Veterans Memorial Coliseum in 2013 - Portland, Oregon.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Memorial Coliseum (Portland)|Memorial Coliseum]] in the [[Rose Quarter]] was an original site for the proposed ballpark; however, it met public opposition.]]\nInitial plans called for the new ballpark to be built at the site currently occupied by the [[Memorial Coliseum (Portland)|Memorial Coliseum]], which would have been torn down,<ref name=mlb>{{cite web|url=http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090311&content_id=523032&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp|date=March 11, 2009|title=Beavers' new stadium a step closer|accessdate=April 24, 2009|publisher=minorleaguebaseball.com| last=Jackson|first=Josh}}</ref> but public outcry about demolishing a Portland landmark led Portland mayor [[Sam Adams (Oregon politician)|Sam Adams]] to propose a second site in the [[Rose Quarter]] area north of Memorial Coliseum. The site, however, proved to be too small.<ref name=frank>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2009/04/saving_portlands_memorial_coli.html|title=Saving Portland's Memorial Coliseum may cost taxpayers|date=April 22, 2009|accessdate=April 24, 2009|last=Frank|first=Ryan|author2=Mark Larabee|work=[[The Oregonian]]}}</ref> Another location on the site of [[Walker Stadium (baseball)|Charles D. Walker Stadium]] in the [[Lents, Portland, Oregon|Lents]] neighborhood in southeast Portland was also rejected due to objections from neighbors.<ref name=larabee062209>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/oregonian/index.ssf?/base/news/124572753115390.xml&coll=7|title=Lents Park out as Beavers' home|last=Larrabee|first=Mark|date=June 22, 2009|accessdate=June 25, 2009|work=[[The Oregonian]]}}</ref>  That was until the [[Portland Pickles]] collegiate wood bat team began play in 2016 at Walker Stadium.\n\nIn June 2009, the Portland City Council voted to separate the soccer and baseball projects, allowing renovation of PGE Park to proceed without completed plans for a baseball stadium in place.<ref name=larabee062409>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2009/06/major_league_soccer_plan_still.html|title=Major League Soccer plan still alive as Portland council endorses latest plan|date=June 24, 2009|accessdate=June 25, 2009|last=Larabee|first=Mark|work=[[The Oregonian]]}}</ref> Other locations in the Portland area were considered for the ballpark, including a vacant terminal at the [[Port of Portland (Oregon)|Port of Portland]], [[Delta Park]], the [[Portland Metropolitan Exposition Center|Portland Expo Center]], [[Portland Meadows]], the [[Westwood Corporation Heliport]] site, a building owned by [[Portland Public Schools (Oregon)|Portland Public Schools]] near the Rose Quarter, and suburban locations in [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]], [[Clackamas, Oregon|Clackamas]], and [[Vancouver, Washington]].<ref name=larabee062209/><ref name=beaverton>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2009/07/beaverton_in_running_for_new_b.html|title=Beaverton in running for new Beavers baseball stadium|date=July 21, 2009|accessdate=July 23, 2009|last=Larabee|first=Mark|work=[[The Oregonian]]}}</ref><ref name=schmidt>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.oregonlive.com/washingtoncounty/index.ssf/2009/09/theres_no_crying_over_baseball.html\n| title      = Clackamas County added to list of possible future sites for Portland Beavers.\n| last       = Schmidt\n| first      = Brad\n| date       = September 3, 2009\n| work       = [[The Oregonian]]\n| accessdate = September 13, 2009\n}}</ref><ref name=brettman>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.oregonlive.com/clark-county/index.ssf/2009/11/vancouver_now_interested_in_wooing_portland_beavers.html\n| title      = Vancouver now interested in wooing Portland Beavers\n| last       = Brettman\n| first      = Allan\n| date       = November 10, 2009\n| work       = [[The Oregonian]]\n| accessdate = April 6, 2010\n}}</ref> None of these sites progressed past initial discussions.\n\nWith no suitable Portland location available, in July 2010, Paulson announced that he was putting the team up for sale and relocation.<ref name=fentress>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.oregonlive.com/pbeavers/index.ssf/2010/07/post_3.html\n| title      = Portland Beavers owner Merritt Paulson prepared to sell team; several cities interested\n| last       = Fentress\n| first      = Aaron\n| date       = July 28, 2010\n| accessdate = July 28, 2010\n| work       = [[The Oregonian]]\n}}</ref> Padres owner [[Jeff Moorad]] formed a group to buy the team and talked of moving its home games to the [[Lake Elsinore Diamond]] in [[Lake Elsinore, California]] until a new stadium in Escondido could be built.<ref name=maffei>{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/minors/business-beat/2010/2610406.html\n| publisher  = Baseball America\n| title      = Displaced Triple-A club likely to share Lake Elsinore ballpark in 2011\n| first1     = John\n| last1      = Maffei\n| first2     = Josh\n| last2      = Leventhal\n| date       = July 26, 2010\n| accessdate = July 28, 2010\n}}</ref> Eventually, the group decided to move the team temporarily to Tucson in 2011, rename them the [[Tucson Padres]], with plans to move again to Escondido when a new ballpark was built.<ref name=escondido>{{cite web|title=Council votes to bring baseball to Escondido|last=Breier|first=Michelle|author2=J. Harry Jones|date=December 15, 2010|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2010/dec/15/escondido-council-approves-moving-ahead-ballpark|accessdate= December 20, 2010}}</ref> The plans in Escondido failed, and the team was sold again; they moved to west Texas prior to the 2014 season and became the [[El Paso Chihuahuas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140502&content_id=74058844&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_farmalmc&sid=milb|title=Greetings from Southwest University Park, home of the El Paso Chihuahuas - MiLB.com News - The Official Site of Minor League Baseball|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe Portland area was without minor league baseball in 2011 and 2012. After the 2012 season, the NWL [[Yakima Bears]] relocated to a [[Ron Tonkin Field|new 4,500-seat stadium]] in the northwest suburb of [[Hillsboro, Oregon|Hillsboro]] and became the [[Hillsboro Hops]]. The Hops won the NWL title in 2014 and again in 2015, averaging more than 3,700 in attendance for 38 regular season home games.<ref name=nwlatt15>{{cite web |url=http://www.milb.com/milb/stats/stats.jsp?y=2015&t=l_att&lid=126&sid=l126 |publisher=Northwest League |title=attendance |accessdate=November 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n[[File:091306 106 Craig Breslow.jpg|thumb|[[Craig Breslow]]]]\n<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n*[[Eddie Basinski]], infielder, inductee in [[Pacific Coast League Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Kyle Blanks]], outfielder\n*[[Craig Breslow]], pitcher\n*[[Mickey Cochrane]], Hall of Fame catcher\n*[[Shawn Estes]], pitcher, pitched in 12 games of rehab between 2006\u20132008\n*[[Ray Fosse]], catcher, 1967\u20131968\n*[[George Freese]], infielder\n*[[Josh Geer]], pitcher\n*[[Ram\u00f3n Hern\u00e1ndez]], catcher, played 7 games of rehab\n*[[Sam McDowell]], pitcher, 8-0 1964\n*[[Satchel Paige]], pitcher, 5 starts, 2.88 ERA\n*[[Lou Piniella]], outfielder, 1964\n*[[Aaron Poreda]], pitcher\n*[[Jeff Richards (baseball player/actor)|Jeff Richards]], a.k.a. Dick Taylor, shortstop; then became an actor \n*[[Richie Scheinblum]], All Star outfielder\n*[[George Stone (outfielder)|George Stone]], AL batting title champion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=stone-003geo |title=George Stone Minor Leagues Statistics & History |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n*[[Luis Tiant]], pitcher, 15-1 1964\n*[[Jim Thorpe]], outfielder and first baseman, 1922\n*[[Ryan Webb]], pitcher\n\n==See also==\n*[[:Category:Portland Beavers players|Portland Beavers players]] \n*[[History of baseball in Portland, Oregon]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* Carlson, Kip & Andersen, Paul. ''The Portland Beavers.'' Arcadia Publishing, Charleston, South Carolina, 2004. {{ISBN|0-7385-3266-5}}\n* O'Neal, Bill. ''The Pacific Coast League 1903\u20131988.'' Eakin Press, Austin TX, 1990. {{ISBN|0-89015-776-6}}.\n* Snelling, Dennis. ''The Pacific Coast League: A Statistical History, 1903\u20131957''. McFarland & Company, Inc., Jefferson, North Carolina, 1995. {{ISBN|0-7864-0045-5}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?city=Portland&state=OR&country=US&empty=0 Baseball Reference] \u2013 Portland teams\n\n{{Baseball teams based in Portland, Oregon}}\n\n[[Category:Portland Beavers| ]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Dodgers minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Detroit Tigers minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Athletics minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Milwaukee Brewers minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Twins minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Athletics minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:San Diego Padres minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Cardinals minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:1903 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Sports teams in Portland, Oregon|Beavers]]\n[[Category:2010 disestablishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Baseball teams established in 1903]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs disestablished in 2010]]\n\n[[fr:Portland Beavers]]\n[[ja:\u30dd\u30fc\u30c8\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9\u30fb\u30d3\u30fc\u30d0\u30fc\u30ba]]\n", "name_user": "Davemck", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv duplicate parms", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portland_Beavers"}
{"title_page": "Neena Schwartz", "text_new": "{{short description|American biology researcher (1926\u20132018)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = Neena Schwartz\n| birth_date  ={{nowrap| {{birth date|1926|12|10}} }}\n| birth_place=[[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2018|4|15|1926|12|10}}\n| nationality = American\n| fields      = [[Physiology]], [[Endocrinology]],[[Reproductive Health]],[[Activism]]\n| workplaces  = [[Northwestern University]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Goucher College]]<br>[[Northwestern University]]\n| academic_advisors = [[Allen Lein]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = Discovery of [[inhibin]]<br>Feminism in science<br>[[LGBT]] advocacy\n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| awards      = \n}}\n\n'''Neena Betty Schwartz''' (December 10, 1926 \u2013 April 15, 2018) was an American [[endocrinologist]] and William Deering Professor of Endocrinology [[emeritus|Emerita]] in the Department of Neurobiology at [[Northwestern University]]. She was best known for her work on female [[reproductive biology]] and the regulation of [[hormone|hormonal]] [[signaling pathway]]s, particularly for the discovery of the signaling hormone [[inhibin]]. Schwartz was an active [[feminist]] advocate for women in science throughout her career; she was a founding member of the [[Association for Women in Science]] organization in 1971 and shared the founding presidency with [[Judith Pool]]. She also co-founded the Women in Endocrinology group under the auspices of the [[Endocrine Society]], served terms as the president of the Endocrine Society and the [[Society for the Study of Reproduction]], and was recognized for her exceptional mentorship of women scientists. In 2010, she wrote a memoir of her life in science, ''A Lab of My Own'', in which she [[came out]] as [[lesbian]].<ref name=lab>{{cite book|last1=Schwartz|first1=Neena B.|title=A lab of my own|date=2009|publisher=Rodopi|location=Amsterdam|isbn=9789042027374}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nSchwartz was born in [[Baltimore, Maryland]] in 1926.<ref>{{cite book |title=American Men & Women of Science Volume 6 (Q\u2013S)|year=2005| publisher=Thomson Gale |isbn=9780787673987 |page=633 |edition=22nd}}</ref> to a family of Russian descent<ref name=interview /> who she has described as politically active.<ref name=bb /> She received her bachelor's degree from [[Goucher College]] (a women's college at the time) in 1948.<ref name=interview>{{cite interview |last=Schwartz |first=Neena |interviewer=Michael Chappelle |title=An oral history conducted in 2008 |date=2008 |location=Chevy Chase, Maryland |work=The Endocrine Society, The Clark Sawin Library}}</ref><ref name=cv>{{cite web|title=Neena B. Schwartz CV|url=https://www.endocrine.org/~/media/endosociety/Files/About%20Us/Sawin/cv-neena-b-schwartz.pdf|website=Endocrine Society|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> Despite originally being interested in English and journalism, she became interested in physiology during her undergraduate studies and spent summers conducting [[undergraduate research]] with [[Curt Richter]] at [[Johns Hopkins University]], and separately at the [[Jackson Laboratory]] in [[Bar Harbor, Maine]].<ref name=interview />\n\nAfter graduation, Schwartz began her graduate studies at [[Northwestern University]], where she received her Ph.D. in physiology in 1953 under the supervision of [[Allen Lein]].<ref name=interview /><ref name=cv /> She was the only female Ph.D. student in the department at the time.<ref name=bb>{{cite web|last1=Silberman|first1=Steve|last2=Koerth-Baker|first2=Maggie|title=Coming Out in the Sciences: Part I\u2014After 50 Years in the Lab, a Reproduction Expert Leaves the Closet|url=http://boingboing.net/2010/10/11/coming-out-in-the-sc.html|website=BoingBoing|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nIn 1954 Schwartz was hired as a physiology instructor at the [[University of Illinois College of Medicine]], which she left a year later to take a position at [[Michael Reese Hospital]]. In 1961 she returned to the University of Illinois with [[tenure]], as the only woman in her department. She moved to her alma mater [[Northwestern University]] in 1973, becoming the chair of the biology department of the medical school a year later and serving for four years.<ref name=interview /><ref name=wie>{{cite web|title=Women in Endocrinology|url=https://www.women-in-endo.org/documents/schwartz%20brochure%201st%20draft_quarter.pdf|accessdate=5 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328125122/https://www.women-in-endo.org/documents/schwartz%20brochure%201st%20draft_quarter.pdf|archive-date=28 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1974, Schwartz organized the founding of the Program for Reproductive Research at Northwestern, which would evolve into the Center for Reproductive Science in 1987 with Schwartz as its director.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://crs.mccormick.northwestern.edu/about_crs/history.html|website=Center for Reproductive Science|publisher=Northwestern University|accessdate=5 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421072818/http://crs.mccormick.northwestern.edu/about_crs/history.html|archive-date=21 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSchwartz was among the very few women who served in the 1960s on [[American Physiological Society]] program committees,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Appel|first1=edited by John R. Brobeck, Orr E. Reynolds, Toby A.|title=History of the American Physiological Society the First Century, 1887\u20131987|date=1987|publisher=Springer New York|location=New York, NY|isbn=9781461475767}}</ref> was the first woman president of the [[Society for the Study of Reproduction]] from 1977\u20131978, and was the second woman president of the [[Endocrine Society]] from 1982\u20131983.<ref name=lab /> Schwartz retired from her academic positions in 1999.<ref name=lab />{{rp|xv}}\n\n==Research==\nSchwartz's research group studied the [[feedback mechanism]]s that govern [[hormone|hormonal]] [[signaling pathway]]s in the female [[reproductive cycle]], using rats as an [[animal model]]. Her work played a major role in the developing the modern understanding of the [[hypothalamic\u2013pituitary\u2013adrenal axis]] in endocrinology and was particularly significant in discovering the hormone [[inhibin]].<ref name=interview /><ref name=nw>{{cite web|title=Neena Schwartz|url=http://www.neurobiology.northwestern.edu/people/emeritus-faculty/neena-schwartz.html|website=Department of Neurobiology|publisher=Northwestern University|accessdate=5 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106143543/http://www.neurobiology.northwestern.edu/people/emeritus-faculty/neena-schwartz.html|archive-date=6 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWhile investigating the secretion of [[gonadotropin]]s by the [[pituitary]], Schwartz and her research group observed that then-dominant models of the reproductive cycle did not explain the observed changes in levels of [[luteinizing hormone]] and [[follicle-stimulating hormone]] in response to [[gonadotropin-releasing hormone]]. A hypothetical additional hormone given the name [[inhibin]] had been suggested years prior based on work with male animals, potentially being secreted from the [[testes]]. Schwartz's key insight was to instead investigate secretion from the [[ovaries]] in female subjects. The existence of inhibin in ovarian [[follicular fluid]] was confirmed by the Schwartz group in collaboration with [[Cornelia Channing]] in the mid 1970s.<ref name=interview /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Schwartz|first1=NB|title=Why I was told not to study inhibin and what I did about it.|journal=Endocrinology|date=October 1991|volume=129|issue=4|pages=1690\u20131|pmid=1915056|doi=10.1210/endo-129-4-1690}}</ref> Inhibin \u2013 which plays a role in both male and female hormonal signaling \u2013 was molecularly characterized in the mid 1980s as a [[protein dimer]]. Inhibin levels have since been identified as one of several [[biomarker]]s that can be used to screen for [[Down syndrome]] in the fetus by testing a woman's blood.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Makanji|first1=Y|last2=Zhu|first2=J|last3=Mishra|first3=R|last4=Holmquist|first4=C|last5=Wong|first5=WP|last6=Schwartz|first6=NB|last7=Mayo|first7=KE|last8=Woodruff|first8=TK|title=Inhibin at 90: from discovery to clinical application, a historical review.|journal=Endocrine Reviews|date=October 2014|volume=35|issue=5|pages=747\u201394|pmid=25051334|doi=10.1210/er.2014-1003|pmc=4167436}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nSchwartz received the Williams Distinguished Service Award from the [[Endocrine Society]] in 1985<ref name=cv /> and the Carl Hartman Research Award from the [[Society for the Study of Reproduction]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Carl G. Hartman Award: Neena B. Schwartz|date=1 January 1993|volume=48|issue=1|page=24|journal=Biology of Reproduction|pmid=    8418910|doi=10.1095/biolreprod48.1.24|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nSchwartz was elected a fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] in 1986 and of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1992. She served on the board of the American Association for the Advancement of Science from 2000\u20132002 and received their Mentor Award for Lifetime Achievement in 2002.<ref name=aaas>{{cite web|title=2002 Mentor Award for Lifetime Achievement|url=http://www.aaas.org/page/2002-mentor-award-lifetime-achievement|website=American Association for the Advancement of Science|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nNeena has also received the following honors:  Northwestern Alumni Excellence in Teaching Award, Women in Endocrinology Mentor of the Year Award, Distinguished Educator Award from the endocrine Society, Northwestern School of Medicine alumni Merit Award, and Pioneer in Reproductive Research Award.\tPage text.<ref>[https://www.nualumnae.org/award-recipient/neena-schwartz Link text], additional text.</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nIn the 1970s Schwartz became involved in the [[feminist movement]].<ref name=bb /> She was a founding member of the [[Association for Women in Science]] (AWIS) \u2013 which she recalled originating after drinks at a [[Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology]] meeting with other women scientists frustrated with their situation.<ref name=interview /> She served as founding co-president of AWIS along with [[Judith Pool]],<ref name=aan>{{cite news|last1=Hampton|first1=Kathleen|title=Women Scientists Probing Discrimination in Their Field|accessdate=5 June 2015|work=Ann Arbor News|date=10 August 1971|url=http://oldnews.aadl.org/node/89833}}</ref> taking a primarily executive role while Pool worked in fundraising.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rossiter|first1=Margaret|title=Women Scientists in America. ; Forging a New World since 1972.|date=2012|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=9781421403632}}</ref> Notable early achievements of AWIS, along with other women in science organizations, include initiating a [[class action lawsuit]] against the [[National Institutes of Health]] for poor representation of women on NIH grant review committees.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bias Charge is Leveled in Lawsuit|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=E9ovAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LO0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5398,5620578&hl=en|accessdate=16 June 2015|work=The Spokesman-Review|issue=321|date=30 March 1972}}</ref> The lawsuit was dropped after [[Robert Marston]], then head of the NIH, met with representatives of the groups, including Schwartz, and committed to appointing more women.<ref name=interview />\n\nIn the 1970s Schwartz co-founded the Women in Endocrinology society within the [[Endocrine Society]] after discovering a lack of women's representation on the society's key organizing committees.<ref name=interview /> She later served as the group's president from 1990\u20131992.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women in Endocrinology Past Presidents|url=https://www.women-in-endo.org/about/#pres|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nSchwartz was one of forty women in non-traditional professions interviewed by filmmaker and artist [[Michelle Citron]] for her 1983 film ''What You Take for Granted''.<ref>{{cite web|title=What You Take for Granted (1983)|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b6e610982|website=BFI Film Forever|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a 20th century female scientist, Schwartz faced micro aggressions and macro aggressions. She wrote her 2010 memoir, ''A Lab of My Own''.<ref name=lab /> to detail her experience as a female scientist to lend visibility to her experiences.  At her first job at the University of Illinois, the chairman of the department asked her to pour the tea.Page text.<ref>[https://boingboing.net/2010/10/11/coming-out-in-the-sc.html Link text], additional text.</ref> She details her experiences like this, her successes and struggles all in the hopes of providing lessons and possibilities for a new generation of scientists and world citizens.\n\n==Personal Life and LGBTQ+ Experience==\nSchwartz identified as [[lesbian]]. She discovered her sexuality as a teenager in the 1940s, but [[closeted|kept her sexuality private]] during her scientific career and publicly [[came out]] in her 2010 memoir, ''A Lab of My Own''.<ref name=lab /> She began writing the book \"because no one had documented the feminist movement in science\" and concluded as she wrote that revealing her sexuality was necessary to telling the story.<ref name=bb /> She hopes that the book will \"provide young gay scientists or other professionals with a lesson of possibilities for success and happiness without such splits in their lives.\".<ref name=bb /> She lived in Evanston Illinois with her life partner of over 20 years [[Harriet Wadeson]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schwartz, Neena}}\n[[Category:American endocrinologists]]\n[[Category:LGBT scientists from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Maryland]]\n[[Category:American women biologists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n[[Category:Goucher College alumni]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University faculty]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois faculty]]\n[[Category:Lesbian academics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American biology researcher (1926\u20132018)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = Neena Schwartz\n| birth_date  ={{nowrap| {{birth date|1926|12|10}} }}\n| birth_place=[[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2018|4|15|1926|12|10}}\n| nationality = American\n| fields      = [[Physiology]], [[Endocrinology]],[[Reproductive Health]],[[Activism]]\n| workplaces  = [[Northwestern University]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Goucher College]]<br>[[Northwestern University]]\n| academic_advisors = [[Allen Lein]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = Discovery of [[inhibin]]<br>Feminism in science<br>[[LGBT]] advocacy\n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| awards      = \n}}\n\n'''Neena Betty Schwartz''' (December 10, 1926 \u2013 April 15, 2018) was an American [[endocrinologist]] and William Deering Professor of Endocrinology [[emeritus|Emerita]] in the Department of Neurobiology at [[Northwestern University]]. She was best known for her work on female [[reproductive biology]] and the regulation of [[hormone|hormonal]] [[signaling pathway]]s, particularly for the discovery of the signaling hormone [[inhibin]]. Schwartz was an active [[feminist]] advocate for women in science throughout her career; she was a founding member of the [[Association for Women in Science]] organization in 1971 and shared the founding presidency with [[Judith Pool]]. She also co-founded the Women in Endocrinology group under the auspices of the [[Endocrine Society]], served terms as the president of the Endocrine Society and the [[Society for the Study of Reproduction]], and was recognized for her exceptional mentorship of women scientists. In 2010, she wrote a memoir of her life in science, ''A Lab of My Own'', in which she [[came out]] as [[lesbian]].<ref name=lab>{{cite book|last1=Schwartz|first1=Neena B.|title=A lab of my own|date=2009|publisher=Rodopi|location=Amsterdam|isbn=9789042027374}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nSchwartz was born in [[Baltimore, Maryland]] in 1926.<ref>{{cite book |title=American Men & Women of Science Volume 6 (Q\u2013S)|year=2005| publisher=Thomson Gale |isbn=9780787673987 |page=633 |edition=22nd}}</ref> to a family of Russian descent<ref name=interview /> who she has described as politically active.<ref name=bb /> She received her bachelor's degree from [[Goucher College]] (a women's college at the time) in 1948.<ref name=interview>{{cite interview |last=Schwartz |first=Neena |interviewer=Michael Chappelle |title=An oral history conducted in 2008 |date=2008 |location=Chevy Chase, Maryland |work=The Endocrine Society, The Clark Sawin Library}}</ref><ref name=cv>{{cite web|title=Neena B. Schwartz CV|url=https://www.endocrine.org/~/media/endosociety/Files/About%20Us/Sawin/cv-neena-b-schwartz.pdf|website=Endocrine Society|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> Despite originally being interested in English and journalism, she became interested in physiology during her undergraduate studies and spent summers conducting [[undergraduate research]] with [[Curt Richter]] at [[Johns Hopkins University]], and separately at the [[Jackson Laboratory]] in [[Bar Harbor, Maine]].<ref name=interview />\n\nAfter graduation, Schwartz began her graduate studies at [[Northwestern University]], where she received her Ph.D. in physiology in 1953 under the supervision of [[Allen Lein]].<ref name=interview /><ref name=cv /> She was the only female Ph.D. student in the department at the time.<ref name=bb>{{cite web|last1=Silberman|first1=Steve|last2=Koerth-Baker|first2=Maggie|title=Coming Out in the Sciences: Part I\u2014After 50 Years in the Lab, a Reproduction Expert Leaves the Closet|url=http://boingboing.net/2010/10/11/coming-out-in-the-sc.html|website=BoingBoing|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nIn 1954 Schwartz was hired as a physiology instructor at the [[University of Illinois College of Medicine]], which she left a year later to take a position at [[Michael Reese Hospital]]. In 1961 she returned to the University of Illinois with [[tenure]], as the only woman in her department. She moved to her alma mater [[Northwestern University]] in 1973, becoming the chair of the biology department of the medical school a year later and serving for four years.<ref name=interview /><ref name=wie>{{cite web|title=Women in Endocrinology|url=https://www.women-in-endo.org/documents/schwartz%20brochure%201st%20draft_quarter.pdf|accessdate=5 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328125122/https://www.women-in-endo.org/documents/schwartz%20brochure%201st%20draft_quarter.pdf|archive-date=28 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1974, Schwartz organized the founding of the Program for Reproductive Research at Northwestern, which would evolve into the Center for Reproductive Science in 1987 with Schwartz as its director.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://crs.mccormick.northwestern.edu/about_crs/history.html|website=Center for Reproductive Science|publisher=Northwestern University|accessdate=5 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421072818/http://crs.mccormick.northwestern.edu/about_crs/history.html|archive-date=21 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSchwartz was among the very few women who served in the 1960s on [[American Physiological Society]] program committees,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Appel|first1=edited by John R. Brobeck, Orr E. Reynolds, Toby A.|title=History of the American Physiological Society the First Century, 1887\u20131987|date=1987|publisher=Springer New York|location=New York, NY|isbn=9781461475767}}</ref> was the first woman president of the [[Society for the Study of Reproduction]] from 1977\u20131978, and was the second woman president of the [[Endocrine Society]] from 1982\u20131983.<ref name=lab /> Schwartz retired from her academic positions in 1999.<ref name=lab />{{rp|xv}}\n\n==Research==\nSchwartz's research group studied the [[feedback mechanism]]s that govern [[hormone|hormonal]] [[signaling pathway]]s in the female [[reproductive cycle]], using rats as an [[animal model]]. Her work played a major role in the developing the modern understanding of the [[hypothalamic\u2013pituitary\u2013adrenal axis]] in endocrinology and was particularly significant in discovering the hormone [[inhibin]].<ref name=interview /><ref name=nw>{{cite web|title=Neena Schwartz|url=http://www.neurobiology.northwestern.edu/people/emeritus-faculty/neena-schwartz.html|website=Department of Neurobiology|publisher=Northwestern University|accessdate=5 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106143543/http://www.neurobiology.northwestern.edu/people/emeritus-faculty/neena-schwartz.html|archive-date=6 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWhile investigating the secretion of [[gonadotropin]]s by the [[pituitary]], Schwartz and her research group observed that then-dominant models of the reproductive cycle did not explain the observed changes in levels of [[luteinizing hormone]] and [[follicle-stimulating hormone]] in response to [[gonadotropin-releasing hormone]]. A hypothetical additional hormone given the name [[inhibin]] had been suggested years prior based on work with male animals, potentially being secreted from the [[testes]]. Schwartz's key insight was to instead investigate secretion from the [[ovaries]] in female subjects. The existence of inhibin in ovarian [[follicular fluid]] was confirmed by the Schwartz group in collaboration with [[Cornelia Channing]] in the mid 1970s.<ref name=interview /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Schwartz|first1=NB|title=Why I was told not to study inhibin and what I did about it.|journal=Endocrinology|date=October 1991|volume=129|issue=4|pages=1690\u20131|pmid=1915056|doi=10.1210/endo-129-4-1690}}</ref> Inhibin \u2013 which plays a role in both male and female hormonal signaling \u2013 was molecularly characterized in the mid 1980s as a [[protein dimer]]. Inhibin levels have since been identified as one of several [[biomarker]]s that can be used to screen for [[Down syndrome]] in the fetus by testing a woman's blood.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Makanji|first1=Y|last2=Zhu|first2=J|last3=Mishra|first3=R|last4=Holmquist|first4=C|last5=Wong|first5=WP|last6=Schwartz|first6=NB|last7=Mayo|first7=KE|last8=Woodruff|first8=TK|title=Inhibin at 90: from discovery to clinical application, a historical review.|journal=Endocrine Reviews|date=October 2014|volume=35|issue=5|pages=747\u201394|pmid=25051334|doi=10.1210/er.2014-1003|pmc=4167436}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nSchwartz received the Williams Distinguished Service Award from the [[Endocrine Society]] in 1985<ref name=cv /> and the Carl Hartman Research Award from the [[Society for the Study of Reproduction]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Carl G. Hartman Award: Neena B. Schwartz|date=1 January 1993|volume=48|issue=1|page=24|journal=Biology of Reproduction|pmid=    8418910|doi=10.1095/biolreprod48.1.24|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nSchwartz was elected a fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] in 1986 and of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1992. She served on the board of the American Association for the Advancement of Science from 2000\u20132002 and received their Mentor Award for Lifetime Achievement in 2002.<ref name=aaas>{{cite web|title=2002 Mentor Award for Lifetime Achievement|url=http://www.aaas.org/page/2002-mentor-award-lifetime-achievement|website=American Association for the Advancement of Science|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nNeena has also received the following honors:  Northwestern Alumni Excellence in Teaching Award, Women in Endocrinology Mentor of the Year Award, Distinguished Educator Award from the endocrine Society, Northwestern School of Medicine alumni Merit Award, and Pioneer in Reproductive Research Award.\tPage text.<ref>[https://www.nualumnae.org/award-recipient/neena-schwartz Link text], additional text.</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nIn the 1970s Schwartz became involved in the [[feminist movement]].<ref name=bb /> She was a founding member of the [[Association for Women in Science]] (AWIS) \u2013 which she recalled originating after drinks at a [[Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology]] meeting with other women scientists frustrated with their situation.<ref name=interview /> She served as founding co-president of AWIS along with [[Judith Pool]],<ref name=aan>{{cite news|last1=Hampton|first1=Kathleen|title=Women Scientists Probing Discrimination in Their Field|accessdate=5 June 2015|work=Ann Arbor News|date=10 August 1971|url=http://oldnews.aadl.org/node/89833}}</ref> taking a primarily executive role while Pool worked in fundraising.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rossiter|first1=Margaret|title=Women Scientists in America. ; Forging a New World since 1972.|date=2012|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=9781421403632}}</ref> Notable early achievements of AWIS, along with other women in science organizations, include initiating a [[class action lawsuit]] against the [[National Institutes of Health]] for poor representation of women on NIH grant review committees.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bias Charge is Leveled in Lawsuit|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=E9ovAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LO0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5398,5620578&hl=en|accessdate=16 June 2015|work=The Spokesman-Review|issue=321|date=30 March 1972}}</ref> The lawsuit was dropped after [[Robert Marston]], then head of the NIH, met with representatives of the groups, including Schwartz, and committed to appointing more women.<ref name=interview />\n\nIn the 1970s Schwartz co-founded the Women in Endocrinology society within the [[Endocrine Society]] after discovering a lack of women's representation on the society's key organizing committees.<ref name=interview /> She later served as the group's president from 1990\u20131992.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women in Endocrinology Past Presidents|url=https://www.women-in-endo.org/about/#pres|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nSchwartz was one of forty women in non-traditional professions interviewed by filmmaker and artist [[Michelle Citron]] for her 1983 film ''What You Take for Granted''.<ref>{{cite web|title=What You Take for Granted (1983)|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b6e610982|website=BFI Film Forever|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a 20th century female scientist, Schwartz faced micro aggressions and macro aggressions. She wrote her 2010 memoir, ''A Lab of My Own''.<ref name=lab /> to detail her experience as a female scientist to lend visibility to her experiences.  At her first job at the University of Illinois, the chairman of the department asked her to pour the tea.Page text.<ref>[https://boingboing.net/2010/10/11/coming-out-in-the-sc.html Link text], additional text.</ref> She details her experiences like this, her successes and struggles all in the hopes of providing lessons and possibilities for a new generation of scientists and world citizens.\n\n==Personal Life and LGBTQ+ Experience==\nSchwartz identified as [[lesbian]]. She discovered her sexuality as a teenager in the 1940s, but [[closeted|kept her sexuality private]] during her scientific career and publicly [[came out]] in her 2010 memoir, ''A Lab of My Own''.<ref name=lab /> She began writing the book \"because no one had documented the feminist movement in science\" and concluded as she wrote that revealing her sexuality was necessary to telling the story.<ref name=bb /> She hopes that the book will \"provide young gay scientists or other professionals with a lesson of possibilities for success and happiness without such splits in their lives.\"<ref name=bb />. She lived in Evanston Illinois with her life partner of over 20 years [[Harriet Wadeson]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schwartz, Neena}}\n[[Category:American endocrinologists]]\n[[Category:LGBT scientists from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Women biologists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n[[Category:Goucher College alumni]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University faculty]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois faculty]]\n[[Category:Lesbian academics]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neena_Schwartz"}
{"title_page": "William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections", "text_new": "__NOTOC__\n{{Infobox library\n| name               = William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections\n| logo               = <!-- file name only (no Image: or File:) -->\n| logo_size          = \n| logo_alt           = \n| image              = File:Reading room in The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections in Mills Memorial Library at McMaster University.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| country            = Canada\n| type               = Academic\n| scope              = \n| established        = \n| ref_legal_mandate  = \n| location           = Mills Memorial Library, Hamilton, Ontario\n| coordinates        = \n| branch_of          = [[McMaster University Library]]\n| num_branches       = \n| items_collected    = \n| collection_size    = \n| criteria           = \n| legal_deposit      = \n| req_to_access      = \n| annual_circulation = \n| pop_served         = \n| members            = \n| budget             = \n| director           = \n| num_employees      = \n| website            = http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/\n| references         = \n| embed              = \n| module             = \n}}\nThe '''William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections''' is the principal repository for rare books, archives, maps and historical material at [[McMaster University]]. Developed to support teaching, research and scholarship, its holdings reflect [[fonds]] and collections pertaining to Canadian literature, politics, popular culture and business history, in addition to war and peace in the 20th century with an emphasis on the [[Holocaust]] and [[Resistance movement|Resistance]]. It also holds a collection of eighteenth century books and journals, and is home to the [[Bertrand Russell]] Archives. Part of the [[McMaster University Library]] system, the Division of Archives and Research Collections is located in Mills Memorial Library.<ref name=About>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/about|website=McMaster University Library|publisher=The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections|accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Division of Archives and Research Collections is named after William Ready who served as University Librarian from 1966 until his retirement in 1979.<ref name=About/> In 2002 the Archives was awarded the [[Archives Association of Ontario]]'s Institutional Award in recognition of its strong archival program and service to the community.<ref>{{cite news |title=Library\u2019s William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections Division Receives AAO Award |url=https://dailynews.mcmaster.ca/articles/librarys-william-ready-division-of-archives-and-research-collections-division-receives-aao-award/ |accessdate=31 December 2018 |work=Daily News |publisher=McMaster University |date=24 June 2002}}</ref>\n\n===William Ready===\nWilliam Bernard Ready (pronounced Reedy) was born on September 16, 1914 in [[Cardiff, Wales]] to James Ready and Nora Hart. He obtained a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from the [[University of Wales]] in 1937, a [[Master of Arts]] from the [[University of Manitoba]] in 1949 and a [[Master of Library and Information Science|Master of Library Science]] from the [[University of Western Ontario]] in 1970, in addition to several diplomas related to archives and library administration. Ready married Bessie Dyer (1917-2007) on April 25, 1945 and together they had six children.<ref name=Reginald>{{cite book|author1=R. Reginald|author2=Douglas Menville|author3=Mary A. Burgess|editor1-last=Menville|editor1-first=Douglas|editor2-last=Burgess|editor2-first=Mary A.|title=Science Fiction and Fantasy Literature, Volume 2|date=2010|publisher=Wildside Press LLC|pages=1043\u20131044|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nPYfqEbfrsC&source=gbs_navlinks_s|isbn=9780941028783|accessdate=6 January 2016|ref=Reginald}}</ref><ref name=BessieObit>{{cite web|title=Deaths & Funerals - Ready, Bessie|url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=3cbc97ae-1a69-47c5-aa19-0b566689f62f|website=Canada.com|publisher=Times Colonist (Victoria)|accessdate=20 January 2016|location=Victoria, British Columbia|date=October 3, 2007}}</ref>\n\nReady considered himself a \"working librarian\" and rejected the academic side of librarianship in favour of hands-on work and collection development <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Neill|first1=S. D.|title=Review of Files on Parade: A Memoir by William B. Ready|journal=[[The Journal of Library History]]|date=1983|volume= 18|issue= 4|pages=521\u2013523|jstor=25541478|publisher=University of Texas Press}}</ref> He was known for his enterprising<ref name=Humphreys/> and cunning<ref name=Grescoe>{{cite news|last1=Grescoe|first1=Paul|title=William Ready is Cunning, Devious, Relentless, Ruthless (and sneaky)|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19710424&id=C5gkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PqEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2566,5958655&hl=en|accessdate=6 January 2016|newspaper=[[The Montreal Gazette]]|date=April 24, 1971|pages=28\u201329}}</ref> approach to building and managing archives and research collections. Having read and enjoyed ''[[The Hobbit]]'', Ready asked a London-based book dealer to contact [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] about acquiring his works for Marquette University. Concerned about his retirement, Tolkien initially agreed to sell a selection of manuscripts. Further negotiation led to Marquette's acquisition of the manuscripts for ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'' and ''[[The Hobbit]]'', among others, amounting to more than 11,000 pages.<ref name=Antlfinger>{{cite news|last1=Antlfinger|first1=Carrie|title=Marquette University holds 'Lord of the Rings,' other Tolkien works|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dukfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=p9kEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1486%2C2154990|accessdate=21 January 2016|newspaper=[[Nevada Herald]]|date=February 3, 2002|page=8A}}</ref> During the same period Ready also secured the personal papers of social activist [[Dorothy Day]].<ref name=Heinen>{{cite journal|last1=Heinen|first1=Tom|title=Diaries reveal another Dorothy|journal=[[Journal Sentinel]]|date=May 7, 2008|url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/education/29522229.html|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=Wire>{{cite news|title=Dorothy Day \u2014 Catholic Worker Collection|url=http://marquettewire.org/2626374/tribune/tribune-news/sheen-mean-on-social-work/|accessdate=21 January 2016|newspaper=Marquette Wire|date=September 18, 2003}}</ref> As University Librarian at McMaster he played an instrumental role in securing numerous high-profile collections, most notably the archives of philosopher and political activist Bertrand Russell.<ref name=Grescoe/><ref name=Griffin/>\n\nReady died in [[Victoria, British Columbia]] on September 12, 1981, two years after retiring from McMaster. His autobiography, ''Files on Parade'', was published posthumously in 1982.<ref name=Antlfinger/><ref name=McFonds>{{cite web|title=William Ready fonds|url=http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/findaids/fonds/r/ready.htm|website=McMaster University Library|publisher=The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\n\nThe holdings of the Division of Archives and Research Collections reflect a broad spectrum of Canadian popular culture ranging from the records of  Canadian [[Publishing|publishers]]<ref name=\"HPCP\">{{cite web|title=About|url=http://hpcanpub.mcmaster.ca/|website=Historical Perspectives on Canadian Publishing|publisher=McMaster|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> and advertisers<ref>{{cite news|last1=Foda|first1=Farzeen|last2=Cumerlato|first2=Sam|title=Collection of popular media donated to Mac|url=http://www.thesil.ca/collection-of-popular-media-donated-to-mac|accessdate=5 February 2016|publisher=The Silhouette|date=February 16, 2012}}</ref> to the personal papers of internationally recognized authors and musicians. Included are writers [[Louise Bennett-Coverley]],<ref name=Wong>{{cite news|last1=Wong|first1=D.|title=A treasure trove from Miss Lou|url=http://www.thespec.com/news-story/2174025-a-treasure-trove-from-miss-lou/|accessdate=28 November 2015|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=Feb 14, 2011}}</ref> [[Pierre Berton]],<ref name=\"McKillop\">{{cite book|last1=McKillop|first1=A.B.|title=Pierre Berton a biography|date=2010|publisher=Emblem|location=Toronto|isbn=9781551996226|page=678|edition=Unabridged.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6QmQvocn4IYC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> [[Austin Clarke (novelist)|Austin Clarke]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Friends, colleagues pay tribute to Austin Clarke|url=http://sharenews.com/friends-colleagues-pay-tribute-to-austin-clarke/|website=ShareNews.com|publisher=Share Newspaper|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> [[Marian Engel]],<ref name=\"Kavanagh\">{{cite journal|last1=Kavanagh|first1=Afra|title=Ambivalence and Intertextuality in Marian Engel's The Glassy Sea: What the Archives Reveal|journal=Journal of Canadian Studies|date=2006|volume=40|issue=2|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/login?auth=0&type=summary&url=/journals/journal_of_canadian_studies/v040/40.2kavanagh.html|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> [[Basil H. Johnston]]<ref name=\"Nolan\">{{cite news|last1=Nolan|first1=Daniel|title=Ojibwa author Johnson donates papers to McMaster|url=http://www.thespec.com/news-story/4124929-ojibwa-author-johnson-donates-papers-to-mcmaster/|accessdate=5 February 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=September 26, 2013}}</ref> and [[Farley Mowat]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rinehart|first1=Dianne|title=Farley Mowat, acclaimed Canadian author, dead at 92|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2014/05/07/farley_mowat_acclaimed_canadian_author_dead_at_92.html|accessdate=31 January 2016|publisher=Toronto Star|date=May 7, 2014}}</ref> and [[singer-songwriters]] [[Bruce Cockburn]],<ref name=\"Carter\">{{cite news|last1=Carter|first1=Adam|title=Bruce Cockburn donates archives to McMaster University|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/hamilton/bruce-cockburn-donates-archives-to-mcmaster-university-1.1373187|accessdate=31 January 2016|publisher=CBC|date=May 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rockingham|first1=Graham|title=Bruce Cockburn donates his archives to McMaster|url=http://www.thespec.com/whatson-story/2550392-bruce-cockburn-donates-his-archives-to-mcmaster/|accessdate=5 February 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=May 3, 2013}}</ref> [[Ian Thomas (Canadian musician)|Ian Thomas]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rockingham|first1=Graham|title=The Thomas crowned affair: Local music superstar joins McMaster archives|url=http://www.thespec.com/whatson-story/4503524-the-thomas-crowned-affair-local-music-superstar-joins-mcmaster-archives/|accessdate=31 January 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=May 7, 2014}}</ref> and [[Jackie Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rockingham|first1=Graham|title=Jackie Washington, 89: Hamilton jazz icon|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2009/06/30/jackie_washington_89_hamilton_jazz_icon.html|accessdate=5 February 2016|publisher=Toronto Star|date=June 3, 2009}}</ref> A sample of [[Alice Munro]]'s handwriting, whose letters appears in the fonds of publishers [[Macmillan Canada]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Macmillan Company of Canada fonds: Part IV. Sixth accrual (Accession No. 06-1993)|url=http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/findaids/findaids/m/macmilla.06.htm|website=McMaster University Library|publisher=The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> and [[McClelland & Stewart]],<ref>{{cite web|title=McClelland & Stewart Ltd. Sixth Accrual (accession 02-2006)|url=http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/findaids/findaids/m/mcstew.06.htm|website=McMaster University Library|publisher=The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> appeared on a commemorative stamp released by [[Canada Post]] in 2015.<ref name=\"McNeil\">{{cite news|last1=McNeil|first1=Mark|title=Munro stamp taps into McMaster's archives|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=July 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPersonal papers and research collections of non-Canadian figures are equally well represented by holdings pertaining to [[Samuel Beckett]],<ref name=\"CP72\">{{cite news|title=Mowatt Discussing Sale of Works|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WdPnEvbEKgQC|accessdate=2 February 2016|agency=Ottawa Citizen|date=January 6, 1972}}</ref> [[Vera Brittain]], [[Thomas Carlyle]] and [[George Catlin (political scientist)|Sir George Catlin]].<ref name=\"Colombo\">{{cite book|last1=Colombo|first1=John Robert|title=Canadian literary landmarks|date=1984|publisher=Hounslow Press|location=Willowdale, Ont., Canada|isbn=9780888820730|page=124|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WdPnEvbEKgQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> The Division of Archives and Research Collection also holds the only surviving manuscript of [[Anthony Burgess]]' ''[[A Clockwork Orange (novel)|A Clockwork Orange]]''. The manuscript, along with several of Burgess' early works, was acquired by McMaster as a result of Ready's persistence and eventual friendship with the author. McMaster's copy is of particular interest because it includes the [[A Clockwork Orange (novel)#Omission of the final chapter|final chapter]] that was omitted by American publishers of the work. The manuscript contains an annotation in Burgess' hand that reads \"Should we end here?\", indicating that he questioned its inclusion.<ref name=Humphreys>{{cite news|last1=Humphreys|first1=Adrian|title=A clockwork original: McMaster University bought manuscript of iconic novel for $250|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/a-clockwork-orange-original-manuscript|accessdate=6 January 2016|publisher=National Post|date=November 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOther items held by the Archives include [[sheet music]] from the First World War,<ref name=\"McNeil2\">{{cite news|last1=McNeil|first1=Mark|title=Dusting off forgotten songs from the Great War|url=http://www.thespec.com/news-story/4956156-dusting-off-forgotten-songs-from-the-great-war/|accessdate=22 February 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=4 November 2015}}</ref> historical postcards,<ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite news|last1=Thompson|first1=Nicole|title=McMaster crowd-sources archival postcard project|url=http://www.thespec.com/news-story/5815795-mcmaster-crowd-sources-archival-postcard-project/|accessdate=22 February 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=27 August 2015}}</ref> and a [[figure skating]] collection consisting of books, programs, photographs and postcards.<ref name=\"Milton\">{{cite news|last1=Milton|first1=Steve|title=Figure skating collection put on ice: Former Mac archivist donates figure skating collection|url=http://www.thespec.com/sports-story/6245527-former-mac-archivist-donates-figure-skating-collection/|accessdate=22 February 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=23 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===The Bertrand Russell Archives===\n[[File:Bertrand Russell photo.jpg|thumb|Russell in 1936]]\nMcMaster University is home to the Bertrand Russell Archives. Manuscripts, correspondence, newspaper clippings and other textual records, in addition to photographs and audio visual resources, make up the more than 140 meters of material held by the Archives.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bertrand Russell fonds|url=http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/findaids/fonds/r/russell.htm|website=McMaster University Library|publisher=The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> Russell's personal library and furniture from his home in [[Penrhyndeudraeth]], [[Wales]] are also housed at McMaster.<ref name=\"Spadoni\">{{cite journal|last1=Spadoni|first1=Carl|last2=Harley|first2=David|title=Bertrand Russell's Library|journal=The Journal of Library History|date=1985|volume=20|issue=1|pages=25\u201345|jstor=25541563|publisher=University of Texas Press}}</ref> Russell's letters, totalling approximately 50,000,<ref name=\"Vowles\">{{cite news|last1=Vowles|first1=Andrew|title=The Original Purchase of the Russell Archives|url=http://www.mcmaster.ca/russdocs/purchase.htm|accessdate=3 February 2016|publisher=The McMaster Courier|date=1994}}</ref> provide insight about his personal and political dealings addressing topics such as his love live, his thoughts on teaching and pacifism, and his experiences in prison.<ref name=\"McArthur\">{{cite news|last1=McArthur|first1=Doug|title=Bertrand Russell|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6IEuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h6AFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1124%2C7174167|accessdate=3 February 2016|publisher=Montreal Gazette|date=February 28, 1970}}</ref> [[Joseph Conrad]], [[T.S. Eliot]], [[Nikita Khrushchev]], [[Lady Constance Malleson]], [[Ho Chi Minh]], [[Jean-Paul Sartre]], [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]] and [[Dorothy Maud Wrinch]] are among Russell's numerous correspondents.<ref>{{cite web|title=BRACERS' Correspondents|url=https://bracers.maclibraries.ca/php/correspondents.php|publisher=McMaster University Library|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nRussell's personal papers were purchased in 1968 for $520,000, with the first transfer of records consisting of 11 filing cabinets and 15 metal trunks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blackwell Again Tackling Job of Assembling Russell Papers|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QjdQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=clYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=926%2C3734554|accessdate=3 February 2016|publisher=Quebec Chronicle-Telegraph|date=Nov 29, 1968}}</ref> At the time, it was the most money spent on the personal papers of one person, topping what was paid for the personal papers of [[Leon Trotsky]] and [[W. B. Yeats]].<ref name=Grescoe/><ref>{{cite news|title=Canada Gets Writings of Lord Russell|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fi8xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lgEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7032%2C3142161|accessdate=3 February 2016|publisher=Toledo Blade|date=March 31, 1968}}</ref> That a Canadian university was able to secure Russell's papers has been linked to his disapproval of the United States' role in Vietnam.<ref name=Grescoe/><ref name=\"Cowan\">{{cite news|last1=Cowan|first1=Edward|title=Lord Russell's Papers to Canada|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sN8jAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EygEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2413%2C2361913|accessdate=3 February 2016|publisher=Milwaukee Journal|date=Oct 5, 1968}}</ref> There was, however, interest from American universities, most notably the [[University of Texas]], which dried up after an erroneous report in ''[[Newsweek]]'' indicated that Russell intended to use the funds to support war efforts in North Vietnam. Selling his papers was, in actuality, a means to support the work of the [[Bertrand Russell Peace Foundation]].<ref name=\"Griffin\">{{cite web|last1=Griffin|first1=Nicholas|title=How the Russell Papers Came to McMaster|url=http://www.lehman.cuny.edu/deanhum/philosophy/BRSQ/04aug/griffin.htm|publisher=The Bertrand Russell Society Quarterly|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cite web|title=Archives & Research Collections homepage|url=https://library.mcmaster.ca/archives|publisher=McMaster University Library|accessdate=20 April 2020}}\n{{cite web|title=Archives & Research Collections database|url=http://archives.mcmaster.ca/|publisher=McMaster University Library|accessdate=13 April 2016}}\n\n{{coord|43.262831|N|79.917598|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Archives in Canada]]\n[[Category:McMaster University]]\n\n{{Authority control |LCCN=n/78/041337 |VIAF=158200074 }}\n", "text_old": "__NOTOC__\n{{Infobox library\n| name               = William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections\n| logo               = <!-- file name only (no Image: or File:) -->\n| logo_size          = \n| logo_alt           = \n| image              = File:Reading room in The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections in Mills Memorial Library at McMaster University.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| country            = Canada\n| type               = Academic\n| scope              = \n| established        = \n| ref_legal_mandate  = \n| location           = Mills Memorial Library, Hamilton, Ontario\n| coordinates        = \n| branch_of          = [[McMaster University Library]]\n| num_branches       = \n| items_collected    = \n| collection_size    = \n| criteria           = \n| legal_deposit      = \n| req_to_access      = \n| annual_circulation = \n| pop_served         = \n| members            = \n| budget             = \n| director           = \n| num_employees      = \n| website            = http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/\n| references         = \n| embed              = \n| module             = \n}}\nThe '''William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections''' is the principal repository for rare books, archives, maps and historical material at [[McMaster University]]. Developed to support teaching, research and scholarship, its holdings reflect [[fonds]] and collections pertaining to Canadian literature, politics, popular culture and business history, in addition to war and peace in the 20th century with an emphasis on the [[Holocaust]] and [[Resistance movement|Resistance]]. It also holds a collection of eighteenth century books and journals, and is home to the [[Bertrand Russell]] Archives. Part of the [[McMaster University Library]] system, the Division of Archives and Research Collections is located in Mills Memorial Library.<ref name=About>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/about|website=McMaster University Library|publisher=The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections|accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Division of Archives and Research Collections is named after William Ready who served as University Librarian from 1966 until his retirement in 1979.<ref name=About/> In 2002 the Archives was awarded the [[Archives Association of Ontario]]'s Institutional Award in recognition of its strong archival program and service to the community.<ref>{{cite news |title=Library\u2019s William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections Division Receives AAO Award |url=https://dailynews.mcmaster.ca/articles/librarys-william-ready-division-of-archives-and-research-collections-division-receives-aao-award/ |accessdate=31 December 2018 |work=Daily News |publisher=McMaster University |date=24 June 2002}}</ref>\n\n===William Ready===\nWilliam Bernard Ready (pronounced Reedy) was born on September 16, 1914 in [[Cardiff, Wales]] to James Ready and Nora Hart. He obtained a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from the [[University of Wales]] in 1937, a [[Master of Arts]] from the [[University of Manitoba]] in 1949 and a [[Master of Library and Information Science|Master of Library Science]] from the [[University of Western Ontario]] in 1970, in addition to several diplomas related to archives and library administration. Ready married Bessie Dyer (1917-2007) on April 25, 1945 and together they had six children.<ref name=Reginald>{{cite book|author1=R. Reginald|author2=Douglas Menville|author3=Mary A. Burgess|editor1-last=Menville|editor1-first=Douglas|editor2-last=Burgess|editor2-first=Mary A.|title=Science Fiction and Fantasy Literature, Volume 2|date=2010|publisher=Wildside Press LLC|pages=1043\u20131044|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nPYfqEbfrsC&source=gbs_navlinks_s|isbn=9780941028783|accessdate=6 January 2016|ref=Reginald}}</ref><ref name=BessieObit>{{cite web|title=Deaths & Funerals - Ready, Bessie|url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=3cbc97ae-1a69-47c5-aa19-0b566689f62f|website=Canada.com|publisher=Times Colonist (Victoria)|accessdate=20 January 2016|location=Victoria, British Columbia|date=October 3, 2007}}</ref>\n\nReady considered himself a \"working librarian\" and rejected the academic side of librarianship in favour of hands-on work and collection development <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Neill|first1=S. D.|title=Review of Files on Parade: A Memoir by William B. Ready|journal=[[The Journal of Library History]]|date=1983|volume= 18|issue= 4|pages=521\u2013523|jstor=25541478|publisher=University of Texas Press}}</ref> He was known for his enterprising<ref name=Humphreys/> and cunning<ref name=Grescoe>{{cite news|last1=Grescoe|first1=Paul|title=William Ready is Cunning, Devious, Relentless, Ruthless (and sneaky)|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19710424&id=C5gkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PqEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2566,5958655&hl=en|accessdate=6 January 2016|newspaper=[[The Montreal Gazette]]|date=April 24, 1971|pages=28\u201329}}</ref> approach to building and managing archives and research collections. Having read and enjoyed ''[[The Hobbit]]'', Ready asked a London-based book dealer to contact [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] about acquiring his works for Marquette University. Concerned about his retirement, Tolkien initially agreed to sell a selection of manuscripts. Further negotiation led to Marquette's acquisition of the manuscripts for ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'' and ''[[The Hobbit]]'', among others, amounting to more than 11,000 pages.<ref name=Antlfinger>{{cite news|last1=Antlfinger|first1=Carrie|title=Marquette University holds 'Lord of the Rings,' other Tolkien works|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dukfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=p9kEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1486%2C2154990|accessdate=21 January 2016|newspaper=[[Nevada Herald]]|date=February 3, 2002|page=8A}}</ref> During the same period Ready also secured the personal papers of social activist [[Dorothy Day]].<ref name=Heinen>{{cite journal|last1=Heinen|first1=Tom|title=Diaries reveal another Dorothy|journal=[[Journal Sentinel]]|date=May 7, 2008|url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/education/29522229.html|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=Wire>{{cite news|title=Dorothy Day \u2014 Catholic Worker Collection|url=http://marquettewire.org/2626374/tribune/tribune-news/sheen-mean-on-social-work/|accessdate=21 January 2016|newspaper=Marquette Wire|date=September 18, 2003}}</ref> As University Librarian at McMaster he played an instrumental role in securing numerous high-profile collections, most notably the archives of philosopher and political activist Bertrand Russell.<ref name=Grescoe/><ref name=Griffin/>\n\nReady died in [[Victoria, British Columbia]] on September 12, 1981, two years after retiring from McMaster. His autobiography, ''Files on Parade'', was published posthumously in 1982.<ref name=Antlfinger/><ref name=McFonds>{{cite web|title=William Ready fonds|url=http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/findaids/fonds/r/ready.htm|website=McMaster University Library|publisher=The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\n\nThe holdings of the Division of Archives and Research Collections reflect a broad spectrum of Canadian popular culture ranging from the records of  Canadian [[Publishing|publishers]]<ref name=\"HPCP\">{{cite web|title=About|url=http://hpcanpub.mcmaster.ca/|website=Historical Perspectives on Canadian Publishing|publisher=McMaster|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> and advertisers<ref>{{cite news|last1=Foda|first1=Farzeen|last2=Cumerlato|first2=Sam|title=Collection of popular media donated to Mac|url=http://www.thesil.ca/collection-of-popular-media-donated-to-mac|accessdate=5 February 2016|publisher=The Silhouette|date=February 16, 2012}}</ref> to the personal papers of internationally recognized authors and musicians. Included are writers [[Louise Bennett-Coverley]],<ref name=Wong>{{cite news|last1=Wong|first1=D.|title=A treasure trove from Miss Lou|url=http://www.thespec.com/news-story/2174025-a-treasure-trove-from-miss-lou/|accessdate=28 November 2015|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=Feb 14, 2011}}</ref> [[Pierre Berton]],<ref name=\"McKillop\">{{cite book|last1=McKillop|first1=A.B.|title=Pierre Berton a biography|date=2010|publisher=Emblem|location=Toronto|isbn=9781551996226|page=678|edition=Unabridged.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6QmQvocn4IYC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> [[Austin Clarke (novelist)|Austin Clarke]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Friends, colleagues pay tribute to Austin Clarke|url=http://sharenews.com/friends-colleagues-pay-tribute-to-austin-clarke/|website=ShareNews.com|publisher=Share Newspaper|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> [[Marian Engel]],<ref name=\"Kavanagh\">{{cite journal|last1=Kavanagh|first1=Afra|title=Ambivalence and Intertextuality in Marian Engel's The Glassy Sea: What the Archives Reveal|journal=Journal of Canadian Studies|date=2006|volume=40|issue=2|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/login?auth=0&type=summary&url=/journals/journal_of_canadian_studies/v040/40.2kavanagh.html|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> [[Basil H. Johnston]]<ref name=\"Nolan\">{{cite news|last1=Nolan|first1=Daniel|title=Ojibwa author Johnson donates papers to McMaster|url=http://www.thespec.com/news-story/4124929-ojibwa-author-johnson-donates-papers-to-mcmaster/|accessdate=5 February 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=September 26, 2013}}</ref> and [[Farley Mowat]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rinehart|first1=Dianne|title=Farley Mowat, acclaimed Canadian author, dead at 92|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2014/05/07/farley_mowat_acclaimed_canadian_author_dead_at_92.html|accessdate=31 January 2016|publisher=Toronto Star|date=May 7, 2014}}</ref> and [[singer-songwriters]] [[Bruce Cockburn]],<ref name=\"Carter\">{{cite news|last1=Carter|first1=Adam|title=Bruce Cockburn donates archives to McMaster University|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/hamilton/bruce-cockburn-donates-archives-to-mcmaster-university-1.1373187|accessdate=31 January 2016|publisher=CBC|date=May 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rockingham|first1=Graham|title=Bruce Cockburn donates his archives to McMaster|url=http://www.thespec.com/whatson-story/2550392-bruce-cockburn-donates-his-archives-to-mcmaster/|accessdate=5 February 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=May 3, 2013}}</ref> [[Ian Thomas (Canadian musician)|Ian Thomas]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rockingham|first1=Graham|title=The Thomas crowned affair: Local music superstar joins McMaster archives|url=http://www.thespec.com/whatson-story/4503524-the-thomas-crowned-affair-local-music-superstar-joins-mcmaster-archives/|accessdate=31 January 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=May 7, 2014}}</ref> and [[Jackie Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rockingham|first1=Graham|title=Jackie Washington, 89: Hamilton jazz icon|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2009/06/30/jackie_washington_89_hamilton_jazz_icon.html|accessdate=5 February 2016|publisher=Toronto Star|date=June 3, 2009}}</ref> A sample of [[Alice Munro]]'s handwriting, whose letters appears in the fonds of publishers [[Macmillan Canada]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Macmillan Company of Canada fonds: Part IV. Sixth accrual (Accession No. 06-1993)|url=http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/findaids/findaids/m/macmilla.06.htm|website=McMaster University Library|publisher=The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> and [[McClelland & Stewart]],<ref>{{cite web|title=McClelland & Stewart Ltd. Sixth Accrual (accession 02-2006)|url=http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/findaids/findaids/m/mcstew.06.htm|website=McMaster University Library|publisher=The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> appeared on a commemorative stamp released by [[Canada Post]] in 2015.<ref name=\"McNeil\">{{cite news|last1=McNeil|first1=Mark|title=Munro stamp taps into McMaster's archives|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=July 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPersonal papers and research collections of non-Canadian figures are equally well represented by holdings pertaining to [[Samuel Beckett]],<ref name=\"CP72\">{{cite news|title=Mowatt Discussing Sale of Works|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WdPnEvbEKgQC|accessdate=2 February 2016|agency=Ottawa Citizen|date=January 6, 1972}}</ref> [[Vera Brittain]], [[Thomas Carlyle]] and [[George Catlin (political scientist)|Sir George Catlin]].<ref name=\"Colombo\">{{cite book|last1=Colombo|first1=John Robert|title=Canadian literary landmarks|date=1984|publisher=Hounslow Press|location=Willowdale, Ont., Canada|isbn=9780888820730|page=124|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WdPnEvbEKgQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> The Division of Archives and Research Collection also holds the only surviving manuscript of [[Anthony Burgess]]' ''[[A Clockwork Orange (novel)|A Clockwork Orange]]''. The manuscript, along with several of Burgess' early works, was acquired by McMaster as a result of Ready's persistence and eventual friendship with the author. McMaster's copy is of particular interest because it includes the [[A Clockwork Orange (novel)#Omission of the final chapter|final chapter]] that was omitted by American publishers of the work. The manuscript contains an annotation in Burgess' hand that reads \"Should we end here?\", indicating that he questioned its inclusion.<ref name=Humphreys>{{cite news|last1=Humphreys|first1=Adrian|title=A clockwork original: McMaster University bought manuscript of iconic novel for $250|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/a-clockwork-orange-original-manuscript|accessdate=6 January 2016|publisher=National Post|date=November 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOther items held by the Archives include [[sheet music]] from the First World War,<ref name=\"McNeil2\">{{cite news|last1=McNeil|first1=Mark|title=Dusting off forgotten songs from the Great War|url=http://www.thespec.com/news-story/4956156-dusting-off-forgotten-songs-from-the-great-war/|accessdate=22 February 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=4 November 2015}}</ref> historical postcards,<ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite news|last1=Thompson|first1=Nicole|title=McMaster crowd-sources archival postcard project|url=http://www.thespec.com/news-story/5815795-mcmaster-crowd-sources-archival-postcard-project/|accessdate=22 February 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=27 August 2015}}</ref> and a [[figure skating]] collection consisting of books, programs, photographs and postcards.<ref name=\"Milton\">{{cite news|last1=Milton|first1=Steve|title=Figure skating collection put on ice: Former Mac archivist donates figure skating collection|url=http://www.thespec.com/sports-story/6245527-former-mac-archivist-donates-figure-skating-collection/|accessdate=22 February 2016|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|date=23 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===The Bertrand Russell Archives===\n[[File:Bertrand Russell photo.jpg|thumb|Russell in 1936]]\nMcMaster University is home to the Bertrand Russell Archives. Manuscripts, correspondence, newspaper clippings and other textual records, in addition to photographs and audio visual resources, make up the more than 140 meters of material held by the Archives.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bertrand Russell fonds|url=http://library.mcmaster.ca/archives/findaids/fonds/r/russell.htm|website=McMaster University Library|publisher=The William Ready Division of Archives and Research Collections|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> Russell's personal library and furniture from his home in [[Penrhyndeudraeth]], [[Wales]] are also housed at McMaster.<ref name=\"Spadoni\">{{cite journal|last1=Spadoni|first1=Carl|last2=Harley|first2=David|title=Bertrand Russell's Library|journal=The Journal of Library History|date=1985|volume=20|issue=1|pages=25\u201345|jstor=25541563|publisher=University of Texas Press}}</ref> Russell's letters, totalling approximately 50,000,<ref name=\"Vowles\">{{cite news|last1=Vowles|first1=Andrew|title=The Original Purchase of the Russell Archives|url=http://www.mcmaster.ca/russdocs/purchase.htm|accessdate=3 February 2016|publisher=The McMaster Courier|date=1994}}</ref> provide insight about his personal and political dealings addressing topics such as his love live, his thoughts on teaching and pacifism, and his experiences in prison.<ref name=\"McArthur\">{{cite news|last1=McArthur|first1=Doug|title=Bertrand Russell|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6IEuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h6AFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1124%2C7174167|accessdate=3 February 2016|publisher=Montreal Gazette|date=February 28, 1970}}</ref> [[Joseph Conrad]], [[T.S. Eliot]], [[Nikita Khrushchev]], [[Lady Constance Malleson]], [[Ho Chi Minh]], [[Jean-Paul Sartre]], [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]] and [[Dorothy Maud Wrinch]] are among Russell's numerous correspondents.<ref>{{cite web|title=BRACERS' Correspondents|url=https://bracers.maclibraries.ca/php/correspondents.php|publisher=McMaster University Library|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nRussell's personal papers were purchased in 1968 for $520,000, with the first transfer of records consisting of 11 filing cabinets and 15 metal trunks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blackwell Again Tackling Job of Assembling Russell Papers|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QjdQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=clYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=926%2C3734554|accessdate=3 February 2016|publisher=Quebec Chronicle-Telegraph|date=Nov 29, 1968}}</ref> At the time, it was the most money spent on the personal papers of one person, topping what was paid for the personal papers of [[Leon Trotsky]] and [[W. B. Yeats]].<ref name=Grescoe/><ref>{{cite news|title=Canada Gets Writings of Lord Russell|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fi8xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lgEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7032%2C3142161|accessdate=3 February 2016|publisher=Toledo Blade|date=March 31, 1968}}</ref> That a Canadian university was able to secure Russell's papers has been linked to his disapproval of the United States' role in Vietnam.<ref name=Grescoe/><ref name=\"Cowan\">{{cite news|last1=Cowan|first1=Edward|title=Lord Russell's Papers to Canada|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sN8jAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EygEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2413%2C2361913|accessdate=3 February 2016|publisher=Milwaukee Journal|date=Oct 5, 1968}}</ref> There was, however, interest from American universities, most notably the [[University of Texas]], which dried up after an erroneous report in ''[[Newsweek]]'' indicated that Russell intended to use the funds to support war efforts in North Vietnam. Selling his papers was, in actuality, a means to support the work of the [[Bertrand Russell Peace Foundation]].<ref name=\"Griffin\">{{cite web|last1=Griffin|first1=Nicholas|title=How the Russell Papers Came to McMaster|url=http://www.lehman.cuny.edu/deanhum/philosophy/BRSQ/04aug/griffin.htm|publisher=The Bertrand Russell Society Quarterly|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cite web|title=Archives & Research Collections database|url=http://archives.mcmaster.ca/|publisher=McMaster University Library|accessdate=13 April 2016}}\n\n{{coord|43.262831|N|79.917598|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Archives in Canada]]\n[[Category:McMaster University]]\n\n{{Authority control |LCCN=n/78/041337 |VIAF=158200074 }}\n", "name_user": "Widgetb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:added link to department homepage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Ready_Division_of_Archives_and_Research_Collections"}
{"title_page": "The Masked Singer (American TV series)", "text_new": "{{About||the current season|The Masked Singer (American season 3)}}\n{{short description|American reality singing competition television show}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name         = The Masked Singer\n| image             = Masked Singer USA Logo.png\n| image_alt         = Title card of ''The Masked Singer''\n| caption           = \n| genre             = [[Reality competition]]<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\">{{cite web|last=Piester|first=Lauren|title=The Secrets of ''The Masked Singer'': Everything We've Learned About TV's Most Mysterious Show|url=https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/1019279/the-secrets-of-the-masked-singer-everything-we-ve-learned-about-tv-s-most-mysterious-show|date=February 27, 2019|website=[[E!#E! Online|E!]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703044452/https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/1019279/the-secrets-of-the-masked-singer-everything-we-ve-learned-about-tv-s-most-mysterious-show|archive-date=July 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| creator            = \n| based_on           = {{based_on|''[[King of Mask Singer]]''|[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]]}}\n| developer          = [[Craig Plestis]]\n| director           = {{unbulleted list|Alex Rudzinski|Brad Duns}}\n| presenter          = [[Nick Cannon]]\n| starring           = {{unbulleted list|[[Ken Jeong]]|[[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]|[[Nicole Scherzinger]]|[[Robin Thicke]]}}\n| narrated           = \n| composer           = \n| executive_producer = {{unbulleted list|Craig Plestis ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1\u2013)|Izzie Pick Ibarra ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1\u2013)|Rosie Seitchik ({{abbr|s.|season}} 2\u2013)|Nick Cannon ({{abbr|s.|season}} 3\u2013)}}\n| producer           = \n| company            = {{unbulleted list|[[Endemol Shine North America]] ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1)|Fox Alternative Entertainment ({{abbr|s.|season}} 2\u2013)}}\n| distributor        = {{unbulleted list|[[Fox Corporation]]|Propagate Content}}\n| location           = \n| camera             = \n| runtime            = 42\u201385 minutes\n| opentheme          = {{theme_song|\"[[Who Are You (The Who song)|Who Are You]]\"|[[The Who]]}}\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| network            = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| channel            = \n| picture_format     = \n| audio_format       = \n| first_run          = \n| released           = \n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2019|1|2}}\n| last_aired         = present\n| num_seasons        = 3\n| num_episodes       = 36<!-- as of April 15, 2020 -->\n| list_episodes      = List of The Masked Singer (American TV series) episodes\n| preceded_by        = \n| related            = {{unbulletedlist|''The Masked Singer: After the Mask''|''The Masked Dancer''}}\n| website            = https://www.fox.com/the-masked-singer/\n| production_website = https://www.smartdogmedia.com/the-masked-singer\n}}\n\n'''''The Masked Singer''''' is an American [[Reality competition|reality singing competition]] television series featuring celebrities in head-to-toe costumes and face masks which conceal their identities from other contestants, panelists, and an audience. After they perform a cover of a famous song, the panelists and audience vote for their favorite performances and the celebrity with the fewest votes is eliminated from the competition, taking off their mask and revealing their identity. The [[Nick Cannon]]-hosted show was the first version of the ''[[Masked Singer]]'' franchise to air outside of Asia, premiering on January 2, 2019, on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]. \n\nThe show employs four permanent panelists\u2014[[Ken Jeong]], [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]], [[Nicole Scherzinger]], and [[Robin Thicke]]\u2014to make guesses as to who the celebrities could be after each performance, with a guest panelist often appearing alongside them. They have received mixed reviews from critics, as have the series' format and production value. However, the costumes have attracted praise. They are designed by Marina Toybina and built by a team of two dozen people who incorporate both [[Haute couture|traditional fashion]] elements and innovative solutions into each costume that help the performer sing clearly and move freely on stage. In recognition of the show's costume design, it has won a [[Costume Designers Guild#Costume Designers Guild Awards|Costume Designers Guild Award]] and received a [[Creative Arts Emmy Award]] nomination.\n\nExtensive measures are taken by the show's production crew to prevent the identities of the contestants from leaking before an episode airs. The episodes themselves have received high television ratings; during the [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319 television season]], the show was the highest rated new series among adults 18\u201349, leading some commentators to consider the show at the forefront of a new reality television era in the United States. It has spawned numerous spin-offs, including an upcoming dance version and a national tour. Subsequent adaptations of the ''Masked Singer'' franchise worldwide have been credited to the show's success, as has an interest in developing other television series centered on costumes. \n\nThe winners of the first and second seasons were [[T-Pain]] and [[Wayne Brady]], respectively. The series is currently in its [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|third season]] which premiered as the [[Super Bowl LIV]] [[List of Super Bowl lead-out programs|lead-out program]] on February 2, 2020. During an interview prior to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Rob Wade, President of Alternative Entertainment and Specials at Fox, confirmed that future seasons of the show are planned.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 6\">{{cite web|last=Daswani|first=Mansha|title=Fox Entertainment's Rob Wade|url=https://worldscreen.com/tvformats/fox-entertainments-rob-wade/|website=TV Formats|date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416012653/https://worldscreen.com/tvformats/fox-entertainments-rob-wade/|archive-date=April 15, 2020|url-status=live|quote=And then ''The Masked Dancer'' is coming up soon. And future cycles of ''The Masked Singer.''}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{Listen|pos=left|filename=Masked Singer US Monster Voiceover.ogg|title=Monster voiceover|description=A sample of a typical voiceover in a clue package showing how modulation is used to disguise the actual identity of the performers on the show while they give hints about their backgrounds.|format=[[Ogg]]}}\nA group of [[Celebrity|celebrities]] compete on the show anonymously in costumes over a series of episodes. The specific format of the competition varies by season and episode, but generally, most episodes feature four to six celebrities performing a cover of a famous song, with the audience and panelists voting for their favorite. The celebrity with the fewest votes in that episode is eliminated from the competition and must take off their mask to reveal their identity. This process of elimination continues for a set number of episodes until three contestants remain, and one is declared the winner after they perform again. There is no cash prize for winning, rather, the celebrity wins the \"golden mask trophy.\"<ref name=\"PeopleS3\">{{cite web|last=Stone|first=Natalie|title=''The Masked Singer'' Renewed for Season 3, to Premiere After 2020 Super Bowl|url=https://people.com/tv/the-masked-singer-renewed-for-season-3/|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220055111/https://people.com/tv/the-masked-singer-renewed-for-season-3/|archive-date=February 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=From the Banana to the Taco, ''The Masked Singer'' Season 3 Costumes Have Been Revealed|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/masked-singer-season-3-costumes-first-look-photos-1203485426/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303231616/https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/masked-singer-season-3-costumes-first-look-photos-1203485426/|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince the second season, the series has also featured a \"smackdown\" round in some episodes in which the two competitors with the fewest votes from their first performances sing again with a second vote occurring, and the performer with the fewest votes is then eliminated.<ref name=\"USA Sep 24\">{{cite web|last=Keveney|first=Bill|title=''The Masked Singer'': Producers promise trickier clues, bigger names and crazier costumes|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/09/24/masked-singer-tweaks-rules-for-16-contestant-season-2/2424261001/|website=[[USA Today]]|date=September 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310055251/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/09/24/masked-singer-tweaks-rules-for-16-contestant-season-2/2424261001/|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the third season, the contestants were divided into three subgroups who each performed on three consecutive episodes before returning to the unified performance format afterwards.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\">{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/television/8549443/masked-singer-showrunner-season-3-changes-surprises-interview|title=''Masked Singer'' Showrunner Promises Big Changes for Season 3, Says Cast is \"Unbelievably Interesting\"|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207084115/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/television/8549443/masked-singer-showrunner-season-3-changes-surprises-interview|archive-date=February 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the singing competition, hints to each masked singer's identity are offered during the show and are referred to as a \"clue package\" by the panelists. Such clues may feature cryptic allusions to what the celebrity is known for, or may be more direct references. Pre-taped interviews are also given as hints and feature the celebrities' electronically masked voices. The panelists are given time to speculate the identity of the singer after their performance and are allowed to ask questions or request that the host offer additional clues.<ref name=\"PeopleS3\"/>\n\n==Panelists and host==\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 450\n| total_height\n| align = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1   = Ken Jeong March 2015.jpg\n| alt1     = Ken Jeong\n| caption1 = [[Ken Jeong]]\n| image2   = Jenny McCarthy at E3 2006.jpg\n| alt2     = Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg\n| caption2 = [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]\n| image3   = Nicole Scherzinger 2012.jpg\n| alt3     = Nicole Scherzinger\n| caption3 = [[Nicole Scherzinger]]\n| image4   = Robin Thicke 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| alt4     = Robin Thicke\n| caption4 = [[Robin Thicke]]\n| image5   = Nick Cannon by David Shankbone.jpg\n| alt5     = Nick Cannon\n| caption5 = [[Nick Cannon]] \n}}\n\nSince the first season, the permanent panel has consisted of actor and comedian [[Ken Jeong]], television personality [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]], recording artist [[Nicole Scherzinger]], and singer-songwriter [[Robin Thicke]], with [[Nick Cannon]] hosting the show.<ref name=\"VAR Aug 2\">{{cite web|last=Birnbaum|first=Debra|title=Fox Orders ''Masked Singer'' Reality Series; Nick Cannon to Host|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/fox-masked-singer-reality-series-nick-cannon-1202893337/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102132907/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/fox-masked-singer-reality-series-nick-cannon-1202893337/|archive-date=November 2, 2019|date=August 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThere are often guest panelists that appear as the fifth panelist on the series\u2014occasionally for multiple episodes. In the first season, they were [[Joel McHale]] (episodes 3\u20134), [[J. B. Smoove]] (episode 7), and [[Kenan Thompson]] (episodes 8 and 10). In the second season, they were [[Anthony Anderson]] (episode 6), [[Triumph the Insult Comic Dog]] ([[Robert Smigel]]; episode 7), McHale (episodes 8\u20139), and [[T-Pain]] (episode 10). In the third season, the guest panelists included [[Jamie Foxx]] (episode 1), [[Jason Biggs]] (episode 2), [[Leah Remini]] (episode 3), [[Gabriel Iglesias]] (episode 5), T-Pain (episode 6), McHale (episode 8), [[Will Arnett]] (episode 9), and [[Yvette Nicole Brown]] (episode 11), with [[Sharon Osbourne]] set to appear in the twelfth episode,<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-313/313A) \"The Mother Of All Final Face Offs, Part 2 / After the Mask: The Mother Of All Final Face Offs, Part 2\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200416fox01/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]}}</ref> [[Gordon Ramsay]] in the thirteenth,<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-314/314A) \"The Battle of The Sixes: The Final 6 / After the Mask: The Battle of The Sixes: The Final 6\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200416fox02/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]}}</ref> and [[Jeff Dye]] in the fourteenth.<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-315/315A) \"A Quarter Mask Crisis: The Quarter Finals / After the Mask: A Quarter Mask Crisis: The Quarter Finals\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200416fox06/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]}}</ref>\n\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; font-size:90%; width:30%;\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\"| Panelist timeline\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:15%;\"| Panelists\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"width:15%;\"| Seasons\n|-\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|1]]\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 2)|2]]\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|3]]\n|-\n| [[Ken Jeong]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Nicole Scherzinger]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Robin Thicke]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Joel McHale]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[J.B. Smoove]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Kenan Thompson]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Anthony Anderson]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Triumph the Comic Insult Dog]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[T-Pain]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jamie Foxx]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jason Biggs]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Leah Remini]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Gabriel Iglesias]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Will Arnett]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Yvette Nicole Brown]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Sharon Osbourne]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Gordon Ramsay]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jeff Dye]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|}\n\n==Production==\n===Conception and development===\n{{quote box|quote=So we're at a restaurant and my back is to the TV. My daughter said Dad, look at this, there's this crazy thing on. I turned around and all the diners were watching the TV screen. I saw a kangaroo in black pleather singing a pop song. At that moment I said, oh my gosh, I love this! It was bizarre. It was flypaper. It was in a foreign language and you didn't know what was going on, and it was still working. I found out that it was a hit format in Korea, it was a hit show in Thailand. And no one had the [U.S.] rights.|source=\u2014Plestis on the creation of ''The Masked Singer''<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\">{{cite magazine|last=Daswani|first=Mansha|title=Craig Plestis|url=https://issuu.com/worldscreen/docs/tv_formats_miptv_2019|page=38|magazine=TV Formats|date=April 2019|via=[[Issuu]]}}</ref>|align=right|width=35em}}\n\n''The Masked Singer'' is based on the popular<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\">{{cite web|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|title=''The Masked Singer'' Boss on Importance of Contestant Secrecy|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-contestant-secrecy-hippo-unmasked-1203089606/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706101843/https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-contestant-secrecy-hippo-unmasked-1203089606/|archive-date=July 6, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> South Korean series ''[[King of Mask Singer]]''. Television producer [[Craig Plestis]] explained that he first discovered the format during a visit to a small [[Studio City, Los Angeles]] Thai restaurant in October 2017.<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\"/><ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\">{{cite web|last=Ravindran|first=Manori|title=How ''Masked Singer'' is reviving costume-led formats|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/04/05/costume-drama/|website=Television Business International|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407120916/https://tbivision.com/2019/04/05/costume-drama/|archive-date=April 7, 2019|date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GH Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Keegan|first=Kayla|title=Going to a ''Masked Singer'' Taping Is Like Visiting a Top-Secret CIA Compound|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|website=[[Good Housekeeping]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405081745/https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|archive-date=April 5, 2020|date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> While waiting for dinner, he observed the other patrons staring at a television while an episode of the [[The Mask Singer (season 3)|third season]] of the [[The Mask Singer (Thai TV series)|Thai version]] of the show was playing. Intrigued, Plestis began to research the series and secured the rights to produce an American adaptation within one week in a deal brokered by his agent, Steve Wohl of [[Paradigm Talent Agency]]. He then called Fox executive Rob Wade on a Friday night to schedule a meeting with him the following Monday and worked to create a showcase during the weekend.<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\"/> According to Plestis, Wade was \"scared\" by the show but envisioned its potential. After successfully pitching the show to Wade under the condition that he \"could cast enough [[A-list]] celebrities,\"<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/><ref name=\"THR Jan 2\">{{cite web|last=Bentley|first=Jean|title=''The Masked Singer'': How the Fox Reality Show Scored Top Talent (and Kept It Secret)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/masked-singer-ep-explains-how-his-insane-reality-competition-made-it-air-1171775|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713155810/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/masked-singer-ep-explains-how-his-insane-reality-competition-made-it-air-1171775|archive-date=July 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Plestis began developing the series in November.<ref>{{cite web|last=White|first=Peter|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/fox-remaking-asian-singing-contest-the-masked-singer-1202206986/|title=Fox Developing Remake of Asian Talent Competition ''The Masked Singer''|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521062138/https://deadline.com/2017/11/fox-remaking-asian-singing-contest-the-masked-singer-1202206986/|archive-date=May 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn January 2018, executive producer Izzie Pick Ibarra became involved with the show to aid in the casting process and \"[[Americanization|Americanize]]\" the format. Rather than follow the South Korean version in which two singers perform in three rounds, with the winner of the final round facing the winner of the previous episode in an attempt to become the new \"Mask King,\" Ibarra opted to air one elimination per night, emphasize the clue packages and guessing component, and have the celebrities wear more extravagant costumes.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> Plestis agreed, wanting to create a [[story arc]] throughout the episodes and\u2014unlike the South Korean series\u2014be able to reuse the costumes.<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\"/> The series was officially ordered by Fox in August 2018.<ref name=\"VAR Aug 2\"/>\n\n[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]], the rightsholder of the ''Masked Singer'' format, lacked the ability to produce the series. As a result, the [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|first season]]  was produced by [[Endemol Shine North America]] due to Plestis' relationship with the studio. For the [[The Masked Singer (American season 2)|second season]], production transitioned to a new in-house studio, Fox Alternative Entertainment, and the show's budget was lowered as a result.<ref>{{cite web|last=Haynes|first=Dade|title=''The Masked Singer'' Renewed For Third Season, Gets Post-Super Bowl Slot On|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-masked-singer-season-3-to-premiere-after-super-bowl-liv-on-fox-1202613462/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830010304/https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-masked-singer-season-3-to-premiere-after-super-bowl-liv-on-fox-1202613462/|archive-date=August 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-launching-unscripted-studio-masked-singer-1209087|title=Fox Launching Unscripted Studio With ''The Masked Singer'' (Exclusive)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817034711/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-launching-unscripted-studio-masked-singer-1209087|archive-date=August 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Wade said this gave the network further creative control over the series and allowed it to sell merchandise, launch a national tour, and create spin-off show ''The Masked Dancer''.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 6\"/> Since the second and [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|third seasons]], respectively, Rosie Seitchik and Cannon have also served as executive producers.<ref>{{cite press release|title=All-New Special \"The Masked Singer: Super Sneak Peek\" to Air Sunday, September 15, on Fox|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2019/08/28/all-new-special-the-masked-singer-super-sneak-peek-to-air-sunday-september-15-on-fox-94001/20190828fox01/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|date=August 28, 2019|archive-url=http://archive.today/XApNp|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=''Beat Shazam'' Host Jamie Foxx Touches Down as a Guest Panelist in The Season Three Premiere of ''The Masked Singer'', Following Super Bowl LIV, Sunday, February 2, on Fox|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2020/01/07/beat-shazam-host-jamie-foxx-touches-down-as-a-guest-panelist-in-the-season-three-premiere-of-the-masked-singer-following-super-bowl-liv-sunday-february-2-on-fox-703210/20200107fox01/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]||publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|date=January 7, 2020|archive-url=http://archive.today/XApNp|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nIbarra was ecstatic when Cannon agreed to host the show, citing him as her number-one choice for the role because of his personality and experience. Regarding the panelists, she said the production team was less concerned with selecting those with an ability to critique participants' singing abilities than being able to create a comedic tone for the show as one of their goals was to reassure celebrities they would not be ridiculed for choosing to appear. Jeong was the first panelist to be signed on to the series due to his humour and pre-existing knowledge of the South Korean version, followed by McCarthy Wahlberg and Thicke, respectively, due to their enthusiasm regarding the concept, and Scherzinger for her positivity and experience as a singer.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/><ref name=\"THR Jan 2\"/> On March 28, 2019, Osbourne revealed on ''[[The Talk (talk show)|The Talk]]'' she was originally supposed to be signed on as a panelist for the series; those plans fell through after being contractually obligated to appear on ''[[The X Factor (British TV series)|The X Factor]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Furdyk|first=Brent|url=https://etcanada.com/news/435743/sharon-osbourne-shreds-simon-cowell-for-firing-her-from-the-x-factor-because-he-thought-i-was-too-old/|title=Sharon Osbourne Shreds Simon Cowell For Firing Her From ''The X Factor'' Because He \"Thought I Was Too Old\"|website=[[Entertainment Tonight Canada|ET Canada]]|date=March 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330152540/https://etcanada.com/news/435743/sharon-osbourne-shreds-simon-cowell-for-firing-her-from-the-x-factor-because-he-thought-i-was-too-old/|archive-date=March 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIbarra described casting for the series' first season as less difficult than she predicted due to her strategy of sending the possible participants sketches of costumes that might be featured on the series. She said many of the celebrities had emotional reactions when presented with the proposed costumes and that they were excited to use the show to reinvent their [[reputation|public image]]. [[T-Pain]], the winner of the first season, said he was skeptical about the series until he saw the costume choices, citing the opportunity to wear the Monster outfit as his motivation for participating in the show.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jensen|first=Erin|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/03/22/t-pain-masked-singer-winner-pitch/3244569002/|title=''Masked Singer'' winner T-Pain first deemed show \"probably the stupidest thing\" he'd heard|website=[[USA Today]]|date=March 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111040704/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/03/22/t-pain-masked-singer-winner-pitch/3244569002/|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Conversely, [[Wayne Brady]], the winner of the second season, was approached by producers to appear in the first season but turned them down after being confused about the show's concept.<ref name=\"VAR Dec 18\">{{cite web|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-winner-interview-wayne-brady-the-fox-season-2-1203447936/|title=''The Masked Singer'' Winner Interview: \"It's the First Time in My Life I Kept a Secret Months on End\"|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110134353/https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-winner-interview-wayne-brady-the-fox-season-2-1203447936/|archive-date=January 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Those who are not professional singers send the show's production crew clips of them singing as a quasi-audition before participating in the series.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/>\n\n===Security===\n[[File:Masked Singer Dont Talk to Me.png|thumb|left|alt=refer to caption|While on set, the participants wear an oversized sweatshirt with the words \"don't talk to me!\" on the front to keep their identities a secret.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/>]]\nBefore each of the competitors is unmasked, the show's staff undertakes significant security measures to prevent the participants' identities from leaking, many of which, according to Plestis, originate from his visits to the sets of the South Korean and Thai versions of the show.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> As a result, he says the series has two [[bible (screenwriting)|bibles]]: one related to the format and a second, larger one for security measures.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Everyone involved in the series signs a [[non-disclosure agreement]] which prevents them from discussing any revealing information about the outcome of an episode with anyone until it airs on television. After the celebrities have been confirmed to appear on the show, they are allowed to inform a few others who also sign one.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"VAR Dec 18\"/> Before arriving on the show's set, the participants and their family, friends, and agents are disguised and driven from a neutral location.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> The manager of [[Joey Fatone]], the Rabbit in the first season, said he was picked up at a [[7-Eleven]] near Television City, given a disguise, and then driven inside the gate.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> Likewise, [[Adrienne Bailon]], the Flamingo in the second season, said she was taken to the set inside of an unmarked black car and only discussed her involvement on the show with producers in a \"secret warehouse.\"<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/>\n\nThe series' security team is almost as large as the production crew.<ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\"/> The set has different access levels<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> and each participant is escorted by security guards while disguised with a mask, visor, gloves, oversized sweatshirt, and pants to prevent their skin from showing.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\"/> They are not allowed to talk to anyone except those who wear a special \"stealth cloth\" on their backs.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> Twenty-five people knew the actual identities of the contestants during the first season,<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> though they never referred to them as such on set, in emails, or during phone calls regarding the show (a secret code is used instead).<ref name=\"EW Sep 26\"/> The participants' names are not listed anywhere on the set, and the crew is discouraged from using their phones for any reason during filming.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> [[Margaret Cho]], the Poodle in the first season, said she never encountered another participant due to the performers' rehearsals occurring at varying times and locations.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/>\n\n===Costumes===\n[[File:Marina Toybina.png|thumb|upright=0.8|alt=refer to caption|The costumes for the series are designed by Marina Toybina.]]\nPlestis described the series' costumes as \"extremely critical\" to the show, adding \"so much money\" is invested in them.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Villareal|first=Yvonne|title=''The Masked Singer'' costume designer takes us inside TV's most colorful closet|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-masked-singer-fox-costumes-marina-toybina-20190206-story.html|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233157/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-masked-singer-fox-costumes-marina-toybina-20190206-story.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|date=February 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  They are designed by [[Emmy Award]]-winner Marina Toybina who, using a variety of inspirations, develops the concepts herself. She begins by sketching each costume idea with a pencil and then gives the drawings to one of her friends who creates a digital version. After the costume concepts are shared with the show's producers and Fox executives who decide which designs will be featured during a season, Toybina buys all of the necessary fabrics herself and collaborates with a team of twenty to thirty people to custom-make them.<ref name=\"DH Costume\">{{cite web|last=Grobar|first=Matt|title=How ''The Masked Singer'' Costume Designer Marina Toybina Crafted 12 Full-Body Art Pieces In Under Two Months|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina-emmys-fox-interview-1202660891/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913182757/https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina-emmys-fox-interview-1202660891/|archive-date=September 13, 2019|date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nEach costume costs thousands of dollars to make over two months and the masks are designed to prevent echoes.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\"/><ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/> Beginning as a wire mesh; foam is gradually added around the mask, creating an easy-to-wear helmet shape for the performer.<ref name=\"TC Mar 1\">{{cite web|last=Spellings|first=Sarah|title=How Heavy Were Those ''The Masked Singer'' Masks, Anyway?|url=https://www.thecut.com/2019/03/interview-the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#The Cut|The Cut]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233201/https://www.thecut.com/2019/03/interview-the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|date=March 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"AVC\">{{cite web|title=How ''The Masked Singer''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s costume designer dreams up the show's insane outfits|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eShX30efZd8|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=August 29, 2019|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Toybina says she purposely uses foam for the costumes instead of wood or metal as their heavy weight would make the costumes difficult to move around in.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> As \"the draping and the handwork [for the costumes are] all done the old school way,\" she cites fashion designers [[Alexander McQueen]], [[Thierry Mugler]], and [[Hussein Chalayan]] as inspirations<ref name=\"HP Costume\">{{cite web|last=Frank|first=Priscilla|title=The Maniacal Costume Designer Behind ''The Masked Singer'' Speaks|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/costume-designer-masked-singer-marina-toybina_n_5c4f3992e4b0f43e41099257|url-status=live|website=[[HuffPost]]|publisher=[[Verizon Media]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915172544/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/costume-designer-masked-singer-marina-toybina_n_5c4f3992e4b0f43e41099257|archive-date=September 15, 2019|date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"VAR Jan 10\">{{cite web|last=Friedlander|first=Whitney|title=Meet the ''Masked Singer'' Costume Designer Behind Those Elaborate Looks|url=https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/masked-singer-costume-designer-1203103034/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222072254/https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/masked-singer-costume-designer-1203103034/|archive-date=December 22, 2019|date=January 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"VF Costume\">{{cite magazine|last=Bradley|first=Laura|date=January 23, 2019|title=How ''The Masked Singer'' Dreamed Up Those Delightfully Delirious Costumes|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/the-masked-singer-costumes-designer-marina-toybina|url-status=live|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915040813/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/the-masked-singer-costumes-designer-marina-toybina|archive-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> and says the majority of costumes turn out identical to her sketches.<ref name=\"VF Costume\"/> \n\nToybina meets in person with each contestant to choose which costume they want to wear on the show.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/><ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Due to time constraints, a maximum of two fittings are conducted with each celebrity at a \"very, very private hidden-away\" location<ref name=\"VAR Jan 10\"/> (either the costume shop or Toybina's personal studio)<ref name=\"VF Costume\"/> in which the costumes are tested with a vocal coach present to be sure the celebrities can sing and hear clearly.<ref name=\"TVI Sep 24\">{{cite web|last=Halterman|first=Jim|title=''The Masked Singer'' Season 2 Disguises by the Numbers|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/810949/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes-preview/|website=TV Insider|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928183052/https://www.tvinsider.com/810949/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes-preview/|archive-date=September 28, 2019|date=September 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"VUL Sep 25\">{{cite web|last=McHenry|first=Jackson|title=''The Masked Singer''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Costume Designer Breaks Down All 16 Egg-cellent New Looks|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and destination sites|Vulture]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221030001/https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During filming, the participants are assisted by a production crew that helps them take their costumes on and off.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> [[Michelle Williams]], the Butterfly in the second season, said this process was short for her (taking about ten minutes) because the costume she wore was made of only three components.<ref name=\"E! Dec 12\">{{cite web|last=Seemayer|first=Zach|title=Michelle Williams Dishes on Getting Electrocuted on ''The Masked Singer'' Set (Exclusive)|url=https://www.etonline.com/michelle-williams-dishes-on-getting-electrocuted-on-the-masked-singer-set-exclusive-137915|date=December 12, 2019|website=[[E!#E! Online|E!]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408224246/https://www.etonline.com/michelle-williams-dishes-on-getting-electrocuted-on-the-masked-singer-set-exclusive-137915|archive-date=April 8, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Ibarra, the costumes make it difficult for the contestants to get on and off the stage and their vision is limited when performing on it.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> [[Tommy Chong]], the Pineapple in the first season, said he \"had to be led everywhere\" because of his difficulty seeing.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/> As there are no backups, each costume is sanitized and repaired if needed between episodes.<ref name=\"HP Costume\"/><ref name=\"TVI Sep 24\"/>\n\nFor their work on the first season's finale, Toybina and costume supervisor Grainne O'Sullivan received a [[Creative Arts Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming|Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming]].<ref name=\"Emmy 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2019/outstanding-costumes-for-a-variety-program-or-a-special|title=Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming Nominees/Winners 2019|website=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205042123/https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2019/outstanding-costumes-for-a-variety-program-or-a-special|archive-date=December 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the second season, Toybina won a [[Costume Designers Guild#Costume Designers Guild Awards|Costume Designers Guild Award]] in the Excellence in Variety, Reality-Competition, Live Television category in recognition of her work on the final episode.<ref name=\"CAG 2020\">{{cite web|title=22nd Costume Designers Guild Awards Winners & Nominees|url=https://costumedesignersguild.com/awards/awards-2019-2020/|website=[[Costume Designers Guild]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302071147/https://costumedesignersguild.com/awards/awards-2019-2020/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:CBS TelevisionCity02.jpg|thumb|left|alt=refer to caption|The series is filmed at [[Television City]] studios in Los Angeles.]]\nThe series is filmed at [[Television City]] in Los Angeles, California, in a studio that seats 380 people.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Keegan|first=Kayla|title=Going to a ''Masked Singer'' Taping Is Like Visiting a Top-Secret CIA Compound|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|website=[[Good Housekeeping]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405081745/https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|archive-date=April 5, 2020|date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first season was filmed from June 4, 2018, to June 28, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526204614/http://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=May 26, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> the second\u2014which introduced an updated set, including a new digital floor<ref name=\"USA Sep 24\"/>\u2014from July 1, 2019, to August 19, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714070242/http://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=July 14, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the third from December 19, 2019, to February 28, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228120213/https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> Despite the show having a much shorter filming schedule than most television shows,<ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\">{{cite web|last=VanDerWerff|first=Emily Todd|title=''The Masked Singer'' is one of TV's oddest shows. Here's how it was made.|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/2/27/18241269/masked-singer-interview-finale-recap-preview|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402114050/https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/2/27/18241269/masked-singer-interview-finale-recap-preview|archive-date=April 2, 2019|date=February 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> filming dates are occasionally moved to accommodate celebrities' other activities.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Before the performances begin, several vocal coaches work with the performers for multiple days to determine their strengths and improve their technique.<ref name=\"EW Sep 26\">{{cite web|last=Rice|first=Lynette|title=The Ice Cream speaks! Here's how ''The Masked Singer'' recruited the mysterious celebrity|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/26/the-masked-singer-ice-cream-tyler-ninja-blevins/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=September 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211102409/https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/26/the-masked-singer-ice-cream-tyler-ninja-blevins/|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Selecting which songs the celebrities sing is a collaborative process, Ibarra says, with both the performers and producers submitting \"ideas [which] merge as [the songs] go through the [[authorization|clearance]] process.\"<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> [[Ninja (gamer)|Tyler \"Ninja\" Blevins]], the Ice Cream in the second season, said he \"definitely got to pick the songs,\" but that the producers want them to be [[mainstream]] so the show's viewers would connect to them.<ref name=\"EW Sep 26\"/>\n\nAt the start of filming, the studio audience is seated next to the stage and a [[warm-up comedian]] tells jokes to loosen them up. They are then encouraged to scream loudly and chant the names of the costumes enthusiastically while the production crew films their reactions for later use. Shortly thereafter, the panelists arrive and the host introduces the first contestant. A clue package plays on the large screen in the studio, and the panelists may choose to write down observations.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> According to Plestis, the contestants sing live and their voices remain unedited in [[post-production]].<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Thicke noted that guessing is a challenge for the panelists due to sound issues in the studio often obscuring performers' voices and that it takes multiple performances for them to catch on to who the celebrity might be. Plestis said the panelists' guesses are heavily edited due to their extensiveness and that they are forbidden from [[Google (verb)|googling]] possible answers to the clues presented to them between the filming of episodes.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/><ref name=\"ADW Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Jason|title=How ''The Masked Singer'' Became Broadcast's Biggest Midseason Hit|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/how-the-masked-singer-became-broadcasts-biggest-midseason-hit/|website=[[Adweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513171046/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/how-the-masked-singer-became-broadcasts-biggest-midseason-hit/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|date=February 6, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> After the guessing concludes, the panelists and audience vote for their favorite performance using electronic keypads. Their votes are then combined and the contestant with the least amount of votes is eliminated.<ref name=\"GD Apr 5\">{{cite web|last=Dixon|first=Marcus James|title=How to vote for ''The Masked Singer'': Voting process explained (Sorry, there's no app for that)|url=https://www.goldderby.com/feature/the-masked-singer-how-to-vote-voting-app-1203408226/|website=[[Gold Derby]]|archive-url=http://archive.today/tHocx|archive-date=April 17, 2020|date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Before the participant takes off their mask, the producers film the entire studio audience acting out how they would react to the moment, with only a select twenty \"extremely well-vetted\" people remaining in the audience during the actual reveal.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/><ref name=\"THR Jan 2\"/> Before it occurs, the celebrity is allowed to go backstage to fix their hair and makeup.<ref name=\"EW Jan 1\">{{cite web|last=Longo|first=Joseph|title=What we saw at a live taping of Fox's The Masked Singer|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/01/01/what-we-saw-live-taping-masked-singer/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=January 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102113745/https://ew.com/tv/2019/01/01/what-we-saw-live-taping-masked-singer/|archive-date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMultiple air-conditioned rooms are located next to the stage which allow contestants to cool down after performing to prevent them from overheating in their costumes. However, mishaps occasionally occur. Toybina said she had to \"reach for the wire and glue\" after the horn of the Unicorn detached during a performance in the first season.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/> While singing during a rehearsal the following season, Williams said she was almost [[electrocution|electrocuted]] after a [[fog machine|smoke machine]] malfunctioned and split in half the boot she was wearing.<ref name=\"E! Dec 12\"/>\n\n==Series overview==\n{{Main|List of The Masked Singer (American TV series) episodes}}\nThe series is broadcast by Fox in the United States and has been [[simulcast]] by [[CTV Television Network|CTV]] in Canada since the second season. The show is available for streaming in the United States on Fox's website and [[Hulu]], and in Canada on CTV's website.<ref>{{cite press release|title= CTV Unveils 2019/20 Primetime Schedule, Featuring Dynamic Dramas with Big Stars and Big Stories|url=https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|publisher=[[Bell Media]]|date=June 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607044629/https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|archive-date=June 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Watch ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://www.hulu.com/series/the-masked-singer-15209f88-6004-4d73-b993-3ff1a244f494|publisher=[[Hulu]]}}</ref> [[Fox Corporation]] distributes the series in the United States and Canada while Propagate Content does so elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web|last=Otterson|first=Joe|title=Fox Partners With Propagate Content to Distribute Unscripted Programming |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/fox-propagate-content-mipcom-1203372433/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=April 7, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017154840/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/fox-propagate-content-mipcom-1203372433/|archive-date=October 17, 2019|date=October 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Aside from double-length episodes, most run for about 43 minutes and carry a TV-PG or TV-14 [[TV Parental Guidelines|parental rating]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch ''The Masked Singer'': Season 3, Episode 8 \"Old Friends, New Clues: Group C Championships\" Online|url=https://www.fox.com/watch/c2f238d84b5863a804a5455cfc687c05/|website=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Series overview\n| auxA        = Celebrities\n| infoA       = Winner\n| infoB       = Runner-up\n| infoC       = Third place\n\n| color1      = #375D71\n| link1       = The Masked Singer (American season 1)\n| auxA1       = 12\n| episodes1   = 10\n| start1      = {{Start date|2019|1|2}}\n| end1        = {{End date|2019|2|27}}\n| infoA1      = [[T-Pain]]<br /><small>as \"Monster\"</small>\n| infoB1      = [[Donny Osmond]]<br /><small>as \"Peacock\"</small>\n| infoC1      = [[Gladys Knight]]<br /><small>as \"Bee\"</small>\n\n| color2      = #A8957F\n| link2       = The Masked Singer (American season 2)\n| auxA2       = 16\n| episodes2   = 13\n| start2      = {{Start date|2019|9|25}}\n| end2        = {{End date|2019|12|18}}\n| infoA2      = [[Wayne Brady]]<br /><small>as \"Fox\"</small>\n| infoB2      = [[Chris Daughtry]]<br /><small>as \"Rottweiler\"</small>\n| infoC2      = [[Adrienne Bailon]]<br /><small>as \"Flamingo\"</small>\n\n| color3      = #453842\n| link3       = The Masked Singer (American season 3)\n| auxA3       = 18\n| episodes3   = \n| start3      = {{Start date|2020|2|2}}\n| end3        = {{End date|2020|5|20}}<ref name=\"The Futon Critic\"/>\n| infoA3      = \n| infoB3      = \n| infoC3      = \n}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Viewership and ratings===\n<noinclude>\n{{Television season ratings\n| width            = 99\n\n| link1            = The Masked Singer (American season 1)\n| timeslot1        = Wednesday 9:00&nbsp;p.m.\n| episodes1        = 10\n| start1           = {{Start date|2019|1|2}}\n| startrating1     = 9.37<ref>{{cite web|url=https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-on-fox-scores-tvs-highest-rated-unscripted-series-launch-in-seven-years/|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' on Fox Scores TV\u2019s Highest-Rated Unscripted Series Launch in Seven Years|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|date=January 4, 2019|website=Programming Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323022456/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-on-fox-scores-tvs-highest-rated-unscripted-series-launch-in-seven-years/|archive-date=March 23, 2019}}</ref>\n| end1             = {{End date|2019|2|27}}\n| endrating1       = 11.48<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403155952/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-michael-cohen-hearing-draws-significant-audience-figures-in-daytime-across-various-networks/|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: Michael Cohen Hearing Draws Significant Audience Figures in Daytime Across Various Networks|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|date=February 28, 2019|website=Programming Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403155952/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-michael-cohen-hearing-draws-significant-audience-figures-in-daytime-across-various-networks/|archive-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| season1          = 2018\u201319\n| rank1            = 16\n| viewers1         = 8.17\n| 18_49_rating1    = 2.6\n| 18_49_rank1      = 5<ref name=\"S1AvgRatings\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ratings-broadcast-network-series-2018-19-1213344|title=2018-19 TV Season Ratings: 90 Percent of Veteran Broadcast Shows Fall|last=Porter|first=Rick|date=May 23, 2019|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617113702/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ratings-broadcast-network-series-2018-19-1213344|archive-date=June 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n| link2            = The Masked Singer (American season 2)\n| timeslot2        = Wednesday 8:00&nbsp;p.m.\n| timeslot_length2 = 2\n| episodes2        = 13\n| start2           = {{Start date|2019|9|25}}\n| startrating2     = 8.03<ref>{{cite web|url=https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-premiere-helps-fox-to-dominate-prime-time-as-it-doubled-the-runner-up-network-in-adults-18-49/|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' Season Premiere Helps Fox to Dominate Prime Time as it Doubled the Runner-Up Network in Adults 18-49|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|date=September 27, 2019|website=Programming Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005182232/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-premiere-helps-fox-to-dominate-prime-time-as-it-doubled-the-runner-up-network-in-adults-18-49/|archive-date=October 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| end2             = {{End date|2019|12|18}}\n| endrating2       = 8.37<ref>{{cite web|url=https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-over-12-million-watch-impeachment-vote-coverage-across-various-cable-news-stations/|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: Over 12 Million Watch Impeachment Vote Coverage Across Various Cable News Stations|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|date=December 19, 2019|website=Programming Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328034025/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-over-12-million-watch-impeachment-vote-coverage-across-various-cable-news-stations/|archive-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n| season2          = 2019\u201320\n| season_length2   = 2\n| rank2            = \n| rank_length2     = 2\n| viewers2         = \n| viewers_length2  = 2\n| 18_49_rating2    = \n| 18_49_rating_length2 = 2\n| 18_49_rank2      = \n| 18_49_rank_length2 = 2\n\n| link3            = The Masked Singer (American season 3)\n| episodes3        = \n| start3           = {{Start date|2020|2|2}}\n| startrating3     = 23.78<ref>{{cite web|url=https://programminginsider.com/sunday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-third-season-premiere-on-fox-generates-second-largest-total-audience-and-adults-18-49-delivery-for-a-super-bowl-lead-out-in-five-years/|title=Sunday Final Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' Third Season Premiere on Fox Generates Second-Largest Total Audience and Adults 18-49 Delivery for a Super Bowl Lead-Out in Five Years|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|date=February 5, 2020|website=Programming Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211224755/https://programminginsider.com/sunday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-third-season-premiere-on-fox-generates-second-largest-total-audience-and-adults-18-49-delivery-for-a-super-bowl-lead-out-in-five-years/|archive-date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| end3             = {{End date|2020|5|20}}<ref name=\"The Futon Critic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/masked-singer/listings/|title=''The Masked Singer'' Episode Listings|website=[[The Futon Critic]]|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| endrating3       = \n| season3          = hide\n| rank3            = hide\n| viewers3         = hide\n| 18_49_rating3    = hide\n| 18_49_rank3      = hide\n}}\n</noinclude>\n''The Masked Singer'' premiered in January 2019 as the highest rated [[reality television|unscripted]] television series debut since ''[[The X Factor (American TV series)|The X Factor]]'' in 2011. Following three days of DVR viewing, the first episode's 18\u201349 rating grew by 30 percent\u2014the highest increase ever for a premiere in the show's genre.<ref>{{cite web|last=Holloway|first=Daniel|title=''The Masked Singer'' Scores Biggest Live+3 Lift Ever for Unscripted Series|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/masked-singer-ratings-1203101918/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125164644/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/masked-singer-ratings-1203101918/|archive-date=December 22, 2019|date=January 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Although initially dropping, ratings grew towards the end of the season, and the finale became the most watched episode.<ref name=\"ADW Sep 25\">{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Jason|title=How Freshman Hit ''The Masked Singer'' Will Try to Avoid a Sophomore Slump|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/masked-singer-season-2-what-to-expect/|website=[[Adweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926021058/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/masked-singer-season-2-what-to-expect/|archive-date=September 26, 2019|date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> According to [[Comscore]], the show had one of the highest viewer engagement levels of any television series during the week the finale aired.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=TV's Stickiest Shows|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A606540478/GPS|magazine=[[Broadcasting & Cable]]|via=[[Gale (publisher)|Gale In Context: Biography]]|date=March 18, 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref> It concluded the [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319 television season]] as the highest rated new series among adults 18\u201349, averaging a 2.6 rating throughout all ten episodes,<ref name=\"S1AvgRatings\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ratings-broadcast-network-series-2018-19-1213344|title=2018-19 TV Season Ratings: 90 Percent of Veteran Broadcast Shows Fall|last=Porter|first=Rick|date=May 23, 2019|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617113702/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ratings-broadcast-network-series-2018-19-1213344|archive-date=June 17, 2019}}</ref> and as the highest rated entertainment series among teens, men 18\u201334, adults 18\u201334, and adults 18\u201349.<ref name=\"ADW Oct 20\">{{cite web|title=The 2019 TV Hot List: The Year's Biggest and Buzziest Shows, Networks and People|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/the-2019-tv-hot-list-the-years-biggest-and-buzziest-shows-networks-and-people/4/|website=[[Adweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230042701/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/the-2019-tv-hot-list-the-years-biggest-and-buzziest-shows-networks-and-people/4/|archive-date=December 30, 2019|date=October 20, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The show was the first unscripted series to rank number-one in the genre in its first season since ''[[Joe Millionaire]]'' in 2003,<ref name=\"VAR Feb 19\">{{cite news|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=Who Is That Masked B-Lister?|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48002572/the-gazette/|work=[[Montreal Gazette]]|agency=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404200853/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48002572/the-gazette/|archive-date=April 4, 2020|date=February 19, 2019|url-status=live|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> and was one of the reasons why Fox was the only network to gain viewers compared to the previous television season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Levin|first=Gary|title=Fox plots more 'toons, a ''9-1-1'' spinoff, the end of ''Empire'' and plenty of ''Masked Singer''|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/05/13/foxs-fall-schedule-adds-new-toon-wwe-wrestling-and-masked-singer/1184733001/|work=[[USA Today]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513172632/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/05/13/foxs-fall-schedule-adds-new-toon-wwe-wrestling-and-masked-singer/1184733001/|archive-date=April 10, 2020|date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[Ad Age]]'', the series was one of two non-[[National Football League|NFL]] programs to cost at least $200,000 per thirty seconds of advertising during the [[2019\u201320 United States network television schedule|2019\u201320 television season]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Adgate|first=Brad|title=TV Ad Rates (But Not Ad Revenue) Are Dropping|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bradadgate/2019/10/15/tv-ad-rates-but-not-ad-revenue-are-dropping/|website=[[Forbes]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408171217/https://www.forbes.com/sites/bradadgate/2019/10/15/tv-ad-rates-but-not-ad-revenue-are-dropping/|archive-date=April 8, 2020|date=October 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The second season premiered 17 percent lower than the previous, though it was mostly in line with the first season's average.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thorne|first=Will|title=TV Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' Easily Wins Wednesday|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/tv-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-2-premiere-1203350350/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927145835/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/tv-ratings-the-masked-singer-season-2-premiere-1203350350/|archive-date=September 27, 2019|date=September 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The finale's ratings also dropped compared to the first season, although the broadcast was up 20 percent in viewers from the previous week.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Ray|title=''The Masked Singer'' & ''Survivor'' Finales, ''Live In Front Of A Studio Audience'' Ratings Dip Amid Primetime Impeachment Vote|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/the-masked-singer-finale-ratings-survivor-winner-live-in-front-of-a-studio-audience-1202813754/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304071423/https://deadline.com/2019/12/the-masked-singer-finale-ratings-survivor-winner-live-in-front-of-a-studio-audience-1202813754/|archive-date=March 4, 2020|date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Deadline Hollywood]] cited the second season as a major reason why Fox\u2014for the first time in the network's history\u2014ranked number-one in fall entertainment programming,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|title=Fox Tops Fall Demo Ratings For First Time In Decade; NBC Snaps CBS' Total Viewers Streak|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/tv-ratings-fall-2019-fox-wins-nbc-the-masked-singer-sunday-night-football-1202817673/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104191044/https://deadline.com/2019/12/tv-ratings-fall-2019-fox-wins-nbc-the-masked-singer-sunday-night-football-1202817673/|archive-date=January 4, 2020|date=December 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and ''[[Adweek]]'' named the show the \"Hottest Reality/Competition Series\" of 2019.<ref name=\"ADW Oct 20\"/> The third season, which premiered as the [[Super Bowl LIV]] [[list of Super Bowl lead-out programs|lead-out program]], was viewed by over 23.7 million people. While the episode was watched by more than the previous lead-out, ''[[The World's Best]]'' (22.2 million), and Fox's most recent lead-out, 2017's ''[[24: Legacy]]'' (17.6 million), it was lower than the viewership of ''[[This Is Us]]'' (27 million) in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last=Adalian|first=Joseph|title=23 Million People Watched a Celebrity Pretend to Be a Robot on ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/the-masked-singer-super-bowl-ratings.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and destination sites|Vulture]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311162320/https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/the-masked-singer-super-bowl-ratings.html|archive-date=March 11, 2020|date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During the latter half of the season which aired during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the series\u2014like others\u2014experienced viewership and 18\u201349 rating gains of 10\u201315 percent compared to the episodes that aired before the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thorne|first=Will|title=Network TV Sees a Ratings Revival Amid Coronavirus Outbreak, but Will It Last?|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/self-isolation-ratings-network-tv-1203545128/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411070014/https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/self-isolation-ratings-network-tv-1203545128/|archive-date=April 11, 2020|date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Porter|first=Rick|title=TV Long View: The Shows With the Biggest Quarantine Viewing Gains|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/60-minutes-blacklist-lead-quarantine-viewing-gains-1288507|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413011213/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/60-minutes-blacklist-lead-quarantine-viewing-gains-1288507|archive-date=April 13, 2020|date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Excluding the third season's premiere following the Super Bowl, the show's two-hour broadcast on April 1 was the most watched since the first season's finale.<ref name=\"VAR Mar 26\">{{cite web|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=''The Masked Singer'': Gordon Ramsay Is First Confirmed Guest for Fox's ''After The Mask'' Post-Show (Exclusive)|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/the-masked-singer-gordon-ramsay-after-the-mask-1234580325/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415220047/https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/the-masked-singer-gordon-ramsay-after-the-mask-1234580325/|archive-date=April 15, 2020|date=April 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 225\n| total_height = 200\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| image1   = CSIvector.png\n| alt1     = CSI: Crime Scene Investigation\n| image2   = American Idol logo.svg\n| alt2     = American Idol\n| footer   = One commentator compared the series' format to ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]'' while another (contrary to most critics) compared the panelists favorably to the original ''[[American Idol]]'' judges.\n}}\nThe series' concept, panelists, and production have attracted mixed reviews from critics while its costumes have been universally praised.\n\nKelly Lawler of ''[[USA Today]]'' attributed the series' success to its brilliant concept only and named the panel the worst in reality television history. She described Jeong as over-the-top, McCarthy Wahlberg as inexperienced, Scherzinger as dull, and Thicke as too serious.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lawler|first=Kelly|title=The 5 best (and 5 worst) reality-TV show judging panels of all time|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/02/25/reality-tv-judges-5-best-and-5-worst-panels-all-time-the-voice-american-idol-simon-cowell-rupaul/2937947002/|website=[[USA Today]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401114701/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/02/25/reality-tv-judges-5-best-and-5-worst-panels-all-time-the-voice-american-idol-simon-cowell-rupaul/2937947002/|archive-date=April 1, 2020|date=February 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Similarly, ''Variety''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Caroline Framke]] felt the panelists gave worthless insights and that the show was boring due to the caliber of celebrities competing not living up to the hype the show promotes them as when they are unmasked.<ref>{{cite web|last=Framke|first=Caroline|author-link=Caroline Framke|title=TV Review: ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/reviews/the-masked-singer-review-fox-korea-1203096239/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406202742/https://variety.com/2018/tv/reviews/the-masked-singer-review-fox-korea-1203096239/|archive-date=April 6, 2019|date=December 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Kristen Baldwin and Joseph Longo also criticized them. The former felt the show was captivating but said the panelists were unfit to be critiquing singers and that they paid little attention to the clues or performances<ref>{{cite web|last=Baldwin|first=Kristen|title=Fox's ''The Masked Singer'': What the holy hell is this?|url=https://ew.com/tv-reviews/2019/01/02/the-masked-singer-fox-recap/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920204236/https://ew.com/tv-reviews/2019/01/02/the-masked-singer-fox-recap/|archive-date=April 20, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the latter thought that Cannon\u2014despite his experience\u2014was overshadowed by the presence and commentary of McCarthy Wahlberg. While Longo criticized him for not interacting with the panelists, he was pleasantly surprised by the quality of singing and thought the performances were more interesting than listening to the panelists' guesses.<ref name=\"EW Jan 1\"/> [[Matt Zoller Seitz]] of ''Vulture'' lambasted the presence of McCarthy Wahlberg as a panelist (referring to her [[Jenny McCarthy#Autism activism and views on vaccines|prominent]] [[vaccine hesitancy|anti-vaccine]] views) but praised her chemistry with the rest of the panel. He criticized the way the show's producers edit their guesses, stating they should cut out repetitive comments more often.<ref>{{cite web|last=Seitz|first=Matt Zoller|author-link=Matt Zoller Seitz|title=How Is ''The Masked Singer'' Real?|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-review.html|website=Vulture|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218162823/https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-review.html|archive-date=December 18, 2019|date=September 26, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Others from ''Vulture'' also derided the editing as awkward and felt the panelists were mindless and unfunny, condemning them for spoiling the show's innovative concept with distracting statements. However, they were impressed by the costumes, describing the Egg as timeless, the Butterfly as gorgeous, and the Rottweiler as a badass.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wright|first=Megh|title=Egg Was Too Pure for This Terrible World|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/goodbye-egg.html|website=Vulture|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926201418/https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/goodbye-egg.html|archive-date=September 26, 2019|date=September 26, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=VanArendonk|first=Kathryn|title=''The Masked Singer'' Is a Reality-TV Fever Dream|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|website=Vulture|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225230817/https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|archive-date=December 25, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAfter attended a taping of the show, Kayla Keegan of ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'' said she appreciated the detailing of the costumes and praised Toybina's skill in designing them.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' also commended Toybina's costumes; Yvonne Villarreal said they were showstopping and helped make the show successful.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/> Malcolm Venable of ''[[TV Guide]]'' thought the costumes were fantastic but described the performers' singing abilities as lackluster and the panelists' guesses as absurd.<ref>{{cite web|last=Venable|first=Malcolm|title=Is ''The Masked Singer'' Terrible, or Am I Just Old and Cranky?|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/the-masked-singer-review/|website=[[TV Guide]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914015641/https://www.tvguide.com/news/the-masked-singer-review/|archive-date=September 14, 2019|date=December 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Megan Garber of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' compared the series' format to that of [[Police procedural|crime procedural]] ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]'' due to its mystery elements while [[CNN]]'s Brian Lowry felt the show's [[novelty]] would soon fade away because it is gimmicky.<ref name=\"ATL Feb 28\">{{cite web|last=Garber|first=Megan|title=''The Masked Singer'' Lets You In on the Scam|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/02/masked-singer-finale-what-show-really-reveals/583882/|website=[[The Atlantic]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308121421/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/02/masked-singer-finale-what-show-really-reveals/583882/|archive-date=March 8, 2020|date=February 28, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lowry|first=Brian|title=''Titan Games'', ''Masked Singer'' launch hunt for next reality hit|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/31/entertainment/titan-games-masked-singer-reality-tv/index.html|website=[[CNN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111064738/https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/31/entertainment/titan-games-masked-singer-reality-tv/index.html|archive-date=January 11, 2019|date=December 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>. Writing for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', Emily Yahr described the show as crazy but said Cannon was perfect as host, noting his years of experience in the same role on ''[[America's Got Talent]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Yahr|first=Emily|title=Yes, that was real life: ''The Masked Singer'' premiered and was even weirder than you imagined|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|website=Vulture|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225230817/https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/the-masked-singer-fox-review.html|archive-date=December 25, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Conversely, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[John Doyle (critic)|John Doyle]] called Cannon inarticulate and described the panelists as [[Camp (style)|cheesy]] and irrelevant. He characterized the show as a wacky and dumb version of [[Charades]] but acknowledged that it is popular because of its simplicity. Doyle cited the series as an example of a cultural shift in the United States away from the competitive and often exploitative nature of shows such as ''[[American Idol]]'' towards a higher level of positivity among reality television series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Doyle|first=John|author-link=John Doyle (critic)|title=Dumb simplicity: Why ''The Masked Singer'' is a massive TV hit|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/article-dumb-simplicity-why-the-masked-singer-is-a-massive-tv-hit/|website=[[The Globe and Mail]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218163655/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/article-dumb-simplicity-why-the-masked-singer-is-a-massive-tv-hit/|archive-date=December 18, 2019|date=November 4, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Daniel D'Addario of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described the show as relaxing and refreshing, calling it a return to form for television as the series possesses the now-rare ability to uplift and unite people. He commended the show's panelists, comparing them to the original ''American Idol'' judges as non-experts in their fields due to their common, implausible A-list celebrity guesses. He also praised the show's platform for allowing celebrities to express themselves freely even if they are not professional singers.<ref>{{cite web|last=D'Addario|first=Daniel|title=In Praise of ''The Masked Singer'', TV's Last Uniter (Column)|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/columns/masked-singer-super-bowl-1203485315/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210183913/https://variety.com/2020/tv/columns/masked-singer-super-bowl-1203485315/|archive-date=February 10, 2020|date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Cultural impact===\nThe series is discussed on numerous [[podcast|podcasts]] and has generated its own [[Reddit#Subreddit|thread]] on [[Reddit]]<ref name=\"ATL Feb 28\"/> where avid fans of the show extensively analyze the clues presented during an episode in an attempt to decode them.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> They have also replicated many of the series' costumes, including Peacock, Thingamajig, and Ice Cream, to wear on [[Halloween]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Yang|first=Rach|title=Best fan-made ''Masked Singer'' Halloween costumes: Lions, Peacocks, and Thingamajigs, oh my!|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/30/best-fan-made-masked-singer-halloween-costumes/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=October 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218093623/https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/30/best-fan-made-masked-singer-halloween-costumes/|archive-date=December 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The show was the first in the [[Masked Singer|''Masked Singer'' franchise]] to air outside of Asia and its success has been attributed to subsequent local adaptations. The producers of the [[The Masked Singer (British TV series)|British series]] said they were inspired to adapt the format after watching the American version.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/><ref name=\"THR Jan 2\"/> Wade has described a shift in the way new shows are [[sales presentation|pitched]] since the series premiered, noting there is an increased openness to new ideas. He also said the heads of almost all television networks thanked him for the series giving them a \"[[blank cheque|carte blanche]]\" to take new programming risks.<ref name=\"VAR Feb 19\"/> Michael Schneider of ''Variety'' said the show's success has revitalized reality television in the United States. The revivals of ''[[Paradise Hotel]]'' and ''[[Temptation Island (TV series)|Temptation Island]]'' by Fox and [[USA Network]], respectively, have been credited to the show's success, as have the American adaptations of ''[[Love Island (American TV series)|Love Island]]'' and ''[[I Can See Your Voice (American game show)|I Can See Your Voice]]''.<ref name=\"VAR Feb 19\"/> The show has also been credited with reinvigorating the costume genre of television. Interest in adapting other costume-centered series such as ''[[Wild Things (game show)|Wild Things]]'' and ''[[Sexy Beasts]]'' has increased around the world since the show premiered.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\"/>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:11%;\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2%;\"| Year{{efn|Indicates the year of the ceremony.}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%;\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30%;\"| Nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4%;\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2%;\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Costume Designers Guild#Costume Designers Guild Awards|Costume Designers Guild Awards]]\n| [[Costume Designers Guild Awards 2019|2020]]\n| Excellence in Variety, Reality-Competition, Live Television\n| Marina Toybina (for \"Season Finale: And The Winner Takes It All and Takes It Off\")\n| {{won}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"CAG 2020\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Creative Arts Emmy Award|Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n| [[71st Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|2019]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming|Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming]]\n| Marina Toybina, Grainne O'Sullivan (for \"Season Finale: The Final Mask is Lifted\")\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"Emmy 2019\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Critics' Choice Real TV Awards]]\n| [